            =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Ramidanda''' is a former [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Jajarkot District]] in the [[Karnali Pradesh|Karnali province]] of [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[1991 Nepal census]] it had a population of 1699 living in 349 individual households.<ref>{{Citation| url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1|title=Nepal Census 2001|magazine=Nepal's Village Development Committees|publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]]|accessdate=15 November 2009 }}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.un.org.np/maps/district-maps/mid-western/Jajarkot.pdf UN map of the municipalities of Jajarkot District]\n\n{{Jajarkot District}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Jajarkot District]]\n\n\n{{Bheri-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pegship", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2013{{Bheri-geo-stub}}, +{{Karnali-geo-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramidanda"}
{"title_page": "Barrow-in-Furness", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|official_name            = Barrow-in-Furness\n|other_name               =\n|native_name              =\n|nickname                 =\n|static_image_name        = Barrow montage2.jpg\n|static_image_caption     = Clockwise from the upper left: [[Central Barrow]] with the skyline of [[Blackpool]] also visible, [[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]], [[Walney Bridge]] and [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]], [[Furness Abbey]], [[Ramsden Square]], [[Dock Museum]] and [[Devonshire Dock Hall|DDH]],  [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|Barrow Town Hall]] and [[St. Mary of Furness Roman Catholic Church|St. Mary's Church]]\n|static_image_2_name      = Barrow in Furness Town Arms.jpg\n|static_image_2_width     = \n|static_image_2_caption   = [[Coat of arms of Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|coordinates              = {{coord|54.1108|-3.2261|display=inline,title}}\n| population              = 56,745\n| population_ref          = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|population_demonym       = [[Barrovian]]\n|shire_district           = [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|shire_county             = [[Cumbria]]\n|region                   = North West England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]]\n|post_town                = BARROW-IN-FURNESS\n|postcode_district        = LA13, LA14\n|postcode_area            = LA\n|dial_code                = 01229\n|os_grid_reference        = SD198690\n|london_distance          = {{convert|297|mi|km|0|abbr=on}}\n }}\n\n'''Barrow-in-Furness''' is a town in [[Cumbria]], North-West England. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] part of [[Lancashire]], it was incorporated as a [[municipal borough]] in 1867 and merged with [[Dalton-in-Furness Urban District]] in 1974 to form the [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]. At the tip of the [[Furness|Furness peninsula]], close to the [[Lake District]], it is bordered by [[Morecambe Bay]], the [[Duddon Estuary]] and the [[Irish Sea]]. In 2011, Barrow's population was 57,000, making it the second largest urban area in Cumbria after [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], although it is geographically closer to the whole of Lancashire and most of [[Merseyside]]. Natives of Barrow, as well as the local dialect, are known as [[Barrovian]].<ref>{{Cite journal| first=Russell | last=Jenkins | title=Chocolate blog sends town into meltdown | date=22 December 2006 |journal=The Times | pages=15 | postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Middle Ages]], Barrow was a small [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]] within the parish of Dalton-in-Furness with [[Furness Abbey]], now on the outskirts of the modern-day town, controlling the local economy before its [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|dissolution]] in 1537. The iron prospector [[Henry Schneider]] arrived in Furness in 1839 and, with other investors, opened the [[Furness Railway]] in 1846 to transport iron ore and slate from local mines to the coast. Further [[hematite]] deposits were discovered, of sufficient size to develop factories for smelting and exporting steel. For a period of the late 19th century, the [[Barrow Hematite Steel Company]]-owned steelworks was the world's largest.<ref>[http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/ Barrow Steelworks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819160207/http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/ |date=19 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBarrow's location and the availability of steel allowed the town to develop into a significant producer of naval vessels, a shift that was accelerated during [[World War I]] and the local yard's specialisation in submarines. The original iron- and steel-making enterprises closed down after [[World War II]], leaving [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering|Vickers]] shipyard as Barrow's main industry and employer. Several [[Royal Navy]] [[Royal Navy Fleet Flagship|flagships]], the vast majority of its [[Nuclear submarine#Royal Navy of the United Kingdom|nuclear submarines]] as well as numerous other naval vessels, [[ocean liner]]s and [[oil tanker]]s have been manufactured at the facility.\n\nThe end of the [[Cold War]] and subsequent [[peace dividend|decrease in military spending]] saw high unemployment in the town through lack of contracts; despite this, the [[BAE Systems]] shipyard remains operational as the UK's largest by workforce and is undergoing a major expansion associated with the {{sclass-|Dreadnought|submarine|0}} submarine programme.<ref name=\"unemployment\" /> Today Barrow is a hub for energy generation and handling. Offshore wind farms form one of the highest concentrations of turbines in the world, including [[Walney Wind Farm|the single largest]] with multiple operating bases in Barrow.<ref name=\"walneyextension\">[\u00a31bn Walney offshore wind farm is world's largest https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-45424559 \u00a31 billion Walney offshore wind farm is world's largest] ''BBC News'', 6 September 2018. Accessed: 6 September 2018.</ref>\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe name was originally that of an island, Barrai, which can be traced back to 1190. This was later renamed Old Barrow, recorded as Oldebarrey in 1537, and Old Barrow Insula and Barrohead in 1577. The island was then joined to the mainland and the town took its name. The name itself seems to mean \"island with promontory\", combining British ''barro-'' and Old Norse ''ey'', but it is more likely that [[Scandinavia]]n settlers simply accepted ''barro-'' as a meaningless name, and so added an explanatory [[Old Norse]] second element.<ref>{{Cite book|last= Mills|first= David|title= The Place Names of Lancashire|year= 1976|publisher= Batsford Books|location= London|isbn= 978-0-7134-3248-0}}</ref>\n\n===Nicknames===\nIn the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Barrow was nicknamed \"the English Chicago\" because of the sudden and rapid growth in its industry, economic stature and overall size.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdonline.co.uk/buildings/barrow-in-furness-kept-on-life-support-by-perpetual-warfare/5011365.article|title=Barrow-in-Furness: kept on life support by perpetual warfare|publisher=}}</ref> More recently the town has been dubbed the \"capital of [[Blue-collar worker|blue-collar]] Britain\" by the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', reflecting its strong working class identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?rlz=1T4ACAW_en___GB384&q=most+working+class+town|title=most working class town \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.com}}</ref> Barrow is also often jokingly referred to as being at the end of the longest [[cul-de-sac]] in the country because of its isolated location at the tip of the Furness peninsula.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-18853714|title=Five lesser-spotted things in the census|first=Lucy Townsend and Kathryn|last=Westcott|date=17 July 2012|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Timeline of Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n===Early history===\nBarrow and the surrounding area has been settled non-continuously for several millennia with evidence of [[Neolithic]] inhabitants on [[Walney Island]]. Despite a rich history of [[Roman Britain|Roman]] settlement across Cumbria and the discovery of related artefacts in the Barrow area, no buildings or structures have been found to support the idea of a functioning Roman community on the [[Furness]] peninsula.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roman Treasure|url=http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/Romans|publisher=Dock Museum|accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref> The [[Furness Hoard]] discovery of [[Viking]] silver coins and other artefacts in 2011 provided significant archaeological evidence of [[Norse activity in the British Isles|Norse]] settlement in the early 9th century. Several areas of Barrow including [[Yarlside]] and [[Ormsgill]], as well as \"Barrow\" and \"Furness\", have names of [[Old Norse]] origin. The [[Domesday Book]] of 1086 recorded the settlements of Hietun, Rosse and Hougenai, which are now the districts of [[Hawcoat]], [[Roose]] and [[Walney Island|Walney]] respectively.\n[[File:Furness Abbey, April 2010.jpg|thumb|right|[[Furness Abbey]], one of England's most powerful monasteries in the Middle Ages]]\n\nIn the [[Middle Ages]] the Furness peninsula was controlled by the [[Cistercian]] monks of the Abbey of St Mary of Furness, known as [[Furness Abbey]]. This was located in the \"Vale of Nightshade\", now on the outskirts of the town.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=150#abbey | title=Local history and heritage | publisher=Barrow Borough Council | accessdate=10 June 2007 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609195921/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=150#abbey | archivedate=9 June 2007 |url-status = dead| df=dmy-all }}</ref> Founded for the [[Congregation of Savigny|Savigniac order]], it was built on the orders of [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] in 1123. Soon after the abbey's foundation the monks discovered iron ore deposits, later to provide the basis for the Furness economy. These thin strata, close to the surface, were extracted through open cut workings,<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.cumbria-industries.org.uk/ironmining.htm | title=Iron Mining | publisher=Industries of Cumbria | accessdate=10 June 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070702101913/http://www.cumbria-industries.org.uk/ironmining.htm| archivedate= 2 July 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> which were then smelted by the monks.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Raymond|first1=Michael|title=A Forgotten Medieval Powerhouse: Furness Abbey|url=http://newhistories.group.shef.ac.uk/wordpress/wordpress/a-forgotten-medieval-powerhouse-furness-abbey/|publisher=New Histories Magazine|accessdate=3 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425033830/http://newhistories.group.shef.ac.uk/wordpress/wordpress/a-forgotten-medieval-powerhouse-furness-abbey/|archive-date=25 April 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref> The proceeds from mining, along with agriculture and fisheries, meant that by the 15th century the abbey had become the second richest and most powerful Cistercian abbey in England, after [[Fountains Abbey]] in Yorkshire.<ref>{{Cite web| author=English Heritage | title=Furness Abbey| publisher=English Heritage | url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/ConProperty.149 | accessdate=6 May 2007 }}</ref> The monks of Furness Abbey constructed a wooden tower on nearby [[Piel Island]] in 1212 which acted as their main trading point; it was twice invaded by the Scots, in 1316 and 1322. In 1327 [[Edward III of England|King Edward III]] gave Furness Abbey a licence to [[crenellate]] the tower, and a [[motte-and-bailey castle]] was built. However Barrow itself was just a hamlet in the parish of [[Dalton-in-Furness]], reliant on the land and sea for survival. Small quantities of iron and ore were exported from jetties on the channel separating the village from Walney Island. Amongst the oldest buildings in Barrow are several cottages and farmhouses in [[Newbarns]] (now a ward of the borough) which date back to the early 17th century; as well as [[Rampside Hall]], a [[Grade I listed]] building and the best-preserved in the town from the 1600s. Even as late as 1843 there were still only 32 dwellings, including two pubs.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/pdf/summary%20of%20plan%20areas.pdf | title=Plan of Barrow 1843 | publisher=Barrow Borough Council | format=[[PDF]] | accessdate=10 June 2007 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704111547/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/pdf/summary%20of%20plan%20areas.pdf | archivedate=4 July 2007 |url-status = dead| df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:Barrow Steelworks.jpg|thumb|left|[[Barrow Hematite Steel Company|Barrow Steelworks]] circa. 1877]]\nIn 1839 [[Henry Schneider]] arrived as a young speculator and dealer in iron, and he discovered large deposits of [[haematite]] in 1850. He and other investors founded the [[Furness Railway]], the first section of which opened in 1846, to transport the ore from the slate quarries at [[Kirkby-in-Furness]] and haematite mines at [[Lindal-in-Furness]] and [[Askam and Ireleth]] to a deep-water harbour near [[Roa Island]].<ref name=\"railway\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.furnessrailwaytrust.org.uk/frco.htm |title=History of the Furness Railway Company |publisher=The Furness Railway Trust |accessdate=8 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715153252/http://www.furnessrailwaytrust.org.uk/frco.htm |archivedate=15 July 2007 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> The crucial and difficult link across [[Morecambe Bay]] between [[Ulverston]] and [[Carnforth]] on the main line was promoted, as the [[Ulverston and Lancaster Railway]], by a group led by [[John Brogden (industrialist)|John Brogden]] and opened in 1857. It was promptly purchased by the Furness Railway.<ref>\n{{cite book  | first = J.D. | last = Marshall | title = Furness and the Industrial Revolution | publisher = Michael Moon, Beckermet, Cumbria | pages = 215\u20138 | origyear = 1958 |year=1981 | isbn = 978-0-904131-26-0 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book  | first = Joseph | last = Richardson | title = Furness Past and Present | pages = 18\u201324 | volume = 1 of 2 | year = 1870 }}</ref>\n\nThe docks built between 1863 and 1881 in the more sheltered channel between the mainland and [[Barrow Island (England)|Barrow Island]] replaced the port at Roa Island. The first dock to open was [[Devonshire Dock]] in 1867, and Prime Minister [[William Ewart Gladstone]] stated his belief that \"Barrow would become another Liverpool\". The increasing quantities of iron ore mined in Furness were then brought into the centre of Barrow to be transported by sea.\n\n[[File:Barrow Jute Works 1875.jpg|thumb|Painting of the [[Barrow Jute Works]] in 1875]]\nThe investors in the burgeoning mining and railway industries decided that greater profits could be made by smelting the iron ore and converting the resultant pig-iron into steel, and then exporting the finished product. Schneider and [[Sir James Ramsden|James Ramsden]], the railway's general manager, erected [[blast furnace]]s at Barrow that by 1876 formed the largest steelworks in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/|title= Barrow|accessdate= 25 August 2007|publisher= [[Ironbridge Gorge]] Museum Trust|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070819160207/http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/|archivedate= 19 August 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Its success was a result of the availability of local iron ore and coal from the [[Cumberland]] mines and easy rail and sea transport. The Furness Railway, which counted local aristocrats [[William Cavendish, 7th Duke of Devonshire]] and the [[Duke of Buccleuch]] as investors, kick-started the [[Industrial Revolution]] on the peninsula. The railway brought mined ore to the town, where the steelworks produced large quantities of steel. It was used for shipbuilding, and derived products such as rails were also exported from the newly-built docks.<ref name=\"railway\"/>\n\nBarrow's population grew rapidly. Population figures for the town itself were not collected until 1871,<ref name=\"THB\">{{cite journal|last1=Bainbridge|first1=TH|title=Barrow in Furness: A Population Study|journal=Economic Geography|volume=15|issue=4|pages=379\u2013383|jstor=141773|year=1939|doi=10.2307/141773}}</ref> though sources suggest that Barrow's population was still as low as 700 in 1851.<ref>{{cite web|title=Timeline History of Barrow-in-Furness|url=http://www.visitoruk.com/Barrow-in-furness/19th-century-T454.html|publisher=VisitorUK|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> During the first half of the 19th century, Barrow formed part of the parish of [[Dalton-in-Furness]], the population of which shows some of Barrow's early growth from the 1850s:\n\n'''Population of the Parish of Dalton-in-Furness'''<ref name=\"THB\" /><br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year||1801||1811||1821||1831||1841||1851||1861\n|-\n|Population||1,954||2,074||2,446||2,697||3,231||4,683||9,152\n|}\n\nIn 1871 Barrow's population was recorded at 18,584 and in 1881 at 47,259, less than forty years after the railway was built.<ref name=\"THB\" /> The majority of migrants originated from elsewhere in Lancashire although significant numbers settled in Barrow from [[Ireland]] and [[Scotland]], which represented 11% and 7% of the local population in the 1890s.<ref name=Irish>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/cultureconflictm00macr_0|url-access=registration|title=Culture, Conflict, and Migration: The Irish in Victorian Cumbria|publisher=Liverpool University Press|accessdate=6 April 2015|isbn=9780853236528|year=1998}}</ref><ref name=IrishScot>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jI6lBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Scots in Victorian and Edwardian Belfast: A Study in Elite Migration|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=1 April 2015|isbn=9780748679928|year=2013}}</ref> By the turn of the 20th century, the Scottish-born population had increased to form the highest portion anywhere in England. In an attempt to diversify Barrow's economy James Ramsden founded the Barrow and Calcutta Jute Company in 1870 and the [[Barrow Jute Works]] was soon constructed alongside the Furness Railway line in [[Hindpool]]. The mill employed 2,000 women at its peak and was awarded a gold medal for its produce at the 1878 Paris [[Exposition Universelle (1878)|Exposition Universelle]].<ref name=Grace>{{cite web|url=http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Barrow_Flax_and_Jute_Co|title=Barrow Flax and Jute Co|publisher=Grace's Guide|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barrow Works 1890.jpg|thumb|left|Barrow's shipyard circa. 1890]]\nThe sheltered strait between Barrow and Walney Island was an ideal location for the shipyard. The first ship to be built, the ''Jane Roper'', was launched in 1852; the first steamship, a 3,000-ton liner named ''Duke of Devonshire'', in 1873. Shipbuilding activity increased, and on 18 February 1871 the Barrow Shipbuilding Company was incorporated. Barrow's relative isolation from the United Kingdom's industrial heartlands meant that the newly formed company included several capabilities that would usually be subcontracted to other establishments. In particular, a large engineering works was constructed including a foundry and pattern shop, a forge, and an engine shop. In addition, the shipyard had a joiners' shop, a boat-building shed and a sailmaking and rigging loft.<ref name=\"barrow-works\">{{Cite book| last = The Naval and Armaments Company Limited | title = The Works at Barrow-in-Furness of The Naval Construction and Armaments Company Limited \u2013 Historical and Descriptive | publisher = The Naval and Armaments Company Limited, partly reprinted from 'Engineering' magazine | year = 1896 | location = Barrow-in-Furness | page = 54 }}</ref>\n\nDuring these boom years, Ramsden proposed building a [[town planning|planned town]] to accommodate the large workforce which had arrived. There are few planned towns in the United Kingdom, and Barrow is one of the oldest. Its centre contains a grid of well-built terraced houses, with a tree-lined road leading away from a central square. Ramsden later became the first mayor of Barrow,<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Mayors|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/council-democracy/mayor/former-mayors/|publisher=Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|accessdate=3 August 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923182432/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/council-democracy/mayor/former-mayors/|archivedate=23 September 2015}}</ref> which was given [[municipal borough]] status in 1867, and county borough status in 1889.<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www.dalton-in-furness.org.uk/dalton-online/history/modern-town/modern-town-localgov.html| title= History of Dalton-in-Furness| accessdate= 6 July 2007| work= Dalton Online| publisher= Dalton Community Association| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070810055439/http://www.dalton-in-furness.org.uk/dalton-online/history/modern-town/modern-town-localgov.html| archivedate= 10 August 2007|url-status = dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> The imposing red sandstone [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|town hall]], designed by W.H. Lynn, was built in a neo-gothic style in 1887.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=150 | title = Local History and Heritage | publisher = Barrow Borough Council | accessdate = 8 July 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070609195921/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=150 | archivedate = 9 June 2007 |url-status = dead| df = dmy-all }}</ref> Prior to this, the borough council had met at the railway headquarters: the railway company's control of industry extended to the administration of the town itself.\n\n[[File:Ancient roam (1).jpg|thumb|Map of Barrow dated 1890 showing no development on Walney Island and little north of the [[Furness Line]]]]\nThe Barrow Shipbuilding Company was taken over by the [[Sheffield]] steel firm of [[Vickers]] in 1897, by which time the shipyard had surpassed the railway and steelworks as the largest employer and landowner in Barrow. The company constructed [[Vickerstown]], modelled on [[George Cadbury]]'s [[Bournville]], on the adjacent Walney Island in the early 20th century to house its employees.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Frank |last=Partridge |title=The Complete Guide to: England's Islands |date=16 March 2006 |publisher=Independent News & Media |url=http://travel.independent.co.uk/uk/article351869.ece |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=10 August 2007 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927211406/http://travel.independent.co.uk/uk/article351869.ece |archivedate=27 September 2007  }}</ref> It also commissioned [[Sir Edwin Lutyens]] to design [[Abbey House, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey House]] as a guest house and residence for its managing director, Commander Craven.<ref>{{cite web|title=Homepage|url=http://www.abbeyhousehotel.com/|publisher=Abbey House Hotel|accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:Abbey House Hotel south elevation.JPG|thumb|left|[[Abbey House, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey House]] was commissioned by Vickers and designed by Sir [[Edwin Lutyens]]]]\n[[File:Cornmillcrossing.jpg|thumb|left|Cornmill Crossing in 1895 (a former goods-depot on the [[Furness Railway]]), a [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Cornmill Crossing|retail park]] now exists on the site]]\nBy the 1890s the shipyard was heavily engaged in the construction of warships for the Royal Navy and also for export. The Royal Navy's first submarine, ''[[Holland 1]]'', was built in 1901,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.submarineheritage.com/history.html |title=Submarine History of Barrow-in-Furness |publisher=Submarine Heritage Centre |accessdate=20 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704042341/http://www.submarineheritage.com/history.html |archivedate=4 July 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> and by 1914 the UK had the most advanced submarine fleet in the world, with 94% of it constructed by Vickers. Vickers was also famous for the construction of [[airship]]s and [[airship hangar]]s during the early 20th century. Originally constructed in a large shed at Cavendish Dock, production later relocated to [[Barrow/Walney Island Airport]]. [[HMA No. 1]], nicknamed the Mayfly is the most notable airship to have been built in Barrow. The first of its kind in the UK it came to an untimely end on 24 September 1911 when it was wrecked by wind during trials. Well-known ships built in Barrow include {{ship|Japanese battleship|Mikasa||2}}, the Japanese flagship during the 1905 [[Russo-Japanese War]], the liner {{SS|Oriana|1959|6}} and the aircraft carriers {{HMS|Invincible|R05|6}} and {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}}. It should also be noted that there was a significant presence of Vickers' armament division in Barrow with the huge [[VSEL Heavy Engineering Workshop|Heavy Engineering Workshop]] on Michaelson Road supplying ammunition for the [[British Army]] and [[Royal Navy]] throughout both world wars. World War 1 brought significant temporary migration as workers arrived to work in the munitions factory and shipyard, with the town's population reaching to an estimated peak of around 82,000 during the War.<ref name=\"THB\" /> Thousands of local men fought abroad during World War I, 616 were ultimately killed in action.<ref name=\"ukniwm.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukniwm.org.uk/server/show/conMemorial.2079/fromUkniwmSearch/1|title=Barrow In Furness Cenotaph|first=Imperial War|last=Museums|website=Imperial War Museums}}</ref>\n\nDuring World War II, Barrow was a target for the [[Luftwaffe|German air force]] looking to disable the town's shipbuilding capabilities (see [[Barrow Blitz]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/bob1940/september2.html |title=The Battle of Britain \u2013 Diary \u2013 2 September 1940 |accessdate=5 August 2007 |date=16 February 2005 |publisher=RAF |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815202245/http://www.raf.mod.uk/bob1940/september2.html |archivedate=15 August 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> The town suffered the most in a short period between April and May 1941. During the war, a local housewife, [[Nella Last]], was selected to write a diary of her experiences on the home front for the [[Mass-Observation]] project. Her memoirs were later adapted for television as ''[[Housewife, 49]]'' starring [[Victoria Wood]]. The difficulty in targeting bombs meant that the shipyards and steelworks were often missed, at the expense of the residential areas. Ultimately, 83 people were killed and 11,000 houses in the area were left damaged. To escape the heaviest bombardments, many people in the central areas left the town to sleep in hedgerows, with some being permanently evacuated. Barrow's industry continued to supply the war effort, with [[Winston Churchill]] visiting the town on one occasion to launch the [[aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Indomitable|R92|6}}.<ref name=\"dock\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/docs/Publication%20world%20war%20II-web.pdf|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070813205557/http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/docs/Publication%20world%20war%20II-web.pdf|url-status = dead|archive-date= 13 August 2007|title= World War II|accessdate=25 August 2007|date=16 February 2005 |publisher= [[Dock Museum]]}}</ref> Besides the dozens of civilians killed during World War II, some 268 Barrovian men were also killed whilst in combat.<ref name=\"ukniwm.org.uk\"/>\n\n[[File:Yokosuka-mikasa-08-2010.png|thumb|right|Barrow-built {{ship|Japanese battleship|Mikasa||2}} was the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]]'s flagship during the [[Russo-Japanese War]]]]\n\nBarrow's population reached a second peak in of 77,900 in 1951;<ref>{{cite book|last1=Freeman|first1=TW|title=The Conurbations of Great Britain|date=1966|publisher=The University Press|location=Manchester|page=239|edition=Second}}</ref> however, by this point the long decline of mining and steel-making as a result of overseas competition and dwindling resources had already begun.  The Barrow ironworks closed in 1963,<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.nwda.co.uk/docs/Project_Corus_July05.doc|title= Project Corus (Workington) Steering Group Report|accessdate= 31 August 2007|date= 1 June 2005|format= [[DOC (computing)|DOC]]|publisher= Northwest Development Agency|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928094413/http://www.nwda.co.uk/docs/Project_Corus_July05.doc|archivedate= 28 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> three years after the last Furness mine shut. The by then small steelworks followed suit in 1983,<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.banklands.com/Barrow%20Steel.htm | title=Barrow Steel | accessdate =21 July 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070702005911/http://www.banklands.com/Barrow%20Steel.htm| archivedate= 2 July 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> leaving Barrow's shipyard as the town's principal industry. From the 1960s onwards it concentrated its efforts in submarine manufacture, and the UK's first nuclear-powered submarine, {{HMS|Dreadnought|S101|6}}, was constructed in 1960. {{HMS|Resolution|S22|6}}, the {{sclass-|Swiftsure|submarine|5}}, {{sclass-|Trafalgar|submarine|5}} and {{sclass-|Vanguard|submarine|2}}<nowiki/>s all followed. The last of these are armed with [[Trident missile|Trident II]] [[Submarine-launched ballistic missile|missiles]] as part of the British government's [[Trident nuclear programme]].\n\nThe end of the Cold War in 1991 marked a reduction in the demand for military ships and submarines, and the town continued its decline. The shipyard's dependency on military contracts at the expense of civilian and commercial engineering and shipbuilding meant it was particularly hard hit as government defence spending was reduced dramatically.<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1080/00076790412331270099|author=Maggie Mort |author2=Graham Spinardi |year=2004 |title=Defence and the decline of UK mechanical engineering \u2013 the case of Vickers at Barrow |journal=Business History |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201322 |url=}}</ref> As a result, the workforce shrank from 14,500 in 1990 to 5,800 in February 1995,<ref>{{Cite journal|publisher=[[Competition Commission]] |title=Views of main parties as part of report into British Aerospace PLC proposed merger with VSEL |date=23 May 1995 |url=http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365c5.pdf |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520023806/http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365c5.pdf |archivedate=20 May 2011  }}</ref> with overall unemployment in the town rising over that period from 4.6% to 10%.<ref name=\"unemployment\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365a4.8.pdf|title= Appendix on unemployment as part of report into British Aerospace PLC proposed merger with VSEL|accessdate= 31 August 2007|date= 23 May 1995|publisher= [[Competition Commission]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928011251/http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365a4.8.pdf|archivedate= 28 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The rejection by the [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering|VSEL]] management of detailed plans for Barrow's industrial renewal in the mid-to-late 1980s remains controversial.<ref>{{Cite book|last= Mort|first= Maggie|title= Building the Trident Network|year= 2002|publisher= [[MIT Press]]|isbn= 978-0-262-13397-5}}</ref> This has led to renewed academic attention in recent years to the possibilities of converting military-industrial production in declining shipbuilding areas to the offshore renewable energy sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.basicint.org/nuclear/beyondtrident/oceans.pdf|title= Oceans of Work: Arms Conversion Revisited|accessdate=25 August 2007 |last= Schofield|first= Steven|date=January 2007|publisher= [[British American Security Information Council]]|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070710111238/http://www.basicint.org/nuclear/beyondtrident/oceans.pdf |archivedate = 10 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Albion and Bulwark, Barrow 2002.jpg|thumb|left|{{HMS|Albion|L14|6}} and {{HMS|Bulwark|L15|6}} undergoing fitting out in 2002 at BAE Systems Marine in Barrow]]\nIn a 2002 [[2002 Barrow-in-Furness legionellosis outbreak|outbreak of legionellosis]] in the town, 172 people were reported to have caught the disease, of whom seven died. This made it the fourth worst outbreak in the world in terms of number of cases and sixth worst in terms of deaths. The source of the bacteria was later found to be steam from a badly maintained air conditioning unit in the council-run arts centre [[The Forum Barrow|Forum 28]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Legionnaires' source officially traced |work=BBC News | date = 20 August 2002 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2205186.stm | accessdate=21 July 2003 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20030814170447/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2205186.stm| archivedate= 14 August 2003 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAt the conclusion of the inquest into the seven deaths, the coroner for Furness and South Cumbria criticised the council for its health and safety failings.<ref>{{Cite news| title = A Total Shambles|publisher = [[North West Evening Mail]]| date = 12 June 2007 | url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508368 | accessdate =21 July 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070623083652/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508368| archivedate = 23 June 2007}}</ref> In 2006, council employee Gillian Beckingham and employer [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow Borough Council]] were cleared of seven charges of [[manslaughter]]. Beckingham, the council senior architect was fined \u00a315,000 and the authority \u00a3125,000. Following the trials the contractor responsible for maintaining the plant settled a \u00a31.5 million claim by the council for damages.<ref>{{cite news| title = Bug Death Council Worker Cleared |work=BBC News | date = 31 July 2006 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/5232086.stm | accessdate=21 July 2007 }}</ref> The borough council was the first public body in the country to face corporate manslaughter charges.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.cipfa.org.uk/publicfinance/features_details.cfm?News_id=24043 | title =Back in the Line of Fire | publisher = publicfinance.co.uk | accessdate =21 July 2007| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071006125830/http://www.cipfa.org.uk/publicfinance/features_details.cfm?News_id=24043| archivedate = 6 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n2006 saw the construction of [[Barrow Offshore Wind Farm]], which has acted as a catalyst for further investment in offshore [[renewable energy]]. [[Ormonde Wind Farm]] and [[Walney Wind Farm]] followed in 2011, the latter of which became the largest offshore wind farm in the world. The three wind farms are located west of Walney Island and are operated primarily by [[DONG Energy]], contain a total of 162 [[Wind turbine|turbines]] and have a combined [[Intermittent energy source#Terminology|nameplate capacity]] of 607&nbsp;MW, providing energy for well over half a million homes. [[West of Duddon Sands Wind Farm]] was commissioned in 2014 while Walney was extended in 2018 to again become the world's largest such offshore facility.\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Barrow town hall, April 2011.jpg|thumb|right|Barrow's Grade II* listed [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|town hall]] viewed from [[Schneider Square]]]]\n\nBarrow is the largest town in the [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/view.asp?ID=6027  | title = Cumbria's Population in Urban Areas 2003 | publisher = Cumbria County Council | format=[[Microsoft Excel|XLS]] | accessdate =11 December 2006}}</ref> and the largest settlement in the peninsula of [[Furness]]. The borough is the direct inheritor of the municipal and county borough charters given to the town in the late 19th century.<ref name=\"mayorlist\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2490 |title=Barrow Borough Council \u2013 Former Mayors |accessdate=18 August 2007 |publisher=[[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow Borough Council]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030726/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2490 |archivedate=28 September 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> Historically it is part of the [[Lonsdale (hundred)|Hundred of Lonsdale]] 'north of the sands' in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county boundaries]] of [[Lancashire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043|title= Lancashire AncC: Historical Boundaries|accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher= A Vision of Britain Through Time| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001412/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043| archivedate = 1 October 2007}}</ref> Since the local government reforms enacted in England in 1974 the town has been within the administrative county of [[Cumbria]]. It still forms a part of the [[Duchy of Lancaster]]. The [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow-in-Furness Borough Council]] forms the 'lower' tier of local government under [[Cumbria|Cumbria County Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Draft Statutory Instrument 2004 The Regional Assembly and Local Government Referendums (Date of Referendums, Referendum Question and Explanatory Material) (North West Region) Order 2004 | work=Office of Public Sector Information | url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/SI/si2004/draft/20049539.htm | accessdate =18 August 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071001000704/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/SI/si2004/draft/20049539.htm| archivedate= 1 October 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> Since the [[2011 Barrow-in-Furness Council election|2011 local election]], the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] has had overall control of the Borough council, while the Borough elected 10 Labour and one Conservative Party councillor at the [[2013 Cumbria County Council election|2013 Cumbria County election]]. The town, along with [[Walney Island]], is unparished and forms the bulk of the wards which make the entire borough's area. The Mayor and Deputy Mayor of Barrow are elected annually, and hold the roles of chairman and Vice-Chairman of Barrow-in-Furness Borough Council.<ref name=\"mayorrole\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/about-the-council/barrow-council/mayor/former-mayors/ |title=Barrow Borough Council \u2013 Mayor's Role |accessdate=4 March 2017 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council }}</ref> The borough and former county borough of Barrow-in-Furness have been served by 107 mayors, beginning with [[Sir James Ramsden]] in 1867 and continuing through to incumbent 2015/16 mayor Ann Thomson.<ref name=\"mayorrole\"/>\n\nThe Barrow-in-Furness [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|UK Parliament constituency]] first came into existence during the [[1885 United Kingdom general election]], with [[David Duncan (UK politician)|David Duncan]] of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] becoming the first [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for the town. The seat was won by the Conservative Party in [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]], before being won for the first time by Labour in [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]. In the subsequent 40 years the seat swung between Conservative and Labour, but since 1945 it has been generally considered a Labour safe seat.<ref name=\"Polling Report\">{{cite web|title=Barrow & Furness|url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/2015guide/barrowandfurness/|publisher=UK Polling Report|accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref> In 1983, the constituency was expanded to include several commuter towns such as Dalton-in-Furness and Ulverston and was renamed [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]]. It was subsequently won by the Conservatives, with the victory attributed to Labour's stance against the nuclear-powered submarines that were being constructed in Barrow.<ref name=\"Polling Report\" /> Following a change in Labour policy the party won Barrow and Furness in 1992. [[John Woodcock (UK politician)|John Woodcock]] has been the MP for the constituency since the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], but is to stand down for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], after resigning from the Labour party amid allegations of sexual harassment made against him.\n\n<br />\n{| style=\"margin:0 auto;\" class=\"toccolours\"\n|align=center| '''Council/ Electoral wards of Barrow-in-Furness'''\n|-\n|align=center|\n[[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]] | [[Central Barrow|Central]] | [[Hawcoat]] |  [[Hindpool]] | [[Newbarns]] | [[Ormsgill]] | [[Parkside, Barrow-in-Furness|Parkside]] | [[Risedale]] | [[Roose]]cote | [[Walney North]] | [[Walney South]]\n|}\n\n==Geography==\nBarrow is situated at the tip of the [[Furness]] peninsula on the north-western edge of [[Morecambe Bay]], south of the [[Duddon Estuary]] and east of the [[Irish Sea]]. [[Walney Island]], to the west of Barrow, surrounds the peninsula's Irish Sea coast and is separated from Barrow by the narrow [[Walney Channel]]. Both Morecambe Bay and the Duddon Estuary are characterized by large areas of [[quicksand]] and fast-moving [[tidal bore]]s. Areas of [[sand dunes]] exist on coasts surrounding Barrow, particularly at [[Roanhead]] and [[North Walney]]. The town centre and major industrial areas sit on a fairly flat coastal shelf, with hillier ground rising to the east of the town, peaking at {{convert|94|m|ft|round=5}} at Yarlside. Barrow sits on soils deposited during the end of the [[Last glacial period|Ice Age]], eroded from the mountains of the [[Lake District National Park]], {{convert|10|mi|km|round=5}} to the north-east. Barrow's soils are composed of glacial lake clay and [[glacial till]], while Walney is almost entirely made up of reworked glacial morraine.<ref>{{cite web|last1=May|first1=VJ|title=Walney Island|url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/pdf/gcrdb/GCRsiteaccount2042.pdf|publisher=DEFRA|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ICE\">{{cite journal|last1=Raison|first1=CA|title=North Morecambe Terminal, Barrow: pile design for seismic conditions|journal=Proceedings of the ICE \u2013 Geotechnical Engineering|date=1999|volume=137|issue=3|page=149\u00b1163|url=http://www.raisonfosterassociates.co.uk/downloads/barrow-piling.pdf|accessdate=16 July 2015|doi=10.1680/gt.1999.370304}}</ref> Beneath these soils is a [[sandstone]] bedrock, from which many of the town's older buildings are constructed.<ref name=\"ICE\" />\n\nBarrow town centre is located to the north-east of the docks, with suburbs also extending to the north and east, as well as onto Walney. The towns of [[Dalton-in-Furness]] and [[Askam-in-Furness]] are the other sizable settlements of the [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]. Barrow is the only major urban area in South Cumbria, with the nearest settlements of a similar size being [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] and [[Morecambe]]. Other towns nearby include [[Ulverston]], [[Millom]], [[Grange-over-Sands]], [[Kendal]] and [[Windermere, Cumbria (town)|Windermere]].\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"220px\">\nFile:Barrow-in-Furness Map.png|Map of Barrow\nFile:Barrow-in-Furness aerial from the south.jpg|Aerial view of Barrow and Walney Island\nFile:Ordnance Survey 1-250000 - SD.jpg|Barrow within North West England (top left)\n</gallery>\n\n===Islands===\n{{Main|Islands of Furness}}\nThe town is sheltered from the Irish Sea by [[Walney Island]], a <span style=\"white-space:nowrap\">14&nbsp;mile&nbsp;(22.5&nbsp;km)</span> long island connected to the mainland by the [[Bascule bridge|bascule]] type [[Walney Bridge|Jubilee bridge]]. About 13,000 live on the isle's various settlements, mostly in [[Vickerstown]], which was built to house workers in the rapidly expanding shipyard. Another significant island which lay in the Walney Channel was [[Barrow Island (England)|Barrow Island]], but following the filling of the channel to create land for the shipyard it is now directly connected to the town. Other islands which lie close to Barrow are [[Piel Island]], whose [[Piel Castle|castle]] protected the harbour from marauding [[Scot]]s, [[Sheep Island (England)|Sheep Island]], [[Roa Island]] and [[Foulney Island]].\n\n===Parks and open spaces===\n\nThere are numerous natural and managed public parks and open spaces within Barrow. Walney North and [[South Walney|South Nature Reserves]] are protected as Sites of Special Scientific Interest, as is [[Sandscale Haws]]. Formal woodland areas within the town include Hawcoat/Ormsgill Quarry, How Tun Woods, [[Abbot's Wood, Cumbria|Abbotswood]], Barrow Steel Works & Slag Bank and Sowerby Wood. The 45-Acre [[Barrow Park]] is the largest and most centrally located man-made park in the town with smaller parks including Channelside Haven, Hindpool Urban Park and Vickerstown Park. There are also 25 council-owned playgrounds and 15 allotments.\n\n===Climate===\nBarrow on the west coast of Great Britain has a [[temperate]] [[maritime climate]] owing to the North Atlantic current and tends to have milder winters than central and eastern parts of the country. The town lies in [[Hardiness zone]] 9 and has an average yearly temperature of 10.4&nbsp;\u00b0C.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Barrow-in-Furness, England, United Kingdom\n|collapsed = y\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan high F = 44\n|Feb high F = 46\n|Mar high F = 49\n|Apr high F = 53\n|May high F = 59\n|Jun high F = 62\n|Jul high F = 66\n|Aug high F = 67\n|Sep high F = 63\n|Oct high F = 57\n|Nov high F = 50\n|Dec high F = 45\n|year high F=\n|Jan low F = 39\n|Feb low F = 39\n|Mar low F = 40\n|Apr low F = 43\n|May low F = 47\n|Jun low F = 52\n|Jul low F = 56\n|Aug low F = 56\n|Sep low F = 53\n|Oct low F = 49\n|Nov low F = 44\n|Dec low F = 39\n|year low F=\n|Jan record high F = 55\n|Feb record high F = 57\n|Mar record high F = 66\n|Apr record high F = 72\n|May record high F = 81\n|Jun record high F = 88\n|Jul record high F = 91\n|Aug record high F = 92\n|Sep record high F = 80\n|Oct record high F = 74\n|Nov record high F = 61\n|Dec record high F = 57\n|year record high F=\n|Jan record low F = 14\n|Feb record low F = 16\n|Mar record low F = 15\n|Apr record low F = 24\n|May record low F = 29\n|Jun record low F = 36\n|Jul record low F = 39\n|Aug record low F = 37\n|Sep record low F = 32\n|Oct record low F = 23\n|Nov record low F = 20\n|Dec record low F = 12\n|year record low F=\n|Jan precipitation inch = 2.80\n|Feb precipitation inch = 2.65\n|Mar precipitation inch = 2.50\n|Apr precipitation inch = 2.13\n|May precipitation inch = 2.17\n|Jun precipitation inch = 2.42\n|Jul precipitation inch = 2.22\n|Aug precipitation inch = 2.69\n|Sep precipitation inch = 3.39\n|Oct precipitation inch = 4.35\n|Nov precipitation inch = 3.62\n|Dec precipitation inch = 3.36\n|year precipitation inch=\n|source 1 = MSN Weather<ref name=MSNWeather >{{Cite web\n| url =http://weather.uk.msn.com/local.aspx?&wealocations=wc%3aUKXX1577&setunit=F | title =Average Weather for Barrow-in-Furness | accessdate =3 August 2007| publisher =[[MSN.com]] }}</ref>\n|date = August 2010}}\n\n==Demography==\n\n===Population===\nThe [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow council district]], which includes adjacent urban areas, had a population of around 69,100 according to the 2011 census. This is 4% less than the 2001 figure of 71,900, and the highest percentage population loss in the country between 2001 and 2011.<ref name=\"population\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/profiles/16uc.asp | title=Census statistics for Barrow-in-Furness 2001 | accessdate=11 May 2007 | publisher=National Statistics }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18681865|title=Census 2011: At a glance|date=16 July 2012|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref> The Office for National Statistics states Barrow's population as being in long term decline with a projected population of around 65,000 by 2037. This is largely a result of negative [[net migration]].<ref name=\"decline\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/snpp/sub-national-population-projections/2012-based-projections/rft-population-las.xls | title=Table 2: 2012-based Subnational Population Projections for Local Authorities in England  | accessdate=20 August 2014 | publisher=Office for National Statistics }}</ref>\n\n===Ethnicity and language===\nThe 2011 census states 96.9% of Barrow's population as [[White British]], and ethnic minority populations in Barrow stood at 3.1%.<ref name=2011ethnicity>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=13&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366140355413&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2575|title=Ethnic Group, 2011 (QS201EW)|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> Other ethnic groups in Barrow include [[White Other (United Kingdom Census)|Other White]] 1.3%, [[Asian people|Asian]] 1.0%, [[British Mixed|Mixed Race]] 0.5%, [[Black British|Black]] 0.1%, [[British Arab|Arab]] 0.1% and [[Other ethnic group (United Kingdom Census)|all other ethnic groups]] represented 0.1% of the population. The first people to settle in what is now Barrow were the [[Celts]] and [[Norsemen|Scandinavians]] followed by the [[Cornish people|Cornish]]. Most Barrovians however are descended from immigrants from [[Scotland]], [[Ireland]] and other parts of England who arrived from the late 19th century onwards. Barrow has significant [[British Chinese|Chinese]] (in particular those originating from Hong Kong), [[Filipinos in the United Kingdom|Filipino]], [[British Indian|Indian]], [[Thais in the United Kingdom|Thai]] and [[Kosovan migration to the United Kingdom|Kosovan]] communities as well as a [[Poles in the United Kingdom|Polish]] population which partly dates back to World War II, however in general Barrow has a much lower proportion of ethnic minorities than national average.<ref name=2011ethnicity/>\n\nBarrow's Chinese connections were the subject of a documentary on Chinese state television in 2014.<ref name=China>{{cite web|url=http://www.in-cumbria.com/links-between-barrow-and-china-to-be-featured-in-film-1.1100560|title=Links Between Barrow and China to be Featured in Film|publisher=in-cumbria.com|accessdate=17 August 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140817153354/http://www.in-cumbria.com/links-between-barrow-and-china-to-be-featured-in-film-1.1100560|archivedate=17 August 2014}}</ref> The programme covered diplomat [[Li Hongzhang]]'s fact finding mission to the town's steelworks and shipyard in 1896 as well as the 2012 discovery of a hoard of Chinese coins discovered in Barrow dated around a similar time that have been suggested as having been brought over by sailors or labourers.<ref name=China/> The [[Society for Anglo-Chinese Understanding]] is a charity with a branch based in Barrow that aims to develop relations with the [[British Chinese]] community and the general British population. It was established in 1975 and publishes the quarterly ''China Eye'' magazine.\n[[File:St James's Church, Barrow.jpg|thumb|right|[[St. James' Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. James' Church]], the largest place of worship in Barrow]]\n\nIn 2011 93.2% of the borough's population was born in England, 2.6% in [[Scotland]], 0.6%  in [[Northern Ireland]] and 0.5% in [[Wales]]. 3.1% of the town's 2011 population were born elsewhere in the world, 1.3% of which were born in the [[European Union]]. The five most common foreign countries of birth were [[Poland]], the [[Republic of Ireland]], Germany, the [[Philippines]] and [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=13&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366138221646&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2525| title = Country of Birth (detailed), 2011 (QS203EW)| accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2011 census, 98.8% of Barrovians spoke English as a main language, although around 40 languages are spoken in the town with [[Polish language|Polish]], Chinese, and [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] prevailing as the second, third and fourth most common main languages (0.3%, 0.2% and 0.1% of the population respectively).<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=13&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366138221646&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2528| title = Main Language (detailed), 2011 (QS204EW)| accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> Of the 797 Barrovians who had a main language other than English, 82.9% can speak English well to very well.<ref name=\"proficiency\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=14&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366143203704&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2500| title = Proficiency in English, 2011 (QS205EW)| accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\n{{See also|List of places of worship in Barrow-in-Furness}}\nIn the 2011 census 70.7% of Barrow's population stated themselves as being Christian. People stating no religion or chose not to state totalled 28.4% combined. Other religious groups represented 0.9% of the population, with [[Islam]] and [[Buddhism]] prevailing as the first and second most common groups.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=14&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366142319396&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2479| title = Religion, 2011 (KS209EW)| accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> Conishead Priory, the first [[Kadampa]] Buddhist centre in the west, is home to around 100 Buddhists and is located off the Barrow to Ulverston Coast Road within the [[South Lakeland]] district.<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www.aboutulverston.co.uk/location/conisheadpriory.htm| title= Conishead Priory, Ulverston| accessdate= 21 July 2007| publisher= AboutUlverston.co.uk| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070804012408/http://www.aboutulverston.co.uk/location/conisheadpriory.htm| archivedate= 4 August 2007|url-status = dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Historically Barrow was home to a notable [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi Jewish]] community that peaked in size during the 1930s with a synagogue in the town. Nonetheless, it closed in 1974 and only a dozen Jews were recorded by the 2011 census.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barrow-in-Furness Jewish Community & Synagogue|url=http://www.jewishgen.org/jcr-uk/Community/barrow/|publisher=Jewish Communities and Records|accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Audacious Under Construction MOD 45155780.jpg|thumb|left|An [[Astute-class submarine|''Astute''-class]] submarine under-construction inside [[Devonshire Dock Hall]] in 2013]]\nHistorically Barrow's economy was dominated by the manufacturing sector, with the [[Barrow Hematite Steel Company]] and [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering]] being amongst the most important global companies in their respective fields during the 20th century. In the present day, manufacturing remains the largest employment sector in the town with [[BAE Systems]] being the single largest employer. However, like most of the UK, employment trends have greatly diversified since the 20th century and there are no other predominant employment sectors in Barrow.\n\n===Shipyard and port===\nBarrow has played a vital role in global ship and submarine construction for around 150 years. [[Ottoman submarine Abd\u00fcl Hamid|Ottoman submarine ''Abd\u00fcl Hamid'']] was built in the town in 1886 and became the first submarine in the world to fire a live torpedo underwater, while oil tanker ''British Admiral'' became the first British vessel to exceed 100,000 tonnes when launched in 1965. The vast majority of all current and former Royal Navy submarines were constructed in Barrow as well as numerous [[Royal Navy Fleet Flagship]]s.\n\n[[File:HMS Invincible (R05).jpg|thumb|right|{{HMS|Invincible|R05|6}} pictured in Florida in 2004 is one of the most famous ships to have been built in Barrow]]\nThe [[BAE Systems Maritime \u2013 Submarines]] shipyard at Barrow is the largest in the UK by workforce ahead of [[BAE Systems Maritime \u2013 Naval Ships]] in [[Govan]]. It was expanded in 1986 by construction of a new covered assembly facility, the [[Devonshire Dock Hall]] (DDH), completed by [[Alfred McAlpine]], on land that was created by infilling part of the [[Devonshire Dock]] with 2.4 million tonnes of sand pumped from nearby Roosecote Sands.<ref>The Road to Success: Alfred McAlpine 1935 \u2013 1985 page 174, Tony Gray, Rainbird Publishing, 1987</ref> DDH is the tallest building in Cumbria at 51&nbsp;m. With a length of {{convert|268|m|ft|abbr=on}}, width of {{convert|51|m|ft|abbr=on}} and an area of {{convert|25000|m2|sqft|}} it is one of the largest shipbuilding construction complex of its kind in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Alison|title=Marine Marvel|url=http://www.thecqi.org/Documents/community/Special-Interest-Groups/Defence/Marine_marvel_jul_07.pdf|publisher=The Chartered Quality Institute|accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe DDH provides a controlled environment for ship and submarine assembly, and avoids the difficulties caused by building on the slope of traditional slipways. Outside the hall, a 24,300 tonne capacity shiplift allows completed vessels to be lowered into the water independently of the tide. Vessels can also be lifted out of the water and transferred to the hall.<ref>{{Cite journal| author = BAE Systems| title = Devonshire Dock Hall (DDH): One of the most advanced Shipbuilding Complexes in the World | url = http://www.baesystems.com/BAEProd/groups/public/documents/ss_asset/bae_subs_ddhdatasheet.pdf | accessdate =3 June 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070704111547/http://www.baesystems.com/BAEProd/groups/public/documents/ss_asset/bae_subs_ddhdatasheet.pdf| archivedate = 4 July 2007}}</ref> The first use of the DDH was for construction of the {{sclass-|Vanguard|submarine|2}}s, and later vessels of the {{sclass-|Trafalgar|submarine|4}} were also built there. The shipyard is currently constructing the {{sclass-|Astute|submarine|2}}s, the first of which was launched on 8 June 2007.<ref name=\"Astute_launch\">{{cite news| title = New UK nuclear submarine launched |work=BBC News | date = 8 June 2007 | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6733777.stm | accessdate =14 June 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070618113755/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6733777.stm| archivedate= 18 June 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> BAE Systems is currently studying the design of a [[British replacement of the Trident system|new class]] of ballistic missile submarines. BAE Systems also has orders for submarine pressure domes for the [[Spanish Navy]].<ref name=\"Spanish_subs\">{{cite news| title = BAE lands submarine export order |work=BBC News | date = 2 May 2007 | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6615139.stm | accessdate =14 June 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070605155840/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6615139.stm| archivedate= 5 June 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe shipyard has been awarded contracts for the construction of submarines which will carry nuclear missiles in a [[Dreadnought-class submarine|successor programme]] to the current ''Vanguard'' class containing the [[UK Trident programme|Trident system]].<ref name=Shipyardexpansion1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Defence-boom-will-create-thousands-of-BAE-Systems-jobs-in-Barrow-f2441d1a-a8f9-401e-befd-67a5aa217b58-ds|title=Defence boom will create thousands of BAE jobs in Barrow|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=13 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085451/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Defence-boom-will-create-thousands-of-BAE-Systems-jobs-in-Barrow-f2441d1a-a8f9-401e-befd-67a5aa217b58-ds|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> BAE Systems is investing \u00a3300 million in Barrow's shipyard to construct buildings capable of manufacturing and assembling the new class of submarines. This major development is the largest in 25 years at the shipyard and will see thousands of new jobs created, further cementing its place as the UK's largest shipyard and one of the few to have seen continuous contracts since founding over a century ago.<ref name=Shipyardexpansion1/>\n\n[[File:Return to base - geograph.org.uk - 580030.jpg|thumb|left|[[Barrow Offshore Wind Farm]]]]\nThe most recent surface vessels to be constructed in Barrow were {{sclass2-|Wave|tanker|2}} {{ship|RFA|Wave Knight|A389|6}} and {{sclass-|Albion|landing platform dock|0}} amphibious assault ships {{HMS|Albion|L14|6}} and {{HMS|Bulwark|L15|6}} in the early 2000s when the shipyard was part of [[BAE Systems Marine]] division. It also undertook fitting out and commissioning of helicopter carrier {{HMS|Ocean|L12|6}} in the mid-1990s after the ship was built by [[Kvaerner Govan]] in Glasgow.\n\n[[Associated British Ports Holdings]] owns and operates the [[Port of Barrow]] which can berth vessels up to {{convert|200|m|ft|abbr=on}} long and with a draught of {{convert|10|m|ft|abbr=on}}. The four main docks include [[Buccleuch Dock]], [[Cavendish Dock]], [[Devonshire Dock]] and [[Ramsden Dock]], with the latter handling almost all of the port's cargo. Buccleuch and Devonshire Docks are utilised primarily by BAE Systems, while Cavendish Dock the largest by surface area is now a reservoir. Principal traffic includes the export of condensate by-product from the production of gas at the [[Rampside Gas Terminal]], wood pulp and locally quarried limestone which is exported to Scandinavia for use in the paper industry. The port, which has deep water access, also handles the shipment of nuclear fuels and radioactive waste for [[BNFL]]'s nearby [[Sellafield]] plant.<ref>{{Cite web  | publisher= Associated British Ports  | title= Port of Barrow  | url= http://www.abports.co.uk/custinfo/ports/barrow.htm  | accessdate= 20 August 2007  | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927122945/http://www.abports.co.uk/custinfo/ports/barrow.htm  | archivedate= 27 September 2007  | url-status= dead  }}</ref>\n\n[[James Fisher & Sons]], a service provider in all sectors of the marine industry and a specialist supplier of engineering services to the nuclear industry in the UK and abroad,<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.james-fisher.co.uk/|title= Welcome to James Fisher|accessdate=30 August 2007 |year= 2005|work= James Fisher official website|publisher= James Fisher and Sons| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070828041321/http://www.james-fisher.co.uk/| archivedate= 28 August 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> was founded in Barrow in 1847.<ref>{{Cite news|first= Mary|last= MacIsaac|title= With a fair wind blowing there are profits to be made on the high seas|url= http://business.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=895&id=401272003|series= Armchair Investor|work=The Scotsman |location=UK|date=  6 April 2003|accessdate=30 August 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070810073535/http://business.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=895&id=401272003| archivedate= 10 August 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> It is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is the largest company to have its headquarters situated in Cumbria.<ref name=Largestplc>{{cite news|url=http://www.whitehavennews.co.uk/barrow-company-s-profits-soar-by-11-per-cent-1.931938|title=Barrow Company's Profits Soar by 11 Percent|newspaper=Whitehaven News|accessdate=5 March 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608051838/http://www.whitehavennews.co.uk/barrow-company-s-profits-soar-by-11-per-cent-1.931938|archivedate=8 June 2015}}</ref> Annual revenue stood at \u00a3307 million in 2012 (up 15% from \u00a3268 million in 2011), as well as staff numbers standing at over 1,500 worldwide, with 120 of those in the Barrow headquarters.<ref name=Largestplc/><ref>{{Cite news|title= Jobs Hope as Fisher Booms|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=536629|publisher= North West Evening Mail|date=  29 August 2007|accessdate=30 August 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926212059/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=536629| archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> Numerous vessels are registered at the Port of Barrow, with the majority being owned by James Fisher & Sons and [[International Nuclear Services]]/Pacific Nuclear Transport Limited.\n\n===Energy generation===\n[[File:North Walney Beach - geograph.org.uk - 209770.jpg|thumb|West Shore Beach at [[Earnse Bay]] with [[Black Combe]] visible in the distance]]\nIn 1985, gas was discovered in Morecambe Bay, and to this day the products have been processed onshore at [[Rampside Gas Terminal]] in south Barrow.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=459 | title=About Us | publisher=Centrica Gas | accessdate=21 July 2007 |url-status = dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070906181440/http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=459 | archivedate=6 September 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The complex is operated jointly by [[Centrica]] and [[ConocoPhillips]]. Directly adjacent to Rampside Gas Terminal is [[Roosecote Power Station]] which was the first [[Combined cycle|CCGT]] power station to supply electricity to the United Kingdom's National Grid. Although originally coal-fired, the station became gas-fired until it was mothballed in 2015.\n\nBarrow and its wider urban area form part of 'Britain's Energy Coast',<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.britainsenergycoast.com/ | title = ACTING LOCALLY, THINKING GLOBALLY | publisher = Britain's Energy Coast | accessdate=25 June 2011 }}</ref> and has one of the highest concentrations of [[wind farm]]s in the world, the vast majority are located offshore and have been built during the early 2010s. All four of these wind farms are located off the coast of Walney Island, including the 189 turbine [[Walney Wind Farm]], 108 turbine [[West Duddon wind farm]], 30 turbine [[Barrow Offshore Wind Farm]] and 30 turbine [[Ormonde Wind Farm]]. Walney Wind Farm was the largest offshore wind farm in the world upon completion, in 2015 it received government consent to be trebled in size. [[DONG Energy]] and [[Scottish Power]] maintain a wind farm operations base with 30 full-time staff members at the Port of Barrow.<ref name=Windoperations>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishpowerrenewables.com/news/pages/new_4_million_wind_farm_operations_base_in_barrow_seeks_skilled_workers.asp|title=New \u00a34 Million Wind Farm Operations Base in Barrow Seeks Skilled Workers|publisher=Scottish Power|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Sellafield]] and [[Heysham nuclear power station]]s are also located within {{convert|25|mi|km}} of Barrow.\n\n===Tourism and leisure===\n[[File:Giraffes south lakes wild animal park.jpg|thumb|left|[[South Lakes Safari Zoo]] on the outskirts of the borough is one of Cumbria's top tourist attractions]]\nAlthough it is at the end of a peninsula, Barrow is only around 20 minutes from the [[Lake District]],<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.totaltravel.co.uk/travel/north-west/carlisle-cumbrian-coast/south-cumbria/travel-guides/Destinations/barrow-in-furness|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071011092642/http://www.totaltravel.co.uk/travel/north-west/carlisle-cumbrian-coast/south-cumbria/travel-guides/Destinations/barrow-in-furness|url-status = dead|archive-date= 11 October 2007|title= Barrow in Furness|accessdate= 14 August 2007|publisher= totaltravel.com}}</ref> Barrow has been referred to as a \"gateway to the lakes\" and \"where the lakes meets the sea\",<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=467814|title= Half Term Fun for the Kids Just on the Doorstep|accessdate=14 August 2007 |date= 17 February 2007|publisher= North West Evening Mail |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926210914/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=467814 |archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> a status which could be enhanced by the new marina complex and planned cruise ship terminal.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/docs/November%202005%20-%20Executive%20Committee%20Agenda.doc|title= November 2005 \u2013 Executive Committee Agenda|accessdate= 14 August 2007|date= November 2005|format= DOC|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|pages= 5|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030709/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/docs/November%202005%20-%20Executive%20Committee%20Agenda.doc|archivedate= 28 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBarrow itself has several tourist attractions that support just over 1,000 jobs; the town saw a higher growth in tourist expenditure during the 2000s than Cumbria as a whole and had about 2.3 million overnight stays during 2008.<ref name=Touriststats>{{cite web|url=http://www.cumbriaobservatory.org.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/675/4356/40501155120.pdf|title=Cumbria Local Economic Assessment|publisher=Cumbria Observatory|accessdate=6 April 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416145143/http://www.cumbriaobservatory.org.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/675/4356/40501155120.pdf|archivedate=16 April 2014}}</ref> Barrow's most popular free-entry tourist attraction is the [[Dock Museum]]. The museum tells the history of Barrow (including the steelworks industry, the shipyard and the [[Barrow Blitz]]), as well as offering gallery space to local artists and schoolchildren. It is built upon and around an old graving dock.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/enjoy_cumbria/places/barrow_dock_museum.shtml|title= Barrow Dock Museum|accessdate=14 August 2007 |work= Enjoy Cumbria|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Walney Island has two world-renowned nature reserves (the 130 hectare (0.5 sq mi) South Walney Nature Reserve<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.cumbriawildlifetrust.org.uk/south-walney.html|title= South Walney|accessdate= 2 September 2011|publisher= Cumbria Wildlife Trust|url-status = dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110903122209/http://www.cumbriawildlifetrust.org.uk/south-walney.html|archivedate= 3 September 2011|df= dmy-all}}</ref> and the 650 hectare (2.5 sq mi) [[North Walney|North Walney Nature Reserve]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designatedareas/nnr/northwalneywhatmakesitspecial.aspx|title= North Walney: what makes it special?|accessdate=2 September 2011|publisher= Natural England}}</ref> Both nature reserves have [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] designation, as do the [[Duddon Estuary]] and [[Sandscale Haws]] to the north of the borough. Barrow has a number of beaches which are popular in the summer with sunbathers, kitesurfers and caravanners. They include [[Earnse Bay]], Biggar Bank, [[Roanhead]] and [[Rampside]]. The first two of these provide views of the [[Isle of Man]] and [[Anglesey]] on exceptionally clear days. The wider borough has more than 60&nbsp;km of coastline.<ref name=Beaches>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=153 |title=Beaches |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |accessdate=6 April 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154537/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=153 |archivedate=24 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The Park Leisure Centre is a fitness suite with a pool, set in the {{convert|45|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[Barrow Park]].<ref name=\"aboutbritain\"/> The historic ruins of [[Furness Abbey]] and [[Piel Castle]], which are both managed by [[English Heritage]], are also popular tourist destinations. [[South Lakes Safari Zoo]] is one of Europe's leading conservation zoos and has been voted Cumbria's best tourist attraction in five non-consecutive years although it has a checkered history; it lies within the borough of Barrow-in-Furness on the outskirts of Dalton. The zoo underwent a multi-million pound expansion during the mid-2010s. It now holds thousands of animals and covers an area of {{Convert|51|acres}} making it one of the Northern England's largest such parks.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.visitcumbria.com/sl/south-lakes-wild-animal-park.htm|title= South Lakes Wild Animal Park|accessdate= 2 September 2011|publisher= Visit Cumbria|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110719164425/http://visitcumbria.com/sl/south-lakes-wild-animal-park.htm|archivedate= 19 July 2011|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:The White House And The Castle.jpg|thumb|right|[[Piel Island]] and [[Piel Castle|castle]] are a popular attraction in Barrow]]\n\nBarrow has been described as the Lake District's premier shopping town, with 'big name shops mingling with small local ones'.<ref name=\"aboutbritain\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.aboutbritain.com/towns/barrow-in-furness.asp|title= Barrow-in-Furness Tourist Information|accessdate=25 August 2007 |publisher= AboutBritain.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070828073226/http://www.aboutbritain.com/towns/barrow-in-furness.asp| archivedate= 28 August 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> The town centre is home to a large indoor market<ref>{{Cite news|first=Bibi |last=van der Zee |title=Pitch Perfect, Part Two |date=7 August 2007 |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,,1838907,00.html |accessdate=27 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702120519/http://www.guardian.co.uk/g2/story/0%2C%2C1838907%2C00.html |archivedate=2 July 2007 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=149 |title=Barrow Borough Council \u2013 Barrow Markets |accessdate=27 July 2007 |date=7 March 2007 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824210003/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=149 |archivedate=24 August 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> and [[Portland Walk Shopping Centre]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=161|title= Shopping and Town Centre|accessdate= 23 September 2007|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070911122313/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=161|archivedate= 11 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Barrow has many retail and leisure parks for a town of its size, including [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Cornmill Crossing|Cornmill Crossing]], [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Cornerhouse Retail Park|Cornerhouse Retail Park]], [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Hollywood Park|Hollywood Park]], [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Hollywood Park|Hindpool Retail Park]] and Walney Road Retail Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=137|title= Exploring the Area around Barrow-in-Furness|accessdate= 23 September 2007|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070911222136/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=137|archivedate= 11 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrow.furness.co.uk/barrow_lifestyle.asp?ID=L6|title= 24 Hour Shopping|accessdate=30 August 2007 |work= Barrow. Furness.co.uk|publisher= Furness Enterprise Ltd.}}</ref> Between them they host a number of supermarkets, electrical, home furnishing, clothing and discount stores, gyms, restaurants and Cumbria's largest cinema. Other modern visitor attractions in Barrow include the growing leisure destination at James Freel Close (consisting of an indoor [[kart racing]] complex, [[bowling]] alley, indoor [[skate park]], [[trampoline]] centre and gym), as well as Lazer Zone in Hindpool Road's former [[Custom House, Barrow-in-Furness|Custom House]] and a similar Lazer Quest, [[escape room]] and play centre in the former Hitchens building on Buccleuch Street.\n\n===Regeneration and redevelopment===\n[[File:Central Yard Facility Barrow July 2017.jpg|thumb|right|The Central Yard Facility, photographed in July 2017, is at the centre of BAE Systems' \u00a3300 million redevelopment]]\n[[File:Abbey Road and Holker Street, Barrow.PNG|thumb|[[Duke of Edinburgh Hotel]] and [[Emlyn Hughes House]]]]\n\nUrban regeneration has been ongoing in Barrow since the 1990s. [[Portland Walk Shopping Centre]] opened in 1998 anchored by [[Debenhams]] as part of a major reconstruction of Barrow town centre. Around the same time the [[Hindpool Retail Parks]] and [[Dock Museum]] were constructed over various former industrial sites in Barrow, including the [[dry dock]], the [[Barrow Jute Works]] and the [[Barrow Hematite Steel Company|Barrow Steel Works]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Barrow Dock Museum|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/enjoy_cumbria/places/barrow_dock_museum.shtml|publisher=BBC Cumbria|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> Recent construction projects in the town also include the \u00a343 million expansion of [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]]'s Channelside campus,<ref name=Redevelopmentcollege>{{cite web|url=http://www.furness.ac.uk/new-build|title=New build|publisher=Furness College|accessdate=26 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701184904/http://www.furness.ac.uk/new-build|archive-date=1 July 2013|url-status = dead}}</ref> \u00a322.5 million [[Furness Academy]] new build,<ref name=Redevelopmentacademy>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/furness-academy-s-22-5m-vision-finally-to-become-reality-1.913623?referrerPath=|title=Furness Academy's \u00a322.5 million vision to finally become reality|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=26 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130628032403/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/furness-academy-s-22-5m-vision-finally-to-become-reality-1.913623?referrerPath=|archivedate=28 June 2013}}</ref> \u00a314.5 million central Barrow flood relief scheme,<ref name=Floodrelief>{{cite web|url=http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2009/UU_Barrow_2009.pdf|title=Barrow DG5 Flood Relief Scheme|publisher=waterprojectsonline.coml|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> \u00a38.5 million Barrow police station,<ref name=Redevelopmentpolice>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/home/multimillion-pound-plans-for-barrow-police-station-unveiled-1.1065289?referrerPath=home|title=Multi million pound plans for Barrow police station revealed|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=26 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130628032342/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/home/multimillion-pound-plans-for-barrow-police-station-unveiled-1.1065289?referrerPath=home|archivedate=28 June 2013}}</ref> \u00a35 million town centre redevelopment scheme,<ref name=Redevelopmentcentre>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitasymonds.co.uk/news__events/news/barrow_town_centre_scheme_on_s.aspx|title=Barrow town centre scheme on schedule|publisher=Capita Symonds|accessdate=26 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506111214/http://capitasymonds.co.uk/news__events/news/barrow_town_centre_scheme_on_s.aspx|archivedate=6 May 2013}}</ref> \u00a34 million Scottish Power wind farm operations centre<ref name=\"Windoperations\"/> as well as the North Central Renewal Area, shake up of the town's residential and retirement homes and a number of large-scale hotel schemes catering for the influx of contractors working for BAE Systems (namely [[Holiday Inn Express]], [[Premier Inn]] and [[Wetherspoon]]).<ref name=Redevelopmentnorthcentral>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/PDF/NorthCentralNRAAug2008.pdf|title=North Central Renewal Area|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|accessdate=26 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714202300/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/PDF/NorthCentralNRAAug2008.pdf|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[The Waterfront Barrow-in-Furness|The Waterfront]] is an ambitious ongoing \u00a3200 million dockland regeneration project, which began in 2007. The project includes a new Barrow Marina Village which will incorporate an \u00a38 million 400-berth marina, 650 homes, restaurants, shops, hotels and a new state of the art bridge across Cavendish Dock. A large watersports centre is also proposed, with the possibility of a cruise ship terminal. Some cruise ships are already scheduled to dock in Barrow, mainly for tourists to visit the Lake District, although there is no official cruise ship terminal yet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Little-Known Barrow Plans British Fanfare for Princess Cruise Passengers|url=http://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/news.cfm?ID=3166|publisher=Cruise Critic|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> Developments have stalled since 2010 when the [[Northwest Regional Development Agency]]  was disbanded and essential government funding was lost. Despite this Barrow Borough Council has since purchased land needed to make the development a reality and currently controls 95% of the site.<ref name=Marinafuture>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/work-on-barrow-s-marina-vision-could-begin-within-three-years-1.1161141|title=Work on Barrow's Marina Vision Could Begin 'Within Three Years'|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=11 September 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911212037/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/work-on-barrow-s-marina-vision-could-begin-within-three-years-1.1161141|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref> The executive director of the council has stated construction of the Waterfront could resume by 2017 as economic prospects improve and has pledged funds to conduct a market testing exercise. The allocation of Growth Deal investment (2014\u20132021) will make improvements to the Barrow Waterfront Enterprise Zone far more secure <ref name=Marinafuture/> In 2014 a \u00a3300 million investment into the shipyard was announced by BAE Systems, in anticipation of the [[trident replacement|new generation of UK nuclear submarines]].<ref name=\"Shipyardexpansion1\"/><ref name=Shipyardexpansion2/> Construction will take up to eight years and create thousands of new jobs at the shipyard thereafter.<ref name=Shipyardexpansion1/> Amongst proposals are an extension to the DDH complex and new buildings in the central yard area off Bridge Road on Barrow Island (a site formerly mooted for a huge construction hall for the construction of [[Queen Elizabeth-class aircraft carrier|''Queen Elizabeth''-class aircraft carrier]] sections which the yard failed to win contracts for), these will house pressure hull units ready for shot blasting and painting, and be a place for joining submarine equipment modules.<ref name=Shipyardexpansion2>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/bae-systems-development-will-change-barrow-skyline-1.1122540|title=BAE Systems Development will change Barrow skyline|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=13 March 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313165418/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/bae-systems-development-will-change-barrow-skyline-1.1122540|archivedate=13 March 2014}}</ref> Redevelopment of the 5.8 hectare central yard area was completed in 2018 and is dominated by the [[Central Yard Complex Facility]] which measures {{convert|178|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|94|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide and {{convert|41|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall, only 10% smaller than the volume of the pre-expansion Devonshire Dock Hall.\n\nOther large-scale developments associated with BAE include a {{convert|30,000|sqm|sqft|abbr=on}} logistics centre which was constructed in the Waterfront Business Park in 2015 and a {{convert|8,100|sqm|sqft|abbr=on}} central training facility which is proposed at Buccleuch Dock Road.\n\n===Other===\nOther major employers include the [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]], through [[Furness General Hospital]], which employs 1,800 staff,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.nwra.gov.uk/downloads/documents/imported/321089760698.doc | title=Cumbria Prosperity Priorities Summit held on 2 April 2004 | publisher=North West Regional Assembly | accessdate=20 August 2007 | format=DOC | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927121818/http://www.nwra.gov.uk/downloads/documents/imported/321089760698.doc | archivedate=27 September 2007 |url-status = dead| df=dmy-all }}</ref> the [[Kimberly Clark]] paper mill, which has 400 employees,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.furnessenterprise.co.uk/furness_enterprise_sectors.asp?menuID=13&ID=IS6 | title=Furness Enterprise \u2013 Fast Moving Consumer Goods | publisher=Furness Enterprise | accessdate=20 August 2007 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929040235/http://www.furnessenterprise.co.uk/furness_enterprise_sectors.asp?menuID=13&ID=IS6 | archivedate=29 September 2007 |url-status = dead| df=dmy-all }}</ref> BAE Systems' [[BAE Systems Land & Armaments|Land and Armaments]] division, [[Furness Building Society]] which is one of the 20 largest of its kind, [[Cumbria County Council]] and [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow Borough Council]]. Amongst many retailers that have established themselves in Barrow, the furniture store [[Stollers]] is noted as being one of the largest shops of its kind in the UK.\n\n===Employment===\n[[File:Craven House, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|[[Craven House]] is headquarters of [[James Fisher & Sons]], the only Barrow company on the [[London Stock Exchange]]]] [[File:Tesco Barrow, Cumbria.jpg|thumb|right|[[Tesco]] is a significant employer, with several outlets across Barrow]]\nAccording to the 2011 census, 78.2% of males aged 16\u201364 and females aged 16\u201359 in Barrow were economically active. This figure is higher than the North West and England averages.<ref name=Employment>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=3&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=4&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1367432044166&enc=1|title=Key Figures for Economic Deprivation|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref> 73.8% of the population was employed, which again is higher than regional and national averages; the unemployment rate stood at 5.6% which is lower than both averages.<ref name=Employment/> Despite this the percentage of people claiming key benefits, which is independent of the unemployment figure, is much higher than both averages at 21.0%, or almost a quarter of all Barrovians of working age.<ref name=Employment/> The most common form of benefit received was the [[Incapacity Benefit]], claimed by 11.0% of the adult population, while 4.0% claimed [[Jobseeker's Allowance]], which is on a par with the national average.<ref name=Employment/>\n\nThe list below shows how many people were employed in certain sectors according to the 2011 census. Little change has occurred over the 10-year period since the previous census; Barrow still has a much higher percentage of workers in the manufacturing sector than the national average, ranking third in 2011 behind [[Corby]], Northamptonshire and [[Borough of Pendle|Pendle]], Lancashire.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=9&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1367430603744&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2538 |publisher=statistics.gov.uk |title=Area: Barrow-in-Furness (Local Authority) |accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=Employmenttrends>{{cite web|url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/2011-census-analysis/170-years-of-industry/170-years-of-industrial-changeponent.html|title=170 Years of Industrial Change across England and Wales|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref> South West Cumbria has one of the UK's most self-contained workforces, and Barrow itself has the sixth lowest proportion of people who travel outside of the country for work.<ref name=othercommute>{{cite web|url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171776_357812.pdf|title=2011 Census Analysis \u2013 Distance Travelled to Work|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> In 2001, 76% of the working age population in Barrow commuted within {{convert|5|km}} for work, when compared to the England average of 54%.<ref name=Traveltowork>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1006&k=distance&m=0&r=1&s=1435005696594&enc=1&domainId=16&dsFamilyId=189|title=Distance Travelled to Work \u2013 Workplace Population, 2001 (UV80)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> A significant proportion of the town's population are employed at the [[Sellafield]] nuclear facility.\n* Manufacturing: 6,570 employed (21.0% of the town's working population)\n* Wholesale and retail trade: 4,728 (15.1%)\n* Human health and social work: 4,539 (14.5%)\n* Construction: 2,387 (7.6%)\n* Education: 2,381 (7.6%)\n* Accommodation and food service activities: 1,962 (6.3%)\n* Public administration and defence: 1,913 (6.1%)\n* Transport and storage: 1,296 (4.1%)\n* Administrative and support service: 1,055 (3.4%)\n* Professional, scientific and technical: 1,000 (3.2%)\n* Information and communication: 496 (1.6%)\n* Financial and insurance: 492 (1.6%)\n* Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply: 441 (1.4%)\n* Water supply: 264 (0.8%)\n* Real estate: 221 (0.7%)\n* Mining and quarrying: 165 (0.5%)\n* Agriculture, forestry and fishing: 122 (0.4%)\n* Other: 1,225 (3.9%)\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Road===\n[[File:Crook Scar - geograph.org.uk - 160218.jpg|thumb|right|[[Walney Bridge]] (officially Jubilee Bridge) links Barrow Island to Walney Island]]\n\nBarrow's principal road link is the [[A590 road|A590]]. This runs to Barrow from the [[M6 motorway]] via [[Ulverston]], skirting the southern [[Lake District]].<ref name=\"Map\">{{Cite web|url= http://maps.google.co.uk/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Barrow+in+Furness&ie=UTF8&ll=54.173287,-2.999268&spn=0.205782,0.6427&z=11&om=1|title= Barrow area map|accessdate=26 August 2007 |format= Flash|work= [[Google Maps]]|publisher= Google Maps}}</ref> Just north of Barrow is the southern end of the [[A595 road|A595]], linking the town to [[West Cumbria]].<ref name=\"Map\"/> The A5087 connects Barrow's southern suburbs to Ulverston via a scenic coastal route. [[Abbey Road, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey Road]] is the principal road through central Barrow, whilst [[Walney Bridge]] connects Barrow Island to [[Walney Island]].\n\nThe possibility of a bridge link over [[Morecambe Bay]] is occasionally raised, and feasibility studies have been carried out.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Hetherington | first = Peter | title = Council gives thumbs up to <span style=\"white-space:nowrap\">12&nbsp;mile&nbsp;(19&nbsp;km)</span> bridge for Morecambe Bay |work=The Guardian |location=London | date = 19 May 2004 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk_news/story/0,3604,1220030,00.html | accessdate =9 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Bus===\nBus services within the town are operated by [[Stagecoach North West]]. There is no specifically designated bus station, although many bus routes start and end near the town hall. The original bus station, since demolished, was known for its role in a 1970s television commercial for [[Chewits]] sweets.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/content/articles/2006/03/30/cumbriaonfilm_chewits_feature.shtml | title=Barrow Chewits ad | publisher=BBC Cumbria | accessdate =17 July 2007 }}</ref> As well as local suburban and village services, longer-distance buses run to [[Millom]], [[Ulverston]], [[Bowness-on-Windermere|Bowness]], [[Windermere, Cumbria (town)|Windermere]] and [[Kendal]].\n\n===Rail===\n[[File:Barrow-in-Furness Station, Cumbria.jpg|thumb|left|[[Barrow-in-Furness railway station]] viewed from [[Abbey Road, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey Road]]]]\n[[Barrow-in-Furness railway station]] provides connections to [[Whitehaven]], [[Workington]] and [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] to the north, via the [[Cumbrian Coast Line]], and to [[Ulverston]], [[Grange-over-Sands]] and [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] to the east, via the [[Furness Line]] \u2013 both of which connect to the [[West Coast Mainline]]. Numerous daily trains run to [[Manchester Piccadilly station|Manchester]]. The station handles over 600,000 passengers annually. Barrow has a second railway station, [[Roose railway station|Roose]], which serves [[Roose|the suburb of the same name]].\n\n[[Furness Abbey railway station|Furness Abbey]], Barrow's third main line station, closed in 1950. There was also a station on [[Island Road railway station|Barrow Island]], for commuters between the shipyard and nearby towns served by the Furness Railway. This railway link was severed in 1966 when the famous cradle bridge across the docks was closed permanently for safety reasons. There were also stations at [[Piel railway station|Piel]], Rabbit Hill, [[Rampside railway station|Rampside]], [[Ramsden Dock railway station|Ramsden Dock]] and [[Barrow-in-Furness Strand railway station|Strand]].\n\nBetween 1885 and 1932, the [[Barrow-in-Furness Tramways Company]] operated a [[double-decker tram]] service over several miles, primarily around central Barrow, Barrow Island and Hindpool.\n\n===Air===\n[[Barrow/Walney Island Airport]] ([[IATA airport code]]: BWF, [[ICAO]]: EGNL) is a former commercial airport and [[Royal Air Force]] base currently owned by BAE Systems which operates two [[Beechcraft King Air|Beechkraft King Air]] B200 and one B250 aircraft which fly to various destinations across the UK every weekday, including Bristol, Glasgow, London and Manchester. The airport's runways take on a triangular form, the longest runway is almost {{convert|4000|ft|m}}. The airport was expanded by BAE in 2018 including the construction of a new terminal building, hangar and control tower.\n\n[[Manchester Airport]] is the closest major airport, with direct links to Barrow railway station and about two hours away by road.\n\nIn 2018 a [[heliport]] was built on a site adjacent to Park Road, Ormsgill for energy firm [[\u00d8rsted (company)|\u00d8rsted]] and to support the offshore energy sector.\n\n===Sea===\nDespite being one of the UK's leading shipbuilding centres, the [[Associated British Ports]]' [[Port of Barrow]] is only a minor port. Historically, the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet]] and the [[Barrow Steam Navigation Company]] (a subsidiary of the Furness Railway and later [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]) operated a number of steamers and passenger ferry services between Rampside and [[Ramsden Dock]] and [[Ardrossan]] (Scotland), [[Belfast]] (Northern Ireland), [[Blackpool]], [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] (Isle of Man), [[Fleetwood]] and [[Heysham]].<ref name=Ferry>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/go-anywhere-on-a-boat-from-barrow-1.116441?referrerPath=home/2.4856 |title=Go Anywhere On a Boat From Barrow |publisher=North West Evening Mail |accessdate=11 January 2015 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112185109/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/go-anywhere-on-a-boat-from-barrow-1.116441?referrerPath=home%2F2.4856 |archivedate=12 January 2015  }}</ref> All services had ceased operation by the mid-20th century.\n\nFor a short period during the early 1880s, transatlantic travel was possible from the town. [[Anchor Line (steamship company)|The Anchor Line]] operated a fortnightly service utilising three of its steamships, ''Alexandria'', ''Caledonia'' and ''Columbia'', between Barrow and [[New York City]] via [[Dublin]]. There are proposals to construct a cruise ship terminal in Barrow as part of the Waterfront redevelopment project.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/4706191.stm | title=Town chosen for cruise ship terminal |publisher=BBC | accessdate=15 June 2007 | date=22 July 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n[[File:Holkerstreetmainstand.jpg|thumb|[[Holker Street]], the home of Barrow A.F.C.]]\n\n===Football===\n\n{{Main|Barrow A.F.C.|Holker Old Boys F.C.}}\n[[Barrow A.F.C.]] are in the [[Conference National]] division of English football.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=151|title= Sports in Barrow and Furness|accessdate= 19 August 2007|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070828161827/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=151|archivedate= 28 August 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The team, founded in 1901, are nicknamed the Bluebirds and play their home games at the [[Holker Street]] stadium.<ref name=\"Bluebirds\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/sport/clubs/barrow/12_2003.shtml|title= Barrow Football Club|accessdate=19 August 2007 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> The side were members of the [[Football League]] until they failed to be re-elected in 1972.<ref name=\"Bluebirds\"/> In 1990, they won the [[FA Trophy]] beating [[Leek Town F.C.|Leek Town]] 3\u20130 in the final at [[Wembley Stadium (1924)|Wembley Stadium]], London.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.napit.co.uk/viewus/infobank/football/fatophy.php|title= The FA Trophy|accessdate=19 August 2007 |publisher= Napit.co.uk| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070823063143/http://www.napit.co.uk/viewus/infobank/football/fatophy.php| archivedate= 23 August 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> Twenty years later, on 8 May 2010, [[Barrow A.F.C.|Barrow]] repeated the feat, beating [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]] 2\u20131 after extra time.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFATrophy/Match%20Centre/Final%202010/080510|title= Walker wins it for hometown Barrow|accessdate=8 May 2010 |publisher= TheFA.com}}</ref> Barrow were bought by Texas-based businessman Paul Casson in 2014 with a five-year plan of returning the team to the Football League and completely redeveloping Holker Street, including the addition of three new stands.\n\nFootball players born in Barrow include England internationals [[Emlyn Hughes]]<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2004/11/10/db1001.xml|title=  Emlyn Hughes Obituary|accessdate=8 July 2007 |date=  11 November 2004|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London }}</ref> and [[Gary M. Stevens|Gary Stevens]],<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.toffeeweb.com/history/legends/Stevens.asp|title= Stevens, Gary 1981\u201388|accessdate=8 July 2007 |last= Pike|first= Richard|author2=Poutianinen, Marko|year= 1999|work= Hall of Fame|publisher= ToffeeWeb| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070611233558/http://toffeeweb.com/history/legends/Stevens.asp| archivedate= 11 June 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> as well as [[Harry Hadley]],<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.englandstats.com/playerreport.php?pid=424 | title = Player Report \u2013 Harry Hadley | accessdate =21 July 2007 |publisher= EnglandStats.com}}</ref> and [[Vic Metcalfe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.englandstats.com/playerreport.php?pid=659 |title=Player Profile \u2013 Vic Metcalfe |accessdate=7 August 2007 |publisher=EnglandStats.com }}</ref>\nOf current professional footballers, [[Wayne Curtis]],<ref>{{Cite news| title=Wayne makes Wembley History | date=21 May 2007 | publisher=[[CN Group]] | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/unknown/viewarticle.aspx?id=500925 | work =[[North West Evening Mail]] | accessdate =7 August 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926211331/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/unknown/viewarticle.aspx?id=500925 |archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] striker, and Iran Under-20 and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] winger Shana Haji<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.persianmirror.com/Article_det.cfm?id=1367&getArticleCategory=42&getArticleSubCategory=4|title= Shana Haji, the first Iranian player in Scotland|accessdate= 21 June 2007|last= Dastafshan|first= Afshin|publisher= Persian Mirror|url-status = dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010053/http://www.persianmirror.com/Article_det.cfm?id=1367&getArticleCategory=42&getArticleSubCategory=4|archivedate= 27 September 2007|df= dmy-all}}</ref> both hail from the town.\n\nHolker Old Boys F.C., based at Rakesmoor Lane, are the town's second most successful football team, and they play in the [[North West Counties Football League]] Division One.\n\n===Rugby===\n{{Main|Barrow Raiders}}\n[[File:Craven Park, Barrow.jpg|thumb|left|[[Craven Park (Barrow)|Craven Park]], the home of Barrow Raiders]]\n[[Rugby league]] is a well-established sport and the town is considered as one of the game's traditional heartlands at professional and amateur levels.<ref name=\"rugby\">{{Cite news|first=Andy |last=Wilson |title=RUGBY LEAGUE: CARLISLE MERGER SIGNALS RETHINK |work=The Guardian |location=UK |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=16 October 1997|page=27 |quote=Now Carlisle's decision to move in with Barrow, a traditional hotbed of league where the amateur game remains as strong as ever, may be followed by a new club from [[South Wales]] entering Super League next year.}}</ref> The professional team, [[Barrow Raiders]], whose home games are at [[Craven Park (Barrow)|Craven Park]], played in the [[Co-operative Championship|Championship]] until 2011 but as of 2012, they now operate in the league below, known as [[RFL League 1|League 1]]. In the 1950s the side played in three [[Challenge Cup]] finals, winning the last of these against [[Workington Town]]. In the 1997 reorganisation of the sport the original Barrow RLFC team merged with [[Carlisle RLFC|Carlisle Border Raiders]] to form Barrow Border Raiders,<ref>{{Cite news|first=Andy |last=Wilson |title=RUGBY LEAGUE: CARLISLE MERGER SIGNALS RETHINK |work=The Guardian |location=UK |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=16 October 1997|page=27 |quote=CARLISLE and Barrow have decided to merge into a new club, Barrow Border Raiders, with repercussions extending well beyond the Second Division and Cumbria.}}</ref> with the word \"border\" later dropped. Players who were born in the town and played at a professional level include brothers [[Ade Gardner|Ade]]<ref>{{cite news| title = Gardner out for indefinite period |work=BBC News | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_league/6599411.stm | date = 27 April 2007 | accessdate =21 July 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070711031424/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_league/6599411.stm| archivedate= 11 July 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> and [[Mat Gardner]]<ref>{{Cite news|first=David |last=Burke |title= A Welcome MAT for My Mate ADE; HUDDERSFIELD GIANTS V ST HELENS, TOMORROW, KICK-OFF 3&nbsp;pm |work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |publisher=[[Mirror Group Newspapers]] | page=57 |date=11 March 2006|quote=Mat, brought up in Barrow with Ade, said: \"It's always been a dream of mine to play against my elder brother and this could be the time it becomes a reality. There's also a big chance we could be meeting head-on on the wing and that would be fantastic. I was pleased with my performance at [[Wakefield Trinity]], I just hope Jon Sharp was pleased too \u2013 that's obviously the key to me playing against Saints.\"}}</ref> and [[Willie Horne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/goingout/viewarticle.aspx?id=326017|title= Vickerstown Cricket Club, Walney|accessdate=21 June 2007 |date=  26 January 2006|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926211104/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/goingout/viewarticle.aspx?id=326017| archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> The latter captained Barrow to their Challenge Cup victory and represented Great Britain at an international level. He was inducted into the \"Barrow Hall of Fame\" along with former Barrow players [[Phil Jackson (rugby league born 1932)|Phil Jackson]] and [[Jimmy Lewthwaite]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rl1908.com/Legends/jackson.htm |title=Rugby League History \u2013 Interview with Phil Jackson |accessdate=4 August 2007 |last=Fagan |first=Sean |work=RL1908.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060511184546/http://www.rl1908.com/Legends/jackson.htm |archivedate=11 May 2006 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nAt a local level, eight amateur rugby league teams participate in the [[Barrow & District League]]. They include Askam, Barrow Island, Dalton, Hindpool, Milliom, Roose Pioneers, Ulverston and Walney\n\n===Golf===\n\nBarrow is home to two large golf clubs. Barrow Golf Club, founded in 1922, is situated in [[Hawcoat]] and covers some {{convert|6209|yd|m|}} with 18 holes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englishgolf-courses.co.uk/cumbria/barrow.php|title=Barrow Golf Club|website=www.englishgolf-courses.co.uk}}</ref> Furness Golf Club, founded in 1872, is the sixth oldest golf club in England and is possibly the more famous of the two. It is located on [[Walney Island]], just {{convert|50|yd|m|}} from the [[Irish Sea]]. It also offers an 18-hole course, a shop and other facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golftoday.co.uk/clubhouse/coursedir/cumbria/furness.html|title=Furness Golf Club,Barrow In Furness,Cumbria,England|website=www.golftoday.co.uk|access-date=10 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517135054/http://www.golftoday.co.uk/clubhouse/coursedir/cumbria/furness.html|archive-date=17 May 2008|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Furness Golf Centre is located on the outskirts of Barrow close to Roanhead and is home to a 14-bay driving range, golf shop, swing studio and the Fairway Hotel.<ref name=Fairway>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairway-hotel.co.uk/index.php|title=Fairway Hotel and Furness Golf Centre|publisher=Fairway Hotel|accessdate=6 April 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404005520/http://www.fairway-hotel.co.uk/index.php|archivedate=4 April 2013}}</ref> The hoaxer [[Maurice Flitcroft]], known as the \"world's worst golfer\" lived and worked in the town.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Murray|first1=Scott|last2=Farnaby|first2=Simon|title=The Phantom of the Open: Maurice Flitcroft, The World's Worst Golfer|date=2011|publisher=Yellow Jersey Press|isbn=978-0224083171}}</ref>\n\n===Motor sports===\n\nBarrow has staged [[Motorcycle speedway|speedway]] racing at three venues since the pioneer days in the late 1920s. The first track was at Holker Street. This venue had a revival for a short spell in the early to mid-1970s being utilised by the short-lived [[Barrow Bombers]]. In 1930 the sport moved to Little Park but this a somewhat hazy venue. The sport had a revival in 1978 at Park Avenue Industrial Estate but this was relatively short lived.\n\n====Bike racing====\n\nBarrow has produced a number of noteworthy motorcyclists throughout the years, such as Manx Grand Prix winner Eddie Crooks, TT Rider Dan Stewart, Speedway ace [[Adam Roynon]] and multiple British Sandtrack Champion John Pepper.\n\n====Karting====\n\nKart racer Kristian Brierley<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kartingmagazine.com/news/maxxis-tkm-festival-double-honours-bonus/attachment/kristian-brierley/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=21 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810144546/http://www.kartingmagazine.com/news/maxxis-tkm-festival-double-honours-bonus/attachment/kristian-brierley/ |archive-date=10 August 2018 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> received national attention after successfully winning the internationally televised TKM Karting Festival in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwemail.co.uk/sport/other-sport/junior-sport/16463770.askam-speedster-earns-national-karting-title/|title=Askam speedster earns national karting title|website=The Mail}}</ref>\n\nHe followed this up by winning the opening round of the British Championship in 2016.\n\nBrierley's first cousin Lydia Burney has also competed at national level in karting, as have multiple other 'Barrovians' such as Max Davis, Daniel Pepper,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwemail.co.uk/sport/other-sport/motor-sport/16460258.kirkby-karter-dan-revved-up-for-shot-at-super-stardom/|title=Kirkby karter Dan revved up for shot at Super-stardom|website=The Mail}}</ref> Kieran Pepper, Oliver Dilks and Jake Calvert.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwemail.co.uk/sport/other-sport/junior-sport/16463928.barrow-teenager-is-the-karting-king-of-britain/|title=Barrow teenager is the karting king of Britain|website=The Mail}}</ref>\n\n===Other sports===\n\nBarrow is home to the [[Walney Terriers]] [[American Football]] club, formed in 2011 the club originally trained at Memorial Fields on Walney Island before establishing training grounds elsewhere in Barrow and Ulverston. The Terriers play in the North West conference of the [[British American Football Association|BAFA]]'s National League alongside the likes of the [[Manchester Titans]] and [[Merseyside Nighthawks]].\n\nOne of the town's most notable annual sporting events is the [[Keswick to Barrow]] (K2B), a {{convert|40|mi|km|adj=on|sigfig=1}} walking and running event that has taken place every year since 1967 between [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]] and Barrow. The event has raised millions for charity and regularly sees in excess of 3,000 participants.<ref name=\"K2B\">{{cite web|title=About The Walk|publisher=Keswick to Barrow|date=|url=https://www.keswick2barrow.co.uk/about.asp|accessdate=3 May 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219014716/http://www.keswick2barrow.co.uk/about.asp|archivedate=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarrow Born Orienteer and Fell Runner Carl Hill was selected to carry the olympic torch for a stage through Morecambe in the buildup to the 2012 summer Olympics. He was nominated for this honor by his father David Hill who was proud of his sons accomplishments in running for England and Great Britain in Orienteering whilst also provided a large portion of his time to getting kids into sport.\n\n==Culture==\nBarrow, although one of the country's smallest local authorities, contains a wealth of natural and built heritage assets, which includes 274 [[Listed building|Listed Buildings]] and four [[Site of Special Scientific Interest|SSSIs]]. The 2016 Heritage Index formed by the [[Royal Society of Arts]] and the [[Heritage Lottery Fund]] placed the borough as sixth highest of 325 English districts for \u2018assets\u2019 with especially high scores relating to nationally important landscape and natural heritage assets and industrial heritage assets.<ref name=HeritageIndex>{{cite web|url=https://www.thersa.org/action-and-research/rsa-projects/public-services-and-communities-folder/heritage-and-place/England/|title=Explore the Heritage Index for England|publisher=The Royal Society for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\n{{See also|Listed buildings in Barrow-in-Furness|List of tallest buildings and structures in Barrow-in-Furness}}\n{{Panorama\n | image      = File:Barrow Panorama 1 (June 17).jpg\n | caption    = View of Barrow looking south from the [[Barrow Hematite Steel Company#Legacy|Slag Bank]] including (left to right) Fells of the [[Lake District]], [[Thorncliffe Cemetery and Crematorium|Thorncliffe Crematorium]], [[Ormsgill]], [[Holker Street]], [[Hindpool]], [[St. James' Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. James' Church]], [[Piel Castle]], the [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|Town Hall]], BAE Systems Central Yard Facility and [[Devonshire Dock Hall]], the new Barrow Police Station, [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]], [[Walney Bridge]] and Walney Channel, [[Vickerstown]], the [[Irish Sea]], [[Walney Wind Farm|Walney]] and [[Ormonde Wind Farm]]s and [[Barrow/Walney Island Airport]]\n | height     = 250\n}}\n{{Panorama\n | image      = File:Barrow panorama from Walney July 2017.jpg\n | caption    = View of Barrow looking east across Walney Channel including (left to right) Fells of the [[Lake District]], Slag Bank, Furness College, St. James' Church, the [[Dock Museum]], [[Devonshire Dock Hall]], BAE Systems Central Yard Facility and [[Walney Bridge]]\n | height     = 250\n}}\n[[File:Vickerstown and Walney Channel.jpg|thumb|right|[[Vickerstown]], a [[model village]] built on Walney Island around 1900]]\n[[File:Barrowterracota.png|thumb|right|Red brick and terracotta were popular building materials at the turn of the 20th century in Barrow \u2013 a style which is imitated to this day]]\n\nBarrow is one of Britain's few planned towns, and the spacious tree-lined avenues within the oldest parts of the town (including Central Barrow, Hindpool and Salthouse) are more akin to the layout of a much larger city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enjoyengland.com/destinations/find/englands-northwest/cumbria/barrow-in-furness.aspx |title=Destination guide for Barrow-in-Furness |accessdate=8 August 2007 |publisher=Enjoy England | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070711101803/http://www.enjoyengland.com/destinations/find/englands-northwest/cumbria/barrow-in-furness.aspx| archivedate= 11 July 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> The town centre is distinguished by its [[Victorian era|Victorian]] and [[Edwardian era]] civic buildings, such as the [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|Town Hall]], [[Barrow-in-Furness Main Public Library|Main Public Library]], former [[Nan Tait Centre|Technical School]], former [[Barrow-in-Furness Central Fire Station|Central Fire Station]], [[Salvation Army]] Building, [[Custom House, Barrow-in-Furness|Custom House]], [[National Westminster Bank, Barrow-in-Furness|National Westminster Bank]], [[The Duke of Edinburgh Hotel]], [[St. George's Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. George's Church]], [[St. Mary of Furness Roman Catholic Church|St. Mary's RC Church]] and [[St. James' Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. James' Church]]. Oppositely, several distinctive buildings have been demolished in Barrow since the mid-20th century as a result of neglect or war damage, amongst the most iconic are [[Abbot's Wood, Cumbria|Abbots Wood]], [[Barrow-in-Furness railway station|Barrow Central Railway Station]], [[Infield House]], [[St. George's Square, Barrow-in-Furness#North Lonsdale Hospital|North Lonsdale Hospital]], [[Scotch Buildings]] and the Waverley Hotel. Lancaster architects [[Sharpe, Paley and Austin]] were prolific throughout the development of Barrow. A number of Barrow's landmark buildings were constructed from locally sourced sandstone, evident from the high number of brown and red coloured stone buildings in the town. Similar materials were used in a number of local buildings in the early 20th century, and often accompanied by terracotta. There are also an increasing number of modern office buildings as well as the shipyard's construction halls which dominate much of Barrow's skyline. Despite much of Barrow having been constructed from the late 19th to mid 20th centuries, architectural styles vary greatly across the town from the [[Art Deco]] [[John Whinnerah Institute]] to the [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine style]] [[St. John's Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. John's Church]], [[Elizabethan architecture|Neo-Elizabethan]] [[Abbey House, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey House]] and [[Tudor Revival architecture|Tudor Revival]] [[Vickerstown]] estate.\n\nBarrow has 8 [[Grade I listed buildings]], 15 [[Listed building|Grade II*]] and 249 [[Grade II]] buildings. The majority of Grade I listed buildings and structures are in and around the Furness Abbey complex while many Grade II* listed buildings in the town are 19th century tenements on Barrow Island including the [[Devonshire Buildings]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2758 |title=Listed Buildings |accessdate=16 August 2007 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030802/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2758 |archivedate=28 September 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> There are a number of [[Conservation Area (United Kingdom)|Conservation Areas]] across Barrow named as such for their architectural or historical significance, they include [[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]], [[Biggar, Cumbria|Biggar]], [[Central Barrow]], [[Furness Abbey]], [[North Scale]], North and South [[Vickerstown]] and [[St. George's Square, Barrow-in-Furness|St. George's Square]].<ref name=Conservation>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=1696|title=Conservation Areas in the Borough|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|accessdate=9 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121123213335/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=1696|archivedate=23 November 2012}}</ref> Historically Barrow's skyline was dominated by shipyard cranes and industrial chimneys, although little evidence of this remains in the present day with the last [[Crane (machine)#Hammerhead crane|hammerhead crane]] \u2013 the iconic yellow crane of [[Buccleuch Dock]] \u2013 being dismantled in 2011, despite calls for listing status like the smaller [[Titan Clydebank]] in Glasgow. The tallest building in Barrow is [[Devonshire Dock Hall]] at {{convert|51|m|ft|0}}. Also worth of note are the turbines of [[Ormonde Wind Farm]] located just off the coast of Barrow which stand at {{convert|152|m|ft|0}}.\n\nIn terms of housing, the majority of dwellings in Barrow are Victorian [[Terraced house|terraces]]. At 47.0% of local housing stock in 2011, the figure is much higher than England's average of 24.5%. 29.7% of dwellings are [[semi-detached]], 12.09% [[Single-family detached home|detached]] and 10.2% flats, maisonettes or apartments.<ref name=Housing>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=7&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1365528720388&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2570|title=Accommodation Type \u2013 Households, 2011|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref> Great variety in housing styles is a feature across central Barrow, Barrow Island, Hindpool, and Vickerstown.  Most were built around a [[Grid plan|grid design]] in accordance with plans drawn up by James Ramsden.\n\n===Arts===\n\n'''Music'''<br />\nBarrow has produced several musical performers of note. They include [[Thomas Round]], a singer and actor in D'Oyly Carte productions of [[Savoy Opera]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://diamond.boisestate.edu/GaS/whowaswho/R/RoundThomas.htm |title=Thomas Round |accessdate=7 August 2007 |publisher=Boise State University |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060903104943/http://diamond.boisestate.edu/gas/whowaswho/R/RoundThomas.htm |archive-date=3 September 2006 |url-status = dead}}</ref> as well as [[Glenn Cornick]], the original bass guitarist in the rock band [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.j-tull.com/musicians/pastmembers/glenncornick.html |title=Glenn Cornick |accessdate=7 August 2007 |publisher=The Official Jethro Tull Website |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815135747/http://www.j-tull.com/musicians/pastmembers/glenncornick.html |archivedate=15 August 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> Paul MacKenzie, bass player with 1980s [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]]-based thrash metal band [[Xentrix]], is from Barrow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metalist.co.il/interviewprivate.asp?id=141&lang=eng |title=Metalist Magazine |accessdate=10 January 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716200952/http://www.metalist.co.il/interviewprivate.asp?id=141&lang=eng |archivedate=16 July 2011  }}</ref> More recently, hip-hop DJ and record producer [[Aim (musician)|Aim]] has had considerable commercial success.<ref>{{Cite news| first=David | last=Sue | title=Superstar DJ continues to Aim high | date=23 June 2006 | publisher=Guardian Media Group | url =http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/rock_and_pop/s/216/216434_superstar_dj_continues_to_aim_high.html | work =[[Manchester Evening News]] | accessdate =7 August 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930165611/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/rock_and_pop/s/216/216434_superstar_dj_continues_to_aim_high.html| archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref>[[File:The Forum, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|left|[[Forum 28|The Forum]], Barrow's largest theatre and arts venue]]\n\n'''Expressive arts'''<br />\nSeveral notables in Art and Literature have come from Barrow. Artist [[Keith Tyson]], the 2002 [[Turner Prize]] winner, was born in nearby [[Ulverston]], attended the Barrow-in-Furness College of Engineering and worked at the then [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering|VSEL]] shipyard.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://collection.britishcouncil.org/collection/artist/5/19092 |title=Keith Tyson Biography |accessdate=4 August 2007 |publisher=[[British Council]] |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629202045/http://collection.britishcouncil.org/collection/artist/5/19092 |archivedate=29 June 2011  }}</ref> [[Constance Spry]], the author and florist who revolutionised interior design in the 1930s, and 1940s, moved to the town with her son Anthony during World War I to work as a welfare supervisor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.designmuseum.org/design/constance-spry |title=Constance Spry / Florist, Author + Social Reformer (1886\u20131960) |accessdate=4 August 2007 |publisher=Design Museum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070806082527/http://www.designmuseum.org/design/constance-spry |archivedate=6 August 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> [[Peter Purves]], later a [[Blue Peter]] presenter, began his acting career with 2 years as a member of the Renaissance Theatre Company at the town's Her Majesty's Theatre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peterpurves.com/inthetheatre.html |title=Peter Purves in the Theatre |accessdate=4 August 2007 |publisher=peterpurves.com | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070911234336/http://www.peterpurves.com/inthetheatre.html| archivedate= 11 September 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-20th century, Barrow contained a wealth of theatres/cinemas including the Coliseum, Electric Theatre, Essoldo, Her Majesty's Theatre, Hippodrome, Pavilion, [[Ritz Cinema, Barrow-in-Furness|Ritz]], [[Roxy Cinema, Barrow-in-Furness|Roxy]], Royalty Theatre and Tivoli. All but the Pavilion and Roxy have since been demolished, most recently in 2004 with the demolition of the Apollo (formerly the Ritz). The Canteen Media & Arts Centre \u2013 known simply as \"The Canteen\" \u2013 and [[Forum 28|The Forum]] are now the main venues for theatre, while the [[Vue Cinemas|Vue Cinema]] in [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Hollywood Park|Hollywood Park]] is the only cinema in the town.\n\n'''Literature'''<br />\nIn fictional works, Barrow and [[Vickerstown]] on [[Walney Island]] featured in children's show ''[[The Railway Series]]'', which developed into ''[[Thomas the Tank Engine]]'', as the point where the fictional [[Sodor (fictional island)|Island of Sodor]] connected to mainland Britain and the national rail network.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.storybookengland.com/authors.php?form_id=3413682892|title= Thomas the Tank Engine books|accessdate= 25 August 2007|publisher= Storybook England|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070921151657/http://www.storybookengland.com/authors.php?form_id=3413682892|archivedate= 21 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA number of the [[Lake Poets]] have referred to locations in present day Barrow, with one notable example being [[William Wordsworth]]'s 1805 autobiographical poem ''[[The Prelude]]'' which describes his visits to Furness Abbey. The Portuguese poet [[Fernando Pessoa]] wrote a series of [[sonnet]]s called \"Barrow-on-Furness\" (sic). His \"heteronym\" [[\u00c1lvaro de Campos]] lived in Barrow when he was studying ship engineering, but Pessoa himself had never visited, and mistakenly assumed that \"Furness\" was the name of a river.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/obra-visor/hispania--11/html/|title= \u00c1lvaro de Campos's Geography|accessdate=1 January 2012|publisher=Hispania }}</ref> According to narrative exposition in Chapter five of [[Dorothy L. Sayers]]' 1926 novel ''[[Clouds of Witness]]'', Inspector Charles Parker, Lord Peter Wimsey's friend and eventual brother-in-law, attended Barrow-in-Furness Grammar School. Renowned novelist [[D. H. Lawrence]] was in Barrow during the outbreak of World War I and wrote about his experiences in the town. The 2015 novel ''[[Career of Evil]]'' by [[J. K. Rowling]]'s pseudonym Robert Galbraith was parially set in Barrow.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/oct/21/career-of-evil-by-robert-galbraith-review |title=Career of Evil by Robert Galbraith review \u2013 a daft but enjoyable hunt for a serial killer |accessdate=20 November 2015 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] }}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n[[File:Portland Walk.jpg|thumb|right|[[Portland Walk Shopping Centre|Portland Walk]], one of Barrow's primary retail areas]]\n\n====Newspapers====\nThere is one paid-for evening daily paper, ''[[The Mail (Cumbria)|The Mail]]''. There is also a weekly freesheet called the ''Advertiser'', which is delivered to most households in the Furness area.\n\n====Radio====\nBarrow is served by one commercial radio station, [[Heart North West]], which broadcasts from Manchester and serves the area around [[Morecambe Bay]]. Another commercial station, [[Abbey FM]], ceased broadcasting in February 2009 when it went into administration.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Abbey FM ceases broadcasting| url= http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.4343.2| accessdate= 24 February 2009| date= 30 January 2009| work= Radio Today| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090205190014/http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.4343.2| archivedate= 5 February 2009|url-status = dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> The BBC's local radio service is [[BBC Radio Cumbria]], who have studio facilities in the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/content/articles/2005/10/19/barrow_office_feature.shtml |title=BBC \u2013 Cumbria \u2013 Local Radio \u2013 The Barrow Office. |accessdate=16 August 2007 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> .  Barrow and the Furness area is served by local community radio CANDOFM 106.3FM in the local area and also available online.  With plans to expand further.  CandoFM is located in Cooke Studios, Abbey Road, Barrow-in-Furness and run by 50+ volunteers providing local information as well as an eclectic mix of shows.\n\n====Television====\nBarrow lies in the [[Granada TV]] \u2013 [[North West England]] region with the main signal coming from the [[Winter Hill transmitting station|Winter Hill]] transmitter near [[Bolton]]. There is also a relay transmitter at [[Millom]] whose signal can be received in the northern end of the town.\n\nVarious television personalities were born in the district. Dave Myers was a biker born in Barrow, and found fame as one half of television cookery duo [[the Hairy Bikers]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Rosanna |last=Greenstreet |title=My Home: Dave Myers of the Hairy Bikers |date=10 May 2006 |publisher=Independent News & Media |url=http://money.independent.co.uk/property/homes/article363011.ece |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=7 August 2007 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927211243/http://money.independent.co.uk/property/homes/article363011.ece |archivedate=27 September 2007  }}</ref> [[Karen Taylor (comedian)|Karen Taylor]] is a TV comedian best known for her BBC Three sketch show ''[[Touch Me, I'm Karen Taylor]]''.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Karen's sketch show opens | date=11 June 2007 | publisher=CN Group | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508863 | work =North West Evening Mail | accessdate =25 July 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926212137/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508863| archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> [[Steve Dixon (newsreader)|Steve Dixon]] is a newsreader for Sky News,<ref>{{Cite news| first=Cassandra | last=Jardine | title='Diabetes is not as simple as it appears' | date=3 November 2003 | url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global/main.jhtml?xml=/global/2003/11/03/hdiab03.xml |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London | accessdate =7 August 2007 }}</ref> while [[Nigel Kneale]] was a well-known film and television scriptwriter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article622130.ece|title=Nigel Kneale|work=The Times |location=London |date=2 November 2006|accessdate=8 February 2007|page=71  | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070211131713/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article622130.ece| archivedate= 11 February 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> The UK's top Thai demo chef and celebrity 'Chef Ooy' has also lived and worked in Barrow for the last 25 years.\n\n[[File:Barrow-in-Furness statue collage.jpg|thumb|left|Barrow has a large number of public works of art, including statues of prominent political figures and sporting personalities]]\nWartime diarist and local housewife [[Nella Last]]'s memoirs were adapted for television, with parts of the town used in filming. The resulting programme, ''[[Housewife, 49]]'', written by and starring comedian [[Victoria Wood]], was broadcast by ITV in 2006. It won two [[British Academy Television Awards 2007|BAFTA]] awards \u2013 one for Best Single Drama, the other for Best Actress (Victoria Wood).<ref>{{Cite news| first=Ian | last=Wylie | title=Victoria plays it straight | date=1 December 2006 | publisher=Guardian Media Group | url =http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/film_and_tv/s/229/229723_victoria_plays_it_straight.html | work =Manchester Evening News | accessdate =5 August 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=481129|title= Top Award for Diary Drama Set in Barrow|accessdate=14 August 2007 |date= 27 March 2007|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926211416/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=481129| archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref>\nCITV children's show [[The Treacle People]] had two villains named Barrow and Furness.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.channel4.com/learning/microsites/T/treacle/series2.html | publisher =Channel 4 | accessdate=10 May 2007 | title=Treacle People microsite }}</ref> Myles Wright also was born in Barrow and lived in the nearby village of Marton.\n\nBarrow-in-Furness is the connection between England and the fictional Island of Sodor in the [[Thomas the Tank Engine]] TV series, as well as in the Railway Series books by the [[Wilbert Awdry|Rev. W. Awdry]], on which the TV series is based.\n\n===Dialect and accent===\n{{main|Barrovian}}\nFurness is unique within Cumbria and the local dialect and accent is fairly [[Lancashire dialect and accent|Lancashire]]-orientated. Until 1974 Furness was an [[exclave]] of Lancashire. As with [[Liverpool]] for example however, the ''Barrovian'' dialect has been influenced by large numbers of settlers from various regions. During the town's rapid growth from 1860 onwards, thousands came to Barrow from [[Scotland]], [[Ireland]], [[Wales]] and elsewhere in northern England. As [[Glasgow patter|Glaswegian]] and [[Geordie]] dialects mingled in Barrow numerous more migrated from Lancashire and other parts of England which in effect created the noticeably [[Northern England English|Northern]] ''Barrovian'' dialect. In general the ''Barrovian'' accent tends to drop certain letters (including ''H'' and ''T'').\n\n===Nightlife===\n[[File:The Crow's Nest Pub - geograph.org.uk - 1559003.jpg|thumb|The Crow's Nest on Barrow Island, a typical Victorian era public house]]\nThere are many pubs and [[working men's club]]s in Barrow. Barrow has fourteen of the latter, one of the highest number per capita of any British town.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2008/10/06/barrow-in-furness-the-working-class-capital-of-britain-115875-20779478/|title=Barrow-in-Furness: The working class capital of Britain|first=Kate|last=Jackson|date=5 October 2008|publisher=}}</ref> There are also many bars and clubs found primarily in [[Central Barrow|Barrow town centre]] on [[Duke Street, Barrow-in-Furness|Duke Street]] and Cornwallis Street. Popular venues on Duke Street include the following bars: Jefferson's, the Buddha Bar, Bar Cairo and the Drawing Room. They did have a [[Yates's]] but the building was deemed unsafe and has since been demolished. Cornwallis Street \u2013 often dubbed the ''\"[[Gaza Strip]]\"'' by locals \u2013 is currently undergoing a multi-million pound renovation with the former Martini's being the flagship renovation into Club M. Other clubs on Cornwallis Street include: Kavanna's, O'Sullivan's and Skint. Between 2004 and 2010 Barrow was home to one of North West England's largest nightclubs, the {{formatnum:2500}}-capacity Blue Lagoon occupied the entire hull of the former Danish ferry [[Princess Selandia]], which has now left the town.<ref>http://www.gardinersecurity.co.uk/articles.asp?pID=1&id=314{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Barrow's largest nightclub is now [[Roxy Cinema, Barrow-in-Furness|Manhattans]], which opened on Cavendish Street in late 2011.\n\n===Food===\nA traditional favourite food in Barrow is the [[pie]], and particularly the [[meat and potato pie]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Tarbuck|first1=Martin|title=The 10 Greatest Pies In Britain|url=http://sabotagetimes.com/life/10-greatest-pies-britain|magazine=Sabotage Times|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> [[Pie shop]]s are common, and Green's of Jarrow Street is noted as a favourite of Barrow-born celebrity chef [[Dave Myers (presenter)|Dave Myers]] <ref>{{cite web|title=The Green's Green Food of Home|url=http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/the-green-s-green-s-food-of-home-1.158252|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721042202/http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/the-green-s-green-s-food-of-home-1.158252|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref> and journalist Martin Tarbuck, who declared them to be Britain's best pies in a book dedicated to the subject.<ref>{{cite news|title=Upper crust: Writer scoffs his way to a winner in search for Britain's favourite pie|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/upper-crust-writer-scoffs-way-5282206|newspaper=Daily Mirror|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nBarrow was also the home of [[soft-drink]] company Marsh's, which produced a distinctive [[sarsaparilla (soft drink)|sarsaparilla]]-flavoured fizzy drink known as ''Sass''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mystery that threatens cult soft drink|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Mystery+that+threatens+cult+soft+drink.-a060206032|publisher=Birmingham Post & Mail Ltd|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> Marsh's was purchased by Purity Soft Drinks of Birmingham in 1993, and the company stopped producing Sass in 1999. Remaining bottles have subsequently sold for high prices as a collector's item.<ref>{{cite web|title=Record Bid for Bottle of Sass|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/record-bid-for-bottle-of-sass-1.486029|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721002701/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/record-bid-for-bottle-of-sass-1.486029|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref> A new product, labelled \"Barrow Sass\", was launched in 2014 in a bid to replicate traditional Sass.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sass in the Miz at Barrow Cocktail Bar|url=http://www.in-cumbria.com/sass-in-the-mix-at-barrow-cocktail-bar-1.1219999|publisher=North-West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721070012/http://www.in-cumbria.com/sass-in-the-mix-at-barrow-cocktail-bar-1.1219999|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref> The coasts around Barrow have rich [[Cockle (bivalve)|cockle]] beds from which cockles have traditionally been gathered, although numbers have been low following intensive gathering during the early 2000s, in the run-up to the [[2004 Morecambe Bay cockling disaster]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Restraint needed to restore cockles|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Restraint-needed-to-restore-cockles-5387c86f-f860-4811-b37e-c5f677214e2c-ds|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721104102/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Restraint-needed-to-restore-cockles-5387c86f-f860-4811-b37e-c5f677214e2c-ds|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cocklers' gangmaster made \u00a3100 a day|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/jan/24/ukcrime1|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> One of England's few remaining [[Oyster farming|Oyster farms]] can also be found located in the [[Biggar, Cumbria|Biggar]] area of Walney. Traditional [[Cumberland sausages]] are less associated with Barrow itself than the rest of Cumbria, but are readily available from the surrounding rural area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Butchers' campaign to protect sausage in Cumbria|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Butchers-campaign-to-protect-sausage-in-Cumbria-6701513e-0a11-4974-a183-72c55fb022ee-ds|publisher=North-West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721080507/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Butchers-campaign-to-protect-sausage-in-Cumbria-6701513e-0a11-4974-a183-72c55fb022ee-ds|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Cumbria has produced a number of famed dishes and is home to countless [[Michelin Guide]] restaurants, one of which is located in Dalton.\n\n==Social issues==\n\n=== Lifestyle ===\n[[File:Parade Street, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|right|The majority of housing within the town is [[Terraced house|terraced]], built for working-class families]]\nHaving emerged as mixture of working-class cultures from across Britain and Ireland in the 19th century, subsequent low levels of migration and a continued tradition of industrial employment mean that Barrow's culture still reflects many of the traditions of the British [[Working Class]].<ref name=\"Blue Cap\">{{cite news|last1=Davies|first1=Caroline|title=Barrow, capital of blue-collar Britain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2008/oct/05/1|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> In September 2008, Barrow was named as the most working-class location in the United Kingdom, based on a series of measures devised to judge the lifestyle of the people.<ref name=workingclass>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/1.244620|title=Have your say on Barrow's flat cap image|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=6 October 2010|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201022016/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/1.244620|archivedate=1 December 2008}}</ref> The research was carried out by Locallife.co.uk which determined that there is a [[Fish and chips|fish and chip shop]], [[working men's club]], [[bookmaker]]s or [[Trade union|trade union office]] for every 2,917 people ([[Crewe]], [[Doncaster]], [[Wolverhampton]] and [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] completed the top five of 'the most working class places in Britain').<ref name=workingclass2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2008/10/06/barrow-in-furness-the-working-class-capital-of-britain-115875-20779478/|title=Barrow-in-Furness: The working class capital of Britain|publisher=The Mirror|accessdate=6 October 2010}}</ref> This is in direct contrast to the 1870s, when a developing Barrow had more [[Aristocracy (class)|aristocrats]] per head of the population than anywhere else in the country.<ref name=workingclass/>\n\nIn the 2015 [[Deprivation index|Indices of Deprivation]], Barrow was ranked as the 44th most deprived district in England (out of a total of 326).<ref name=Deprivation>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/464464/File_10_ID2015_Local_Authority_District_Summaries.xlsx|title=Indices of Deprivation 2015 Local Authority Summaries|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> The equivalent figures for 2007 and 2010 stood at 29th most deprived and 32nd most deprived respectively.<ref name=Deprivation2>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=1572|title=Indices of Deprivation 2010|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=11 September 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911203616/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=1572|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref> The Indices of Deprivation is based on income, employment, education, health, crime and barriers to housing and services and living environment. Within these subcategories, most notably Barrow ranked as the 5th most deprived in terms of health deprivation and disability, and in huge contrast, 324th most deprived in terms of access to housing and services (i.e. 3rd least deprived).<ref name=Deprivation/> In the 2010 Indices of Deprivation, the majority of areas in Barrow Island, Central, Hindpool, Ormsgill were amongst the 3% most deprived areas in the country, while large parts of suburban Barrow including Newbarns and Roose were amongst the 25% of least deprived areas in England.<ref name=Deprivation2/>\n\n=== Health ===\n[[File:Furness General.jpg|thumb|left|[[Furness General Hospital]], the primary hospital for Barrow and South West Cumbria]]\nThe principal hospital in Barrow is [[Furness General Hospital]], operated by the [[University Hospitals of Morecambe Bay NHS Trust]] and located on the outskirts of the town. As of July 2010 there were 12 NHS GP practices/doctors' surgeries and 5 NHS dental surgeries in Barrow.<ref name=NHSsearch>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/servicedirectories/pages/servicesearch.aspx|title=Find and choose services|publisher=[[National Health Service (England)|NHS]]|accessdate=22 July 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100722013546/http://www.nhs.uk/servicedirectories/Pages/ServiceSearch.aspx| archivedate= 22 July 2010 |url-status = live}}</ref> The [[life expectancy]] for males in Barrow is 77.1 years (compared to the England average of 79.5) and 81.5 years for females (compared to the national average of 83.2).<ref name=NHSpublication>{{Cite web|url= http://fingertipsreports.phe.org.uk/health-profiles/2016/e07000027.pdf |title=Barrow-in-Furness Health Profile|publisher=NHS|year=2016|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref> A 2016 [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]] in depth publication on health in Barrow indicated that the population of Barrow is by most measures in a worse state than the national average.<ref name=NHSpublication/> Indicators such as hospital stays for alcohol related harm, excessive weight, diabetes, smoking related death and self-harm are significantly worse than the England average. However, a number of indicators are similar to the average or are significantly better, including rates of homelesness, STI transmission and road deaths.\"<ref name=NHSpublication/> Barrow has the tenth worst rate of [[Incapacity Benefit]] claimants for [[Mental disorder|mental illness]] in the country.\n\n=== Crime ===\n[[File:Barrow Police Station June 2015.JPG|thumb|Barrow's new main police station (under construction) in June 2015]]\nPolicing is by [[Cumbria Constabulary]], which alongside the county of Cumbria was formed in 1974. Previously the town was policed by Barrow-in-Furness Borough Police. Barrow previously had one full-time police station in Market Street in the [[Central Barrow|Central]] ward. A new multi-million pound building was built on James Freel Close on Channelside in [[Hindpool]] and is the town's only police station, with extra jail cells and improved facilities. Several consecutive annual publications by Cumbria Constabulary entitled the 'Cumbria Community Safety Strategic Assessment' have stated that overall crime in Barrow is declining, with some indicators far better than the national average.<ref name=Crimeobserv>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cumbriaobservatory.org.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/671/4674/5172/41260152144.pdf|title=Cumbria Community Safety Strategic Assessment|publisher=Cumbria Intelligence Observatory|year=2012|accessdate=9 September 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910200016/http://www.cumbriaobservatory.org.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/671/4674/5172/41260152144.pdf|archivedate=10 September 2014}}</ref> Despite this, crime levels as a whole are higher than the national average: 2013 statistics show crime levels in the borough as the 16th worst in the UK; most notably, Barrow has amongst the worst rates of alcohol misuse in the country.<ref name=CrimeStats>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/crime-statistics-for-barrow-in-furness-3217045|title=Crime statistics for Barrow-in-Furness|publisher=Cumbria Constabulary|year=2013|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> Between July and December 2013 Barrow saw an average of 7.39 crimes per 100 of the population; the UK average was 6.57.<ref name=CrimeStats/> Incidents of anti-social behaviour stood at 7.83 per 100 in Barrow, cf 5.02 in the UK.<ref name=CrimeStats/> Burglary averaged 0.53 per 100 in 2013 while the national average was 1.00 per 100. Robbery averaged 0.02 in Barrow and 0.07 nationwide, shoplifting 0.72 and 0.53 and vehicle crime at 0.31 and 0.58.<ref name=CrimeStats/> Violent crimes and sexual offences occurred at a rate of 1.70 per 100, significantly higher than UK average of 1.06 and ranking the area as the 29th worst out of 348 in the country.<ref name=CrimeStats/> Crime rates remain the highest in deprived areas of inner wards such as Central and Hindpool.<ref name=Crimeobserv/>\n\nSince November 2019 [[Ministry of Defence Police]] have been based at the [[BAE Systems]] Shipyard.\n\n==Education==\n{{See also|List of schools in Barrow-in-Furness}}\n[[File:Furness College campus, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|The Copper Box building at [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]]'s Channelside campus]]\n[[File:Furness Academy newbuild2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Furness Academy]] was established in 2009 and opened a new site in 2013]]\nEducation in the state-funded sector includes fifteen [[primary school]]s, five [[infant school]]s, five [[junior school]]s and many nurseries. The three [[secondary school]]s in the town are: [[Furness Academy]], [[St. Bernard's Catholic High School]] and [[Walney School]]. [[Chetwynde School]] is an all-through school for children aged 4 to 18. Formerly an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent school]], Chetwynde became a state-funded [[Free school (England)|free school]] in 2014.\n\nIn the further education sector there is one college, [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]]. Furness College merged with [[Barrow Sixth Form College]] in 2016 forming the largest college in Cumbria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barrow colleges merger hailed \"exciting new era for education\"|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/Barrow-colleges-merger-hailed-exciting-new-era-for-education-c401988c-92d0-4bde-9806-3b13892705b3-ds|website=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> Technical and professional qualifications are delivered at the Channelside campus, with A' levels delivered at the Rating Lane campus, the home of the former sixth form college. Although there is no [[higher education]] institution based in Barrow, Furness College offers several higher apprenticeships, [[foundation degree]]s, [[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor's]] and [[Master's degree|Master's]] programmes accredited by the [[University of Cumbria]], [[University of Lancaster]] and the [[University of Central Lancashire]].<ref>{{cite web|title=University Education|url=http://www.furness.ac.uk/course-index/university-education|publisher=Furness College|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe town's main library is the [[Barrow-in-Furness Main Public Library|Central Library]] in [[Ramsden Square]], situated near the town centre.<ref name=\"Library\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=163|title= Libraries and Archives|accessdate= 18 August 2007|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070827135601/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=163|archivedate= 27 August 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The library was established in 1882 in a room near the town hall, and moved to its current premises in 1922. A branch of the County Archive Service, opened in 1979 and containing many of the town's archives, is located within adjoining premises,<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.familia.org.uk/services/england/cumbria_barrow.html|title= Cumbria County Council (Barrow)|accessdate=18 August 2007 |publisher= Familia| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070906141740/http://www.familia.org.uk/services/england/cumbria_barrow.html| archivedate= 6 September 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> whilst until 1991 the library also housed the Furness Museum, a forerunner of the Dock Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/museum_history.htm|title= Museum History|accessdate=18 August 2007 |format= Flash|publisher= [[Dock Museum]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070805222430/http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/museum_history.htm| archivedate = 5 August 2007}}</ref> Smaller branch libraries are currently provided at [[Walney]], [[Roose]] and [[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]]. Known librarian Michael Wilson originates in Barrow-in-Furness. Michael Wilson is currently leader of the Collection Logistics Alpha Team at Cambridge University Library.<ref name=\"Library\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cumbria}}\n* [[Barrovian]]\n* [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]\n* [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)]]\n* [[List of people from Barrow-in-Furness]]\n* [[List of ships and submarines built in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n* [[Listed buildings in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n* [[List of places of worship in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Barrow-in-Furness}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Barrow-in-Furness}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n{{Cumbria}}\n{{Barrow-in-Furness topics}}\n{{Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrow-In-Furness}}\n[[Category:Barrow-in-Furness| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Districts of Barrow-in-Furness| ]]\n[[Category:Furness]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns of the Irish Sea]]\n[[Category:Planned communities in England]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1867]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in North West England]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Morecambe Bay]]\n[[Category:1867 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Unparished areas in Cumbria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|official_name            = Barrow-in-Furness\n|other_name               =\n|native_name              =\n|nickname                 =\n|static_image_name        = Barrow montage2.jpg\n|static_image_caption     = Clockwise from the upper left: [[Central Barrow]] with the skyline of [[Blackpool]] also visible, [[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]], [[Walney Bridge]] and [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]], [[Furness Abbey]], [[Ramsden Square]], [[Dock Museum]] and [[Devonshire Dock Hall|DDH]],  [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|Barrow Town Hall]] and [[St. Mary of Furness Roman Catholic Church|St. Mary's Church]]\n|static_image_2_name      = Barrow in Furness Town Arms.jpg\n|static_image_2_width     = \n|static_image_2_caption   = [[Coat of arms of Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|coordinates              = {{coord|54.1108|-3.2261|display=inline,title}}\n| population              = 56,745\n| population_ref          = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])\n|population_demonym       = [[Barrovian]]\n|shire_district           = [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|shire_county             = [[Cumbria]]\n|region                   = North West England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]]\n|post_town                = BARROW-IN-FURNESS\n|postcode_district        = LA13, LA14\n|postcode_area            = LA\n|dial_code                = 01229\n|os_grid_reference        = SD198690\n|london_distance          = {{convert|297|mi|km|0|abbr=on}}\n }}\n\n'''Barrow-in-Furness''' is a town in [[Cumbria]], North-West England. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] part of [[Lancashire]], it was incorporated as a [[municipal borough]] in 1867 and merged with [[Dalton-in-Furness Urban District]] in 1974 to form the [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]. At the tip of the [[Furness|Furness peninsula]], close to the [[Lake District]], it is bordered by [[Morecambe Bay]], the [[Duddon Estuary]] and the [[Irish Sea]]. In 2011, Barrow's population was 57,000, making it the second largest urban area in Cumbria after [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], although it is geographically closer to the whole of Lancashire and most of [[Merseyside]]. Natives of Barrow, as well as the local dialect, are known as [[Barrovian]].<ref>{{Cite journal| first=Russell | last=Jenkins | title=Chocolate blog sends town into meltdown | date=22 December 2006 |journal=The Times | pages=15 | postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Middle Ages]], Barrow was a small [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]] within the parish of Dalton-in-Furness with [[Furness Abbey]], now on the outskirts of the modern-day town, controlling the local economy before its [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|dissolution]] in 1537. The iron prospector [[Henry Schneider]] arrived in Furness in 1839 and, with other investors, opened the [[Furness Railway]] in 1846 to transport iron ore and slate from local mines to the coast. Further [[hematite]] deposits were discovered, of sufficient size to develop factories for smelting and exporting steel. For a period of the late 19th century, the [[Barrow Hematite Steel Company]]-owned steelworks was the world's largest.<ref>[http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/ Barrow Steelworks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819160207/http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/ |date=19 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBarrow's location and the availability of steel allowed the town to develop into a significant producer of naval vessels, a shift that was accelerated during [[World War I]] and the local yard's specialisation in submarines. The original iron- and steel-making enterprises closed down after [[World War II]], leaving [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering|Vickers]] shipyard as Barrow's main industry and employer. Several [[Royal Navy]] [[Royal Navy Fleet Flagship|flagships]], the vast majority of its [[Nuclear submarine#Royal Navy of the United Kingdom|nuclear submarines]] as well as numerous other naval vessels, [[ocean liner]]s and [[oil tanker]]s have been manufactured at the facility.\n\nThe end of the [[Cold War]] and subsequent [[peace dividend|decrease in military spending]] saw high unemployment in the town through lack of contracts; despite this, the [[BAE Systems]] shipyard remains operational as the UK's largest by workforce and is undergoing a major expansion associated with the {{sclass-|Dreadnought|submarine|0}} submarine programme.<ref name=\"unemployment\" /> Today Barrow is a hub for energy generation and handling. Offshore wind farms form one of the highest concentrations of turbines in the world, including [[Walney Wind Farm|the single largest]] with multiple operating bases in Barrow.<ref name=\"walneyextension\">[\u00a31bn Walney offshore wind farm is world's largest https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-45424559 \u00a31 billion Walney offshore wind farm is world's largest] ''BBC News'', 6 September 2018. Accessed: 6 September 2018.</ref>\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe name was originally that of an island, Barrai, which can be traced back to 1190. This was later renamed Old Barrow, recorded as Oldebarrey in 1537, and Old Barrow Insula and Barrohead in 1577. The island was then joined to the mainland and the town took its name. The name itself seems to mean \"island with promontory\", combining British ''barro-'' and Old Norse ''ey'', but it is more likely that [[Scandinavia]]n settlers simply accepted ''barro-'' as a meaningless name, and so added an explanatory [[Old Norse]] second element.<ref>{{Cite book|last= Mills|first= David|title= The Place Names of Lancashire|year= 1976|publisher= Batsford Books|location= London|isbn= 978-0-7134-3248-0}}</ref>\n\n===Nicknames===\nIn the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Barrow was nicknamed \"the English Chicago\" because of the sudden and rapid growth in its industry, economic stature and overall size.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdonline.co.uk/buildings/barrow-in-furness-kept-on-life-support-by-perpetual-warfare/5011365.article|title=Barrow-in-Furness: kept on life support by perpetual warfare|publisher=}}</ref> More recently the town has been dubbed the \"capital of [[Blue-collar worker|blue-collar]] Britain\" by the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', reflecting its strong working class identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?rlz=1T4ACAW_en___GB384&q=most+working+class+town|title=most working class town \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.com}}</ref> Barrow is also often jokingly referred to as being at the end of the longest [[cul-de-sac]] in the country because of its isolated location at the tip of the Furness peninsula.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-18853714|title=Five lesser-spotted things in the census|first=Lucy Townsend and Kathryn|last=Westcott|date=17 July 2012|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Timeline of Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n===Early history===\nBarrow and the surrounding area has been settled non-continuously for several millennia with evidence of [[Neolithic]] inhabitants on [[Walney Island]]. Despite a rich history of [[Roman Britain|Roman]] settlement across Cumbria and the discovery of related artefacts in the Barrow area, no buildings or structures have been found to support the idea of a functioning Roman community on the [[Furness]] peninsula.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roman Treasure|url=http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/Romans|publisher=Dock Museum|accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref> The [[Furness Hoard]] discovery of [[Viking]] silver coins and other artefacts in 2011 provided significant archaeological evidence of [[Norse activity in the British Isles|Norse]] settlement in the early 9th century. Several areas of Barrow including [[Yarlside]] and [[Ormsgill]], as well as \"Barrow\" and \"Furness\", have names of [[Old Norse]] origin. The [[Domesday Book]] of 1086 recorded the settlements of Hietun, Rosse and Hougenai, which are now the districts of [[Hawcoat]], [[Roose]] and [[Walney Island|Walney]] respectively.\n[[File:Furness Abbey, April 2010.jpg|thumb|right|[[Furness Abbey]], one of England's most powerful monasteries in the Middle Ages]]\n\nIn the [[Middle Ages]] the Furness peninsula was controlled by the [[Cistercian]] monks of the Abbey of St Mary of Furness, known as [[Furness Abbey]]. This was located in the \"Vale of Nightshade\", now on the outskirts of the town.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=150#abbey | title=Local history and heritage | publisher=Barrow Borough Council | accessdate=10 June 2007 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609195921/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=150#abbey | archivedate=9 June 2007 |url-status = dead| df=dmy-all }}</ref> Founded for the [[Congregation of Savigny|Savigniac order]], it was built on the orders of [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] in 1123. Soon after the abbey's foundation the monks discovered iron ore deposits, later to provide the basis for the Furness economy. These thin strata, close to the surface, were extracted through open cut workings,<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.cumbria-industries.org.uk/ironmining.htm | title=Iron Mining | publisher=Industries of Cumbria | accessdate=10 June 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070702101913/http://www.cumbria-industries.org.uk/ironmining.htm| archivedate= 2 July 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> which were then smelted by the monks.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Raymond|first1=Michael|title=A Forgotten Medieval Powerhouse: Furness Abbey|url=http://newhistories.group.shef.ac.uk/wordpress/wordpress/a-forgotten-medieval-powerhouse-furness-abbey/|publisher=New Histories Magazine|accessdate=3 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425033830/http://newhistories.group.shef.ac.uk/wordpress/wordpress/a-forgotten-medieval-powerhouse-furness-abbey/|archive-date=25 April 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref> The proceeds from mining, along with agriculture and fisheries, meant that by the 15th century the abbey had become the second richest and most powerful Cistercian abbey in England, after [[Fountains Abbey]] in Yorkshire.<ref>{{Cite web| author=English Heritage | title=Furness Abbey| publisher=English Heritage | url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/ConProperty.149 | accessdate=6 May 2007 }}</ref> The monks of Furness Abbey constructed a wooden tower on nearby [[Piel Island]] in 1212 which acted as their main trading point; it was twice invaded by the Scots, in 1316 and 1322. In 1327 [[Edward III of England|King Edward III]] gave Furness Abbey a licence to [[crenellate]] the tower, and a [[motte-and-bailey castle]] was built. However Barrow itself was just a hamlet in the parish of [[Dalton-in-Furness]], reliant on the land and sea for survival. Small quantities of iron and ore were exported from jetties on the channel separating the village from Walney Island. Amongst the oldest buildings in Barrow are several cottages and farmhouses in [[Newbarns]] (now a ward of the borough) which date back to the early 17th century; as well as [[Rampside Hall]], a [[Grade I listed]] building and the best-preserved in the town from the 1600s. Even as late as 1843 there were still only 32 dwellings, including two pubs.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/pdf/summary%20of%20plan%20areas.pdf | title=Plan of Barrow 1843 | publisher=Barrow Borough Council | format=[[PDF]] | accessdate=10 June 2007 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704111547/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/pdf/summary%20of%20plan%20areas.pdf | archivedate=4 July 2007 |url-status = dead| df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:Barrow Steelworks.jpg|thumb|left|[[Barrow Hematite Steel Company|Barrow Steelworks]] circa. 1877]]\nIn 1839 [[Henry Schneider]] arrived as a young speculator and dealer in iron, and he discovered large deposits of [[haematite]] in 1850. He and other investors founded the [[Furness Railway]], the first section of which opened in 1846, to transport the ore from the slate quarries at [[Kirkby-in-Furness]] and haematite mines at [[Lindal-in-Furness]] and [[Askam and Ireleth]] to a deep-water harbour near [[Roa Island]].<ref name=\"railway\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.furnessrailwaytrust.org.uk/frco.htm |title=History of the Furness Railway Company |publisher=The Furness Railway Trust |accessdate=8 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715153252/http://www.furnessrailwaytrust.org.uk/frco.htm |archivedate=15 July 2007 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> The crucial and difficult link across [[Morecambe Bay]] between [[Ulverston]] and [[Carnforth]] on the main line was promoted, as the [[Ulverston and Lancaster Railway]], by a group led by [[John Brogden (industrialist)|John Brogden]] and opened in 1857. It was promptly purchased by the Furness Railway.<ref>\n{{cite book  | first = J.D. | last = Marshall | title = Furness and the Industrial Revolution | publisher = Michael Moon, Beckermet, Cumbria | pages = 215\u20138 | origyear = 1958 |year=1981 | isbn = 978-0-904131-26-0 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book  | first = Joseph | last = Richardson | title = Furness Past and Present | pages = 18\u201324 | volume = 1 of 2 | year = 1870 }}</ref>\n\nThe docks built between 1863 and 1881 in the more sheltered channel between the mainland and [[Barrow Island (England)|Barrow Island]] replaced the port at Roa Island. The first dock to open was [[Devonshire Dock]] in 1867, and Prime Minister [[William Ewart Gladstone]] stated his belief that \"Barrow would become another Liverpool\". The increasing quantities of iron ore mined in Furness were then brought into the centre of Barrow to be transported by sea.\n\n[[File:Barrow Jute Works 1875.jpg|thumb|Painting of the [[Barrow Jute Works]] in 1875]]\nThe investors in the burgeoning mining and railway industries decided that greater profits could be made by smelting the iron ore and converting the resultant pig-iron into steel, and then exporting the finished product. Schneider and [[Sir James Ramsden|James Ramsden]], the railway's general manager, erected [[blast furnace]]s at Barrow that by 1876 formed the largest steelworks in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/|title= Barrow|accessdate= 25 August 2007|publisher= [[Ironbridge Gorge]] Museum Trust|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070819160207/http://www.ironbridge.org.uk/about_us/ironbridge_archaeology/projects/barrow/|archivedate= 19 August 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Its success was a result of the availability of local iron ore and coal from the [[Cumberland]] mines and easy rail and sea transport. The Furness Railway, which counted local aristocrats [[William Cavendish, 7th Duke of Devonshire]] and the [[Duke of Buccleuch]] as investors, kick-started the [[Industrial Revolution]] on the peninsula. The railway brought mined ore to the town, where the steelworks produced large quantities of steel. It was used for shipbuilding, and derived products such as rails were also exported from the newly-built docks.<ref name=\"railway\"/>\n\nBarrow's population grew rapidly. Population figures for the town itself were not collected until 1871,<ref name=\"THB\">{{cite journal|last1=Bainbridge|first1=TH|title=Barrow in Furness: A Population Study|journal=Economic Geography|volume=15|issue=4|pages=379\u2013383|jstor=141773|year=1939|doi=10.2307/141773}}</ref> though sources suggest that Barrow's population was still as low as 700 in 1851.<ref>{{cite web|title=Timeline History of Barrow-in-Furness|url=http://www.visitoruk.com/Barrow-in-furness/19th-century-T454.html|publisher=VisitorUK|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> During the first half of the 19th century, Barrow formed part of the parish of [[Dalton-in-Furness]], the population of which shows some of Barrow's early growth from the 1850s:\n\n'''Population of the Parish of Dalton-in-Furness'''<ref name=\"THB\" /><br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year||1801||1811||1821||1831||1841||1851||1861\n|-\n|Population||1,954||2,074||2,446||2,697||3,231||4,683||9,152\n|}\n\nIn 1871 Barrow's population was recorded at 18,584 and in 1881 at 47,259, less than forty years after the railway was built.<ref name=\"THB\" /> The majority of migrants originated from elsewhere in Lancashire although significant numbers settled in Barrow from [[Ireland]] and [[Scotland]], which represented 11% and 7% of the local population in the 1890s.<ref name=Irish>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/cultureconflictm00macr_0|url-access=registration|title=Culture, Conflict, and Migration: The Irish in Victorian Cumbria|publisher=Liverpool University Press|accessdate=6 April 2015|isbn=9780853236528|year=1998}}</ref><ref name=IrishScot>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jI6lBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Scots in Victorian and Edwardian Belfast: A Study in Elite Migration|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=1 April 2015|isbn=9780748679928|year=2013}}</ref> By the turn of the 20th century, the Scottish-born population had increased to form the highest portion anywhere in England. In an attempt to diversify Barrow's economy James Ramsden founded the Barrow and Calcutta Jute Company in 1870 and the [[Barrow Jute Works]] was soon constructed alongside the Furness Railway line in [[Hindpool]]. The mill employed 2,000 women at its peak and was awarded a gold medal for its produce at the 1878 Paris [[Exposition Universelle (1878)|Exposition Universelle]].<ref name=Grace>{{cite web|url=http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Barrow_Flax_and_Jute_Co|title=Barrow Flax and Jute Co|publisher=Grace's Guide|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barrow Works 1890.jpg|thumb|left|Barrow's shipyard circa. 1890]]\nThe sheltered strait between Barrow and Walney Island was an ideal location for the shipyard. The first ship to be built, the ''Jane Roper'', was launched in 1852; the first steamship, a 3,000-ton liner named ''Duke of Devonshire'', in 1873. Shipbuilding activity increased, and on 18 February 1871 the Barrow Shipbuilding Company was incorporated. Barrow's relative isolation from the United Kingdom's industrial heartlands meant that the newly formed company included several capabilities that would usually be subcontracted to other establishments. In particular, a large engineering works was constructed including a foundry and pattern shop, a forge, and an engine shop. In addition, the shipyard had a joiners' shop, a boat-building shed and a sailmaking and rigging loft.<ref name=\"barrow-works\">{{Cite book| last = The Naval and Armaments Company Limited | title = The Works at Barrow-in-Furness of The Naval Construction and Armaments Company Limited \u2013 Historical and Descriptive | publisher = The Naval and Armaments Company Limited, partly reprinted from 'Engineering' magazine | year = 1896 | location = Barrow-in-Furness | page = 54 }}</ref>\n\nDuring these boom years, Ramsden proposed building a [[town planning|planned town]] to accommodate the large workforce which had arrived. There are few planned towns in the United Kingdom, and Barrow is one of the oldest. Its centre contains a grid of well-built terraced houses, with a tree-lined road leading away from a central square. Ramsden later became the first mayor of Barrow,<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Mayors|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/council-democracy/mayor/former-mayors/|publisher=Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|accessdate=3 August 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923182432/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/council-democracy/mayor/former-mayors/|archivedate=23 September 2015}}</ref> which was given [[municipal borough]] status in 1867, and county borough status in 1889.<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www.dalton-in-furness.org.uk/dalton-online/history/modern-town/modern-town-localgov.html| title= History of Dalton-in-Furness| accessdate= 6 July 2007| work= Dalton Online| publisher= Dalton Community Association| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070810055439/http://www.dalton-in-furness.org.uk/dalton-online/history/modern-town/modern-town-localgov.html| archivedate= 10 August 2007|url-status = dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> The imposing red sandstone [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|town hall]], designed by W.H. Lynn, was built in a neo-gothic style in 1887.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=150 | title = Local History and Heritage | publisher = Barrow Borough Council | accessdate = 8 July 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070609195921/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=150 | archivedate = 9 June 2007 |url-status = dead| df = dmy-all }}</ref> Prior to this, the borough council had met at the railway headquarters: the railway company's control of industry extended to the administration of the town itself.\n\n[[File:Ancient roam (1).jpg|thumb|Map of Barrow dated 1890 showing no development on Walney Island and little north of the [[Furness Line]]]]\nThe Barrow Shipbuilding Company was taken over by the [[Sheffield]] steel firm of [[Vickers]] in 1897, by which time the shipyard had surpassed the railway and steelworks as the largest employer and landowner in Barrow. The company constructed [[Vickerstown]], modelled on [[George Cadbury]]'s [[Bournville]], on the adjacent Walney Island in the early 20th century to house its employees.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Frank |last=Partridge |title=The Complete Guide to: England's Islands |date=16 March 2006 |publisher=Independent News & Media |url=http://travel.independent.co.uk/uk/article351869.ece |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=10 August 2007 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927211406/http://travel.independent.co.uk/uk/article351869.ece |archivedate=27 September 2007  }}</ref> It also commissioned [[Sir Edwin Lutyens]] to design [[Abbey House, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey House]] as a guest house and residence for its managing director, Commander Craven.<ref>{{cite web|title=Homepage|url=http://www.abbeyhousehotel.com/|publisher=Abbey House Hotel|accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:Abbey House Hotel south elevation.JPG|thumb|left|[[Abbey House, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey House]] was commissioned by Vickers and designed by Sir [[Edwin Lutyens]]]]\n[[File:Cornmillcrossing.jpg|thumb|left|Cornmill Crossing in 1895 (a former goods-depot on the [[Furness Railway]]), a [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Cornmill Crossing|retail park]] now exists on the site]]\nBy the 1890s the shipyard was heavily engaged in the construction of warships for the Royal Navy and also for export. The Royal Navy's first submarine, ''[[Holland 1]]'', was built in 1901,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.submarineheritage.com/history.html |title=Submarine History of Barrow-in-Furness |publisher=Submarine Heritage Centre |accessdate=20 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704042341/http://www.submarineheritage.com/history.html |archivedate=4 July 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> and by 1914 the UK had the most advanced submarine fleet in the world, with 94% of it constructed by Vickers. Vickers was also famous for the construction of [[airship]]s and [[airship hangar]]s during the early 20th century. Originally constructed in a large shed at Cavendish Dock, production later relocated to [[Barrow/Walney Island Airport]]. [[HMA No. 1]], nicknamed the Mayfly is the most notable airship to have been built in Barrow. The first of its kind in the UK it came to an untimely end on 24 September 1911 when it was wrecked by wind during trials. Well-known ships built in Barrow include {{ship|Japanese battleship|Mikasa||2}}, the Japanese flagship during the 1905 [[Russo-Japanese War]], the liner {{SS|Oriana|1959|6}} and the aircraft carriers {{HMS|Invincible|R05|6}} and {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}}. It should also be noted that there was a significant presence of Vickers' armament division in Barrow with the huge [[VSEL Heavy Engineering Workshop|Heavy Engineering Workshop]] on Michaelson Road supplying ammunition for the [[British Army]] and [[Royal Navy]] throughout both world wars. World War 1 brought significant temporary migration as workers arrived to work in the munitions factory and shipyard, with the town's population reaching to an estimated peak of around 82,000 during the War.<ref name=\"THB\" /> Thousands of local men fought abroad during World War I, 616 were ultimately killed in action.<ref name=\"ukniwm.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukniwm.org.uk/server/show/conMemorial.2079/fromUkniwmSearch/1|title=Barrow In Furness Cenotaph|first=Imperial War|last=Museums|website=Imperial War Museums}}</ref>\n\nDuring World War II, Barrow was a target for the [[Luftwaffe|German air force]] looking to disable the town's shipbuilding capabilities (see [[Barrow Blitz]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/bob1940/september2.html |title=The Battle of Britain \u2013 Diary \u2013 2 September 1940 |accessdate=5 August 2007 |date=16 February 2005 |publisher=RAF |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815202245/http://www.raf.mod.uk/bob1940/september2.html |archivedate=15 August 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> The town suffered the most in a short period between April and May 1941. During the war, a local housewife, [[Nella Last]], was selected to write a diary of her experiences on the home front for the [[Mass-Observation]] project. Her memoirs were later adapted for television as ''[[Housewife, 49]]'' starring [[Victoria Wood]]. The difficulty in targeting bombs meant that the shipyards and steelworks were often missed, at the expense of the residential areas. Ultimately, 83 people were killed and 11,000 houses in the area were left damaged. To escape the heaviest bombardments, many people in the central areas left the town to sleep in hedgerows, with some being permanently evacuated. Barrow's industry continued to supply the war effort, with [[Winston Churchill]] visiting the town on one occasion to launch the [[aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Indomitable|R92|6}}.<ref name=\"dock\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/docs/Publication%20world%20war%20II-web.pdf|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070813205557/http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/docs/Publication%20world%20war%20II-web.pdf|url-status = dead|archive-date= 13 August 2007|title= World War II|accessdate=25 August 2007|date=16 February 2005 |publisher= [[Dock Museum]]}}</ref> Besides the dozens of civilians killed during World War II, some 268 Barrovian men were also killed whilst in combat.<ref name=\"ukniwm.org.uk\"/>\n\n[[File:Yokosuka-mikasa-08-2010.png|thumb|right|Barrow-built {{ship|Japanese battleship|Mikasa||2}} was the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]]'s flagship during the [[Russo-Japanese War]]]]\n\nBarrow's population reached a second peak in of 77,900 in 1951;<ref>{{cite book|last1=Freeman|first1=TW|title=The Conurbations of Great Britain|date=1966|publisher=The University Press|location=Manchester|page=239|edition=Second}}</ref> however, by this point the long decline of mining and steel-making as a result of overseas competition and dwindling resources had already begun.  The Barrow ironworks closed in 1963,<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.nwda.co.uk/docs/Project_Corus_July05.doc|title= Project Corus (Workington) Steering Group Report|accessdate= 31 August 2007|date= 1 June 2005|format= [[DOC (computing)|DOC]]|publisher= Northwest Development Agency|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928094413/http://www.nwda.co.uk/docs/Project_Corus_July05.doc|archivedate= 28 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> three years after the last Furness mine shut. The by then small steelworks followed suit in 1983,<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.banklands.com/Barrow%20Steel.htm | title=Barrow Steel | accessdate =21 July 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070702005911/http://www.banklands.com/Barrow%20Steel.htm| archivedate= 2 July 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> leaving Barrow's shipyard as the town's principal industry. From the 1960s onwards it concentrated its efforts in submarine manufacture, and the UK's first nuclear-powered submarine, {{HMS|Dreadnought|S101|6}}, was constructed in 1960. {{HMS|Resolution|S22|6}}, the {{sclass-|Swiftsure|submarine|5}}, {{sclass-|Trafalgar|submarine|5}} and {{sclass-|Vanguard|submarine|2}}<nowiki/>s all followed. The last of these are armed with [[Trident missile|Trident II]] [[Submarine-launched ballistic missile|missiles]] as part of the British government's [[Trident nuclear programme]].\n\nThe end of the Cold War in 1991 marked a reduction in the demand for military ships and submarines, and the town continued its decline. The shipyard's dependency on military contracts at the expense of civilian and commercial engineering and shipbuilding meant it was particularly hard hit as government defence spending was reduced dramatically.<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1080/00076790412331270099|author=Maggie Mort |author2=Graham Spinardi |year=2004 |title=Defence and the decline of UK mechanical engineering \u2013 the case of Vickers at Barrow |journal=Business History |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201322 |url=}}</ref> As a result, the workforce shrank from 14,500 in 1990 to 5,800 in February 1995,<ref>{{Cite journal|publisher=[[Competition Commission]] |title=Views of main parties as part of report into British Aerospace PLC proposed merger with VSEL |date=23 May 1995 |url=http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365c5.pdf |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520023806/http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365c5.pdf |archivedate=20 May 2011  }}</ref> with overall unemployment in the town rising over that period from 4.6% to 10%.<ref name=\"unemployment\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365a4.8.pdf|title= Appendix on unemployment as part of report into British Aerospace PLC proposed merger with VSEL|accessdate= 31 August 2007|date= 23 May 1995|publisher= [[Competition Commission]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928011251/http://www.competition-commission.gov.uk/rep_pub/reports/1995/fulltext/365a4.8.pdf|archivedate= 28 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The rejection by the [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering|VSEL]] management of detailed plans for Barrow's industrial renewal in the mid-to-late 1980s remains controversial.<ref>{{Cite book|last= Mort|first= Maggie|title= Building the Trident Network|year= 2002|publisher= [[MIT Press]]|isbn= 978-0-262-13397-5}}</ref> This has led to renewed academic attention in recent years to the possibilities of converting military-industrial production in declining shipbuilding areas to the offshore renewable energy sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.basicint.org/nuclear/beyondtrident/oceans.pdf|title= Oceans of Work: Arms Conversion Revisited|accessdate=25 August 2007 |last= Schofield|first= Steven|date=January 2007|publisher= [[British American Security Information Council]]|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070710111238/http://www.basicint.org/nuclear/beyondtrident/oceans.pdf |archivedate = 10 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Albion and Bulwark, Barrow 2002.jpg|thumb|left|{{HMS|Albion|L14|6}} and {{HMS|Bulwark|L15|6}} undergoing fitting out in 2002 at BAE Systems Marine in Barrow]]\nIn a 2002 [[2002 Barrow-in-Furness legionellosis outbreak|outbreak of legionellosis]] in the town, 172 people were reported to have caught the disease, of whom seven died. This made it the fourth worst outbreak in the world in terms of number of cases and sixth worst in terms of deaths. The source of the bacteria was later found to be steam from a badly maintained air conditioning unit in the council-run arts centre [[The Forum Barrow|Forum 28]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Legionnaires' source officially traced |work=BBC News | date = 20 August 2002 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2205186.stm | accessdate=21 July 2003 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20030814170447/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2205186.stm| archivedate= 14 August 2003 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAt the conclusion of the inquest into the seven deaths, the coroner for Furness and South Cumbria criticised the council for its health and safety failings.<ref>{{Cite news| title = A Total Shambles|publisher = [[North West Evening Mail]]| date = 12 June 2007 | url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508368 | accessdate =21 July 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070623083652/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508368| archivedate = 23 June 2007}}</ref> In 2006, council employee Gillian Beckingham and employer [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow Borough Council]] were cleared of seven charges of [[manslaughter]]. Beckingham, the council senior architect was fined \u00a315,000 and the authority \u00a3125,000. Following the trials the contractor responsible for maintaining the plant settled a \u00a31.5 million claim by the council for damages.<ref>{{cite news| title = Bug Death Council Worker Cleared |work=BBC News | date = 31 July 2006 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/5232086.stm | accessdate=21 July 2007 }}</ref> The borough council was the first public body in the country to face corporate manslaughter charges.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.cipfa.org.uk/publicfinance/features_details.cfm?News_id=24043 | title =Back in the Line of Fire | publisher = publicfinance.co.uk | accessdate =21 July 2007| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071006125830/http://www.cipfa.org.uk/publicfinance/features_details.cfm?News_id=24043| archivedate = 6 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n2006 saw the construction of [[Barrow Offshore Wind Farm]], which has acted as a catalyst for further investment in offshore [[renewable energy]]. [[Ormonde Wind Farm]] and [[Walney Wind Farm]] followed in 2011, the latter of which became the largest offshore wind farm in the world. The three wind farms are located west of Walney Island and are operated primarily by [[DONG Energy]], contain a total of 162 [[Wind turbine|turbines]] and have a combined [[Intermittent energy source#Terminology|nameplate capacity]] of 607&nbsp;MW, providing energy for well over half a million homes. [[West of Duddon Sands Wind Farm]] was commissioned in 2014 while Walney was extended in 2018 to again become the world's largest such offshore facility.\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Barrow town hall, April 2011.jpg|thumb|right|Barrow's Grade II* listed [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|town hall]] viewed from [[Schneider Square]]]]\n\nBarrow is the largest town in the [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/view.asp?ID=6027  | title = Cumbria's Population in Urban Areas 2003 | publisher = Cumbria County Council | format=[[Microsoft Excel|XLS]] | accessdate =11 December 2006}}</ref> and the largest settlement in the peninsula of [[Furness]]. The borough is the direct inheritor of the municipal and county borough charters given to the town in the late 19th century.<ref name=\"mayorlist\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2490 |title=Barrow Borough Council \u2013 Former Mayors |accessdate=18 August 2007 |publisher=[[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow Borough Council]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030726/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2490 |archivedate=28 September 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> Historically it is part of the [[Lonsdale (hundred)|Hundred of Lonsdale]] 'north of the sands' in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county boundaries]] of [[Lancashire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043|title= Lancashire AncC: Historical Boundaries|accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher= A Vision of Britain Through Time| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001412/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043| archivedate = 1 October 2007}}</ref> Since the local government reforms enacted in England in 1974 the town has been within the administrative county of [[Cumbria]]. It still forms a part of the [[Duchy of Lancaster]]. The [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow-in-Furness Borough Council]] forms the 'lower' tier of local government under [[Cumbria|Cumbria County Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Draft Statutory Instrument 2004 The Regional Assembly and Local Government Referendums (Date of Referendums, Referendum Question and Explanatory Material) (North West Region) Order 2004 | work=Office of Public Sector Information | url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/SI/si2004/draft/20049539.htm | accessdate =18 August 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071001000704/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/SI/si2004/draft/20049539.htm| archivedate= 1 October 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> Since the [[2011 Barrow-in-Furness Council election|2011 local election]], the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] has had overall control of the Borough council, while the Borough elected 10 Labour and one Conservative Party councillor at the [[2013 Cumbria County Council election|2013 Cumbria County election]]. The town, along with [[Walney Island]], is unparished and forms the bulk of the wards which make the entire borough's area. The Mayor and Deputy Mayor of Barrow are elected annually, and hold the roles of chairman and Vice-Chairman of Barrow-in-Furness Borough Council.<ref name=\"mayorrole\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/about-the-council/barrow-council/mayor/former-mayors/ |title=Barrow Borough Council \u2013 Mayor's Role |accessdate=4 March 2017 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council }}</ref> The borough and former county borough of Barrow-in-Furness have been served by 107 mayors, beginning with [[Sir James Ramsden]] in 1867 and continuing through to incumbent 2015/16 mayor Ann Thomson.<ref name=\"mayorrole\"/>\n\nThe Barrow-in-Furness [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|UK Parliament constituency]] first came into existence during the [[1885 United Kingdom general election]], with [[David Duncan (UK politician)|David Duncan]] of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] becoming the first [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for the town. The seat was won by the Conservative Party in [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]], before being won for the first time by Labour in [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]. In the subsequent 40 years the seat swung between Conservative and Labour, but since 1945 it has been generally considered a Labour safe seat.<ref name=\"Polling Report\">{{cite web|title=Barrow & Furness|url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/2015guide/barrowandfurness/|publisher=UK Polling Report|accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref> In 1983, the constituency was expanded to include several commuter towns such as Dalton-in-Furness and Ulverston and was renamed [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]]. It was subsequently won by the Conservatives, with the victory attributed to Labour's stance against the nuclear-powered submarines that were being constructed in Barrow.<ref name=\"Polling Report\" /> Following a change in Labour policy the party won Barrow and Furness in 1992. [[John Woodcock (UK politician)|John Woodcock]] has been the MP for the constituency since the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], but is to stand down for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], after resigning from the Labour party amid allegations of sexual harassment made against him.\n\n<br />\n{| style=\"margin:0 auto;\" class=\"toccolours\"\n|align=center| '''Council/ Electoral wards of Barrow-in-Furness'''\n|-\n|align=center|\n[[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]] | [[Central Barrow|Central]] | [[Hawcoat]] |  [[Hindpool]] | [[Newbarns]] | [[Ormsgill]] | [[Parkside, Barrow-in-Furness|Parkside]] | [[Risedale]] | [[Roose]]cote | [[Walney North]] | [[Walney South]]\n|}\n\n==Geography==\nBarrow is situated at the tip of the [[Furness]] peninsula on the north-western edge of [[Morecambe Bay]], south of the [[Duddon Estuary]] and east of the [[Irish Sea]]. [[Walney Island]], to the west of Barrow, surrounds the peninsula's Irish Sea coast and is separated from Barrow by the narrow [[Walney Channel]]. Both Morecambe Bay and the Duddon Estuary are characterized by large areas of [[quicksand]] and fast-moving [[tidal bore]]s. Areas of [[sand dunes]] exist on coasts surrounding Barrow, particularly at [[Roanhead]] and [[North Walney]]. The town centre and major industrial areas sit on a fairly flat coastal shelf, with hillier ground rising to the east of the town, peaking at {{convert|94|m|ft|round=5}} at Yarlside. Barrow sits on soils deposited during the end of the [[Last glacial period|Ice Age]], eroded from the mountains of the [[Lake District National Park]], {{convert|10|mi|km|round=5}} to the north-east. Barrow's soils are composed of glacial lake clay and [[glacial till]], while Walney is almost entirely made up of reworked glacial morraine.<ref>{{cite web|last1=May|first1=VJ|title=Walney Island|url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/pdf/gcrdb/GCRsiteaccount2042.pdf|publisher=DEFRA|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ICE\">{{cite journal|last1=Raison|first1=CA|title=North Morecambe Terminal, Barrow: pile design for seismic conditions|journal=Proceedings of the ICE \u2013 Geotechnical Engineering|date=1999|volume=137|issue=3|page=149\u00b1163|url=http://www.raisonfosterassociates.co.uk/downloads/barrow-piling.pdf|accessdate=16 July 2015|doi=10.1680/gt.1999.370304}}</ref> Beneath these soils is a [[sandstone]] bedrock, from which many of the town's older buildings are constructed.<ref name=\"ICE\" />\n\nBarrow town centre is located to the north-east of the docks, with suburbs also extending to the north and east, as well as onto Walney. The towns of [[Dalton-in-Furness]] and [[Askam-in-Furness]] are the other sizable settlements of the [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]. Barrow is the only major urban area in South Cumbria, with the nearest settlements of a similar size being [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] and [[Morecambe]]. Other towns nearby include [[Ulverston]], [[Millom]], [[Grange-over-Sands]], [[Kendal]] and [[Windermere, Cumbria (town)|Windermere]].\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"220px\">\nFile:Barrow-in-Furness Map.png|Map of Barrow\nFile:Barrow-in-Furness aerial from the south.jpg|Aerial view of Barrow and Walney Island\nFile:Ordnance Survey 1-250000 - SD.jpg|Barrow within North West England (top left)\n</gallery>\n\n===Islands===\n{{Main|Islands of Furness}}\nThe town is sheltered from the Irish Sea by [[Walney Island]], a <span style=\"white-space:nowrap\">14&nbsp;mile&nbsp;(22.5&nbsp;km)</span> long island connected to the mainland by the [[Bascule bridge|bascule]] type [[Walney Bridge|Jubilee bridge]]. About 13,000 live on the isle's various settlements, mostly in [[Vickerstown]], which was built to house workers in the rapidly expanding shipyard. Another significant island which lay in the Walney Channel was [[Barrow Island (England)|Barrow Island]], but following the filling of the channel to create land for the shipyard it is now directly connected to the town. Other islands which lie close to Barrow are [[Piel Island]], whose [[Piel Castle|castle]] protected the harbour from marauding [[Scot]]s, [[Sheep Island (England)|Sheep Island]], [[Roa Island]] and [[Foulney Island]].\n\n===Parks and open spaces===\n\nThere are numerous natural and managed public parks and open spaces within Barrow. Walney North and [[South Walney|South Nature Reserves]] are protected as Sites of Special Scientific Interest, as is [[Sandscale Haws]]. Formal woodland areas within the town include Hawcoat/Ormsgill Quarry, How Tun Woods, [[Abbot's Wood, Cumbria|Abbotswood]], Barrow Steel Works & Slag Bank and Sowerby Wood. The 45-Acre [[Barrow Park]] is the largest and most centrally located man-made park in the town with smaller parks including Channelside Haven, Hindpool Urban Park and Vickerstown Park. There are also 25 council-owned playgrounds and 15 allotments.\n\n===Climate===\nBarrow on the west coast of Great Britain has a [[temperate]] [[maritime climate]] owing to the North Atlantic current and tends to have milder winters than central and eastern parts of the country. The town lies in [[Hardiness zone]] 9 and has an average yearly temperature of 10.4&nbsp;\u00b0C.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Barrow-in-Furness, England, United Kingdom\n|collapsed = y\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan high F = 44\n|Feb high F = 46\n|Mar high F = 49\n|Apr high F = 53\n|May high F = 59\n|Jun high F = 62\n|Jul high F = 66\n|Aug high F = 67\n|Sep high F = 63\n|Oct high F = 57\n|Nov high F = 50\n|Dec high F = 45\n|year high F=\n|Jan low F = 39\n|Feb low F = 39\n|Mar low F = 40\n|Apr low F = 43\n|May low F = 47\n|Jun low F = 52\n|Jul low F = 56\n|Aug low F = 56\n|Sep low F = 53\n|Oct low F = 49\n|Nov low F = 44\n|Dec low F = 39\n|year low F=\n|Jan record high F = 55\n|Feb record high F = 57\n|Mar record high F = 66\n|Apr record high F = 72\n|May record high F = 81\n|Jun record high F = 88\n|Jul record high F = 91\n|Aug record high F = 92\n|Sep record high F = 80\n|Oct record high F = 74\n|Nov record high F = 61\n|Dec record high F = 57\n|year record high F=\n|Jan record low F = 14\n|Feb record low F = 16\n|Mar record low F = 15\n|Apr record low F = 24\n|May record low F = 29\n|Jun record low F = 36\n|Jul record low F = 39\n|Aug record low F = 37\n|Sep record low F = 32\n|Oct record low F = 23\n|Nov record low F = 20\n|Dec record low F = 12\n|year record low F=\n|Jan precipitation inch = 2.80\n|Feb precipitation inch = 2.65\n|Mar precipitation inch = 2.50\n|Apr precipitation inch = 2.13\n|May precipitation inch = 2.17\n|Jun precipitation inch = 2.42\n|Jul precipitation inch = 2.22\n|Aug precipitation inch = 2.69\n|Sep precipitation inch = 3.39\n|Oct precipitation inch = 4.35\n|Nov precipitation inch = 3.62\n|Dec precipitation inch = 3.36\n|year precipitation inch=\n|source 1 = MSN Weather<ref name=MSNWeather >{{Cite web\n| url =http://weather.uk.msn.com/local.aspx?&wealocations=wc%3aUKXX1577&setunit=F | title =Average Weather for Barrow-in-Furness | accessdate =3 August 2007| publisher =[[MSN.com]] }}</ref>\n|date = August 2010}}\n\n==Demography==\n\n===Population===\nThe [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow council district]], which includes adjacent urban areas, had a population of around 69,100 according to the 2011 census. This is 4% less than the 2001 figure of 71,900, and the highest percentage population loss in the country between 2001 and 2011.<ref name=\"population\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/profiles/16uc.asp | title=Census statistics for Barrow-in-Furness 2001 | accessdate=11 May 2007 | publisher=National Statistics }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18681865|title=Census 2011: At a glance|date=16 July 2012|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref> The Office for National Statistics states Barrow's population as being in long term decline with a projected population of around 65,000 by 2037. This is largely a result of negative [[net migration]].<ref name=\"decline\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/snpp/sub-national-population-projections/2012-based-projections/rft-population-las.xls | title=Table 2: 2012-based Subnational Population Projections for Local Authorities in England  | accessdate=20 August 2014 | publisher=Office for National Statistics }}</ref>\n\n===Ethnicity and language===\nThe 2011 census states 96.9% of Barrow's population as [[White British]], and ethnic minority populations in Barrow stood at 3.1%.<ref name=2011ethnicity>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=13&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366140355413&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2575|title=Ethnic Group, 2011 (QS201EW)|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> Other ethnic groups in Barrow include [[White Other (United Kingdom Census)|Other White]] 1.3%, [[Asian people|Asian]] 1.0%, [[British Mixed|Mixed Race]] 0.5%, [[Black British|Black]] 0.1%, [[British Arab|Arab]] 0.1% and [[Other ethnic group (United Kingdom Census)|all other ethnic groups]] represented 0.1% of the population. The first people to settle in what is now Barrow were the [[Celts]] and [[Norsemen|Scandinavians]] followed by the [[Cornish people|Cornish]]. Most Barrovians however are descended from immigrants from [[Scotland]], [[Ireland]] and other parts of England who arrived from the late 19th century onwards. Barrow has significant [[British Chinese|Chinese]] (in particular those originating from Hong Kong), [[Filipinos in the United Kingdom|Filipino]], [[British Indian|Indian]], [[Thais in the United Kingdom|Thai]] and [[Kosovan migration to the United Kingdom|Kosovan]] communities as well as a [[Poles in the United Kingdom|Polish]] population which partly dates back to World War II, however in general Barrow has a much lower proportion of ethnic minorities than national average.<ref name=2011ethnicity/>\n\nBarrow's Chinese connections were the subject of a documentary on Chinese state television in 2014.<ref name=China>{{cite web|url=http://www.in-cumbria.com/links-between-barrow-and-china-to-be-featured-in-film-1.1100560|title=Links Between Barrow and China to be Featured in Film|publisher=in-cumbria.com|accessdate=17 August 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140817153354/http://www.in-cumbria.com/links-between-barrow-and-china-to-be-featured-in-film-1.1100560|archivedate=17 August 2014}}</ref> The programme covered diplomat [[Li Hongzhang]]'s fact finding mission to the town's steelworks and shipyard in 1896 as well as the 2012 discovery of a hoard of Chinese coins discovered in Barrow dated around a similar time that have been suggested as having been brought over by sailors or labourers.<ref name=China/> The [[Society for Anglo-Chinese Understanding]] is a charity with a branch based in Barrow that aims to develop relations with the [[British Chinese]] community and the general British population. It was established in 1975 and publishes the quarterly ''China Eye'' magazine.\n[[File:St James's Church, Barrow.jpg|thumb|right|[[St. James' Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. James' Church]], the largest place of worship in Barrow]]\n\nIn 2011 93.2% of the borough's population was born in England, 2.6% in [[Scotland]], 0.6%  in [[Northern Ireland]] and 0.5% in [[Wales]]. 3.1% of the town's 2011 population were born elsewhere in the world, 1.3% of which were born in the [[European Union]]. The five most common foreign countries of birth were [[Poland]], the [[Republic of Ireland]], Germany, the [[Philippines]] and [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=13&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366138221646&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2525| title = Country of Birth (detailed), 2011 (QS203EW)| accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2011 census, 98.8% of Barrovians spoke English as a main language, although around 40 languages are spoken in the town with [[Polish language|Polish]], Chinese, and [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] prevailing as the second, third and fourth most common main languages (0.3%, 0.2% and 0.1% of the population respectively).<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=13&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366138221646&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2528| title = Main Language (detailed), 2011 (QS204EW)| accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> Of the 797 Barrovians who had a main language other than English, 82.9% can speak English well to very well.<ref name=\"proficiency\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=14&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366143203704&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2500| title = Proficiency in English, 2011 (QS205EW)| accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\n{{See also|List of places of worship in Barrow-in-Furness}}\nIn the 2011 census 70.7% of Barrow's population stated themselves as being Christian. People stating no religion or chose not to state totalled 28.4% combined. Other religious groups represented 0.9% of the population, with [[Islam]] and [[Buddhism]] prevailing as the first and second most common groups.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=14&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1366142319396&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2479| title = Religion, 2011 (KS209EW)| accessdate=16 April 2013}}</ref> Conishead Priory, the first [[Kadampa]] Buddhist centre in the west, is home to around 100 Buddhists and is located off the Barrow to Ulverston Coast Road within the [[South Lakeland]] district.<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www.aboutulverston.co.uk/location/conisheadpriory.htm| title= Conishead Priory, Ulverston| accessdate= 21 July 2007| publisher= AboutUlverston.co.uk| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070804012408/http://www.aboutulverston.co.uk/location/conisheadpriory.htm| archivedate= 4 August 2007|url-status = dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Historically Barrow was home to a notable [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi Jewish]] community that peaked in size during the 1930s with a synagogue in the town. Nonetheless, it closed in 1974 and only a dozen Jews were recorded by the 2011 census.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barrow-in-Furness Jewish Community & Synagogue|url=http://www.jewishgen.org/jcr-uk/Community/barrow/|publisher=Jewish Communities and Records|accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Audacious Under Construction MOD 45155780.jpg|thumb|left|An [[Astute-class submarine|''Astute''-class]] submarine under-construction inside [[Devonshire Dock Hall]] in 2013]]\nHistorically Barrow's economy was dominated by the manufacturing sector, with the [[Barrow Hematite Steel Company]] and [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering]] being amongst the most important global companies in their respective fields during the 20th century. In the present day, manufacturing remains the largest employment sector in the town with [[BAE Systems]] being the single largest employer. However, like most of the UK, employment trends have greatly diversified since the 20th century and there are no other predominant employment sectors in Barrow.\n\n===Shipyard and port===\nBarrow has played a vital role in global ship and submarine construction for around 150 years. [[Ottoman submarine Abd\u00fcl Hamid|Ottoman submarine ''Abd\u00fcl Hamid'']] was built in the town in 1886 and became the first submarine in the world to fire a live torpedo underwater, while oil tanker ''British Admiral'' became the first British vessel to exceed 100,000 tonnes when launched in 1965. The vast majority of all current and former Royal Navy submarines were constructed in Barrow as well as numerous [[Royal Navy Fleet Flagship]]s.\n\n[[File:HMS Invincible (R05).jpg|thumb|right|{{HMS|Invincible|R05|6}} pictured in Florida in 2004 is one of the most famous ships to have been built in Barrow]]\nThe [[BAE Systems Maritime \u2013 Submarines]] shipyard at Barrow is the largest in the UK by workforce ahead of [[BAE Systems Maritime \u2013 Naval Ships]] in [[Govan]]. It was expanded in 1986 by construction of a new covered assembly facility, the [[Devonshire Dock Hall]] (DDH), completed by [[Alfred McAlpine]], on land that was created by infilling part of the [[Devonshire Dock]] with 2.4 million tonnes of sand pumped from nearby Roosecote Sands.<ref>The Road to Success: Alfred McAlpine 1935 \u2013 1985 page 174, Tony Gray, Rainbird Publishing, 1987</ref> DDH is the tallest building in Cumbria at 51&nbsp;m. With a length of {{convert|268|m|ft|abbr=on}}, width of {{convert|51|m|ft|abbr=on}} and an area of {{convert|25000|m2|sqft|}} it is one of the largest shipbuilding construction complex of its kind in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Alison|title=Marine Marvel|url=http://www.thecqi.org/Documents/community/Special-Interest-Groups/Defence/Marine_marvel_jul_07.pdf|publisher=The Chartered Quality Institute|accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe DDH provides a controlled environment for ship and submarine assembly, and avoids the difficulties caused by building on the slope of traditional slipways. Outside the hall, a 24,300 tonne capacity shiplift allows completed vessels to be lowered into the water independently of the tide. Vessels can also be lifted out of the water and transferred to the hall.<ref>{{Cite journal| author = BAE Systems| title = Devonshire Dock Hall (DDH): One of the most advanced Shipbuilding Complexes in the World | url = http://www.baesystems.com/BAEProd/groups/public/documents/ss_asset/bae_subs_ddhdatasheet.pdf | accessdate =3 June 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070704111547/http://www.baesystems.com/BAEProd/groups/public/documents/ss_asset/bae_subs_ddhdatasheet.pdf| archivedate = 4 July 2007}}</ref> The first use of the DDH was for construction of the {{sclass-|Vanguard|submarine|2}}s, and later vessels of the {{sclass-|Trafalgar|submarine|4}} were also built there. The shipyard is currently constructing the {{sclass-|Astute|submarine|2}}s, the first of which was launched on 8 June 2007.<ref name=\"Astute_launch\">{{cite news| title = New UK nuclear submarine launched |work=BBC News | date = 8 June 2007 | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6733777.stm | accessdate =14 June 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070618113755/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6733777.stm| archivedate= 18 June 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> BAE Systems is currently studying the design of a [[British replacement of the Trident system|new class]] of ballistic missile submarines. BAE Systems also has orders for submarine pressure domes for the [[Spanish Navy]].<ref name=\"Spanish_subs\">{{cite news| title = BAE lands submarine export order |work=BBC News | date = 2 May 2007 | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6615139.stm | accessdate =14 June 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070605155840/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6615139.stm| archivedate= 5 June 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe shipyard has been awarded contracts for the construction of submarines which will carry nuclear missiles in a [[Dreadnought-class submarine|successor programme]] to the current ''Vanguard'' class containing the [[UK Trident programme|Trident system]].<ref name=Shipyardexpansion1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Defence-boom-will-create-thousands-of-BAE-Systems-jobs-in-Barrow-f2441d1a-a8f9-401e-befd-67a5aa217b58-ds|title=Defence boom will create thousands of BAE jobs in Barrow|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=13 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085451/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Defence-boom-will-create-thousands-of-BAE-Systems-jobs-in-Barrow-f2441d1a-a8f9-401e-befd-67a5aa217b58-ds|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> BAE Systems is investing \u00a3300 million in Barrow's shipyard to construct buildings capable of manufacturing and assembling the new class of submarines. This major development is the largest in 25 years at the shipyard and will see thousands of new jobs created, further cementing its place as the UK's largest shipyard and one of the few to have seen continuous contracts since founding over a century ago.<ref name=Shipyardexpansion1/>\n\n[[File:Return to base - geograph.org.uk - 580030.jpg|thumb|left|[[Barrow Offshore Wind Farm]]]]\nThe most recent surface vessels to be constructed in Barrow were {{sclass2-|Wave|tanker|2}} {{ship|RFA|Wave Knight|A389|6}} and {{sclass-|Albion|landing platform dock|0}} amphibious assault ships {{HMS|Albion|L14|6}} and {{HMS|Bulwark|L15|6}} in the early 2000s when the shipyard was part of [[BAE Systems Marine]] division. It also undertook fitting out and commissioning of helicopter carrier {{HMS|Ocean|L12|6}} in the mid-1990s after the ship was built by [[Kvaerner Govan]] in Glasgow.\n\n[[Associated British Ports Holdings]] owns and operates the [[Port of Barrow]] which can berth vessels up to {{convert|200|m|ft|abbr=on}} long and with a draught of {{convert|10|m|ft|abbr=on}}. The four main docks include [[Buccleuch Dock]], [[Cavendish Dock]], [[Devonshire Dock]] and [[Ramsden Dock]], with the latter handling almost all of the port's cargo. Buccleuch and Devonshire Docks are utilised primarily by BAE Systems, while Cavendish Dock the largest by surface area is now a reservoir. Principal traffic includes the export of condensate by-product from the production of gas at the [[Rampside Gas Terminal]], wood pulp and locally quarried limestone which is exported to Scandinavia for use in the paper industry. The port, which has deep water access, also handles the shipment of nuclear fuels and radioactive waste for [[BNFL]]'s nearby [[Sellafield]] plant.<ref>{{Cite web  | publisher= Associated British Ports  | title= Port of Barrow  | url= http://www.abports.co.uk/custinfo/ports/barrow.htm  | accessdate= 20 August 2007  | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927122945/http://www.abports.co.uk/custinfo/ports/barrow.htm  | archivedate= 27 September 2007  | url-status= dead  }}</ref>\n\n[[James Fisher & Sons]], a service provider in all sectors of the marine industry and a specialist supplier of engineering services to the nuclear industry in the UK and abroad,<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.james-fisher.co.uk/|title= Welcome to James Fisher|accessdate=30 August 2007 |year= 2005|work= James Fisher official website|publisher= James Fisher and Sons| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070828041321/http://www.james-fisher.co.uk/| archivedate= 28 August 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> was founded in Barrow in 1847.<ref>{{Cite news|first= Mary|last= MacIsaac|title= With a fair wind blowing there are profits to be made on the high seas|url= http://business.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=895&id=401272003|series= Armchair Investor|work=The Scotsman |location=UK|date=  6 April 2003|accessdate=30 August 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070810073535/http://business.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=895&id=401272003| archivedate= 10 August 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> It is listed on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is the largest company to have its headquarters situated in Cumbria.<ref name=Largestplc>{{cite news|url=http://www.whitehavennews.co.uk/barrow-company-s-profits-soar-by-11-per-cent-1.931938|title=Barrow Company's Profits Soar by 11 Percent|newspaper=Whitehaven News|accessdate=5 March 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608051838/http://www.whitehavennews.co.uk/barrow-company-s-profits-soar-by-11-per-cent-1.931938|archivedate=8 June 2015}}</ref> Annual revenue stood at \u00a3307 million in 2012 (up 15% from \u00a3268 million in 2011), as well as staff numbers standing at over 1,500 worldwide, with 120 of those in the Barrow headquarters.<ref name=Largestplc/><ref>{{Cite news|title= Jobs Hope as Fisher Booms|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=536629|publisher= North West Evening Mail|date=  29 August 2007|accessdate=30 August 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926212059/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=536629| archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> Numerous vessels are registered at the Port of Barrow, with the majority being owned by James Fisher & Sons and [[International Nuclear Services]]/Pacific Nuclear Transport Limited.\n\n===Energy generation===\n[[File:North Walney Beach - geograph.org.uk - 209770.jpg|thumb|West Shore Beach at [[Earnse Bay]] with [[Black Combe]] visible in the distance]]\nIn 1985, gas was discovered in Morecambe Bay, and to this day the products have been processed onshore at [[Rampside Gas Terminal]] in south Barrow.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=459 | title=About Us | publisher=Centrica Gas | accessdate=21 July 2007 |url-status = dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070906181440/http://www.centrica.com/index.asp?pageid=459 | archivedate=6 September 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The complex is operated jointly by [[Centrica]] and [[ConocoPhillips]]. Directly adjacent to Rampside Gas Terminal is [[Roosecote Power Station]] which was the first [[Combined cycle|CCGT]] power station to supply electricity to the United Kingdom's National Grid. Although originally coal-fired, the station became gas-fired until it was mothballed in 2015.\n\nBarrow and its wider urban area form part of 'Britain's Energy Coast',<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.britainsenergycoast.com/ | title = ACTING LOCALLY, THINKING GLOBALLY | publisher = Britain's Energy Coast | accessdate=25 June 2011 }}</ref> and has one of the highest concentrations of [[wind farm]]s in the world, the vast majority are located offshore and have been built during the early 2010s. All four of these wind farms are located off the coast of Walney Island, including the 189 turbine [[Walney Wind Farm]], 108 turbine [[West Duddon wind farm]], 30 turbine [[Barrow Offshore Wind Farm]] and 30 turbine [[Ormonde Wind Farm]]. Walney Wind Farm was the largest offshore wind farm in the world upon completion, in 2015 it received government consent to be trebled in size. [[DONG Energy]] and [[Scottish Power]] maintain a wind farm operations base with 30 full-time staff members at the Port of Barrow.<ref name=Windoperations>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishpowerrenewables.com/news/pages/new_4_million_wind_farm_operations_base_in_barrow_seeks_skilled_workers.asp|title=New \u00a34 Million Wind Farm Operations Base in Barrow Seeks Skilled Workers|publisher=Scottish Power|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Sellafield]] and [[Heysham nuclear power station]]s are also located within {{convert|25|mi|km}} of Barrow.\n\n===Tourism and leisure===\n[[File:Giraffes south lakes wild animal park.jpg|thumb|left|[[South Lakes Safari Zoo]] on the outskirts of the borough is one of Cumbria's top tourist attractions]]\nAlthough it is at the end of a peninsula, Barrow is only around 20 minutes from the [[Lake District]],<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.totaltravel.co.uk/travel/north-west/carlisle-cumbrian-coast/south-cumbria/travel-guides/Destinations/barrow-in-furness|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071011092642/http://www.totaltravel.co.uk/travel/north-west/carlisle-cumbrian-coast/south-cumbria/travel-guides/Destinations/barrow-in-furness|url-status = dead|archive-date= 11 October 2007|title= Barrow in Furness|accessdate= 14 August 2007|publisher= totaltravel.com}}</ref> Barrow has been referred to as a \"gateway to the lakes\" and \"where the lakes meets the sea\",<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=467814|title= Half Term Fun for the Kids Just on the Doorstep|accessdate=14 August 2007 |date= 17 February 2007|publisher= North West Evening Mail |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926210914/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=467814 |archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> a status which could be enhanced by the new marina complex and planned cruise ship terminal.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/docs/November%202005%20-%20Executive%20Committee%20Agenda.doc|title= November 2005 \u2013 Executive Committee Agenda|accessdate= 14 August 2007|date= November 2005|format= DOC|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|pages= 5|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030709/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/docs/November%202005%20-%20Executive%20Committee%20Agenda.doc|archivedate= 28 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBarrow itself has several tourist attractions that support just over 1,000 jobs; the town saw a higher growth in tourist expenditure during the 2000s than Cumbria as a whole and had about 2.3 million overnight stays during 2008.<ref name=Touriststats>{{cite web|url=http://www.cumbriaobservatory.org.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/675/4356/40501155120.pdf|title=Cumbria Local Economic Assessment|publisher=Cumbria Observatory|accessdate=6 April 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416145143/http://www.cumbriaobservatory.org.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/675/4356/40501155120.pdf|archivedate=16 April 2014}}</ref> Barrow's most popular free-entry tourist attraction is the [[Dock Museum]]. The museum tells the history of Barrow (including the steelworks industry, the shipyard and the [[Barrow Blitz]]), as well as offering gallery space to local artists and schoolchildren. It is built upon and around an old graving dock.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/enjoy_cumbria/places/barrow_dock_museum.shtml|title= Barrow Dock Museum|accessdate=14 August 2007 |work= Enjoy Cumbria|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Walney Island has two world-renowned nature reserves (the 130 hectare (0.5 sq mi) South Walney Nature Reserve<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.cumbriawildlifetrust.org.uk/south-walney.html|title= South Walney|accessdate= 2 September 2011|publisher= Cumbria Wildlife Trust|url-status = dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110903122209/http://www.cumbriawildlifetrust.org.uk/south-walney.html|archivedate= 3 September 2011|df= dmy-all}}</ref> and the 650 hectare (2.5 sq mi) [[North Walney|North Walney Nature Reserve]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designatedareas/nnr/northwalneywhatmakesitspecial.aspx|title= North Walney: what makes it special?|accessdate=2 September 2011|publisher= Natural England}}</ref> Both nature reserves have [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] designation, as do the [[Duddon Estuary]] and [[Sandscale Haws]] to the north of the borough. Barrow has a number of beaches which are popular in the summer with sunbathers, kitesurfers and caravanners. They include [[Earnse Bay]], Biggar Bank, [[Roanhead]] and [[Rampside]]. The first two of these provide views of the [[Isle of Man]] and [[Anglesey]] on exceptionally clear days. The wider borough has more than 60&nbsp;km of coastline.<ref name=Beaches>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=153 |title=Beaches |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |accessdate=6 April 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154537/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=153 |archivedate=24 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The Park Leisure Centre is a fitness suite with a pool, set in the {{convert|45|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[Barrow Park]].<ref name=\"aboutbritain\"/> The historic ruins of [[Furness Abbey]] and [[Piel Castle]], which are both managed by [[English Heritage]], are also popular tourist destinations. [[South Lakes Safari Zoo]] is one of Europe's leading conservation zoos and has been voted Cumbria's best tourist attraction in five non-consecutive years although it has a checkered history; it lies within the borough of Barrow-in-Furness on the outskirts of Dalton. The zoo underwent a multi-million pound expansion during the mid-2010s. It now holds thousands of animals and covers an area of {{Convert|51|acres}} making it one of the Northern England's largest such parks.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.visitcumbria.com/sl/south-lakes-wild-animal-park.htm|title= South Lakes Wild Animal Park|accessdate= 2 September 2011|publisher= Visit Cumbria|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110719164425/http://visitcumbria.com/sl/south-lakes-wild-animal-park.htm|archivedate= 19 July 2011|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:The White House And The Castle.jpg|thumb|right|[[Piel Island]] and [[Piel Castle|castle]] are a popular attraction in Barrow]]\n\nBarrow has been described as the Lake District's premier shopping town, with 'big name shops mingling with small local ones'.<ref name=\"aboutbritain\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.aboutbritain.com/towns/barrow-in-furness.asp|title= Barrow-in-Furness Tourist Information|accessdate=25 August 2007 |publisher= AboutBritain.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070828073226/http://www.aboutbritain.com/towns/barrow-in-furness.asp| archivedate= 28 August 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> The town centre is home to a large indoor market<ref>{{Cite news|first=Bibi |last=van der Zee |title=Pitch Perfect, Part Two |date=7 August 2007 |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,,1838907,00.html |accessdate=27 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702120519/http://www.guardian.co.uk/g2/story/0%2C%2C1838907%2C00.html |archivedate=2 July 2007 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=149 |title=Barrow Borough Council \u2013 Barrow Markets |accessdate=27 July 2007 |date=7 March 2007 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824210003/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=149 |archivedate=24 August 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> and [[Portland Walk Shopping Centre]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=161|title= Shopping and Town Centre|accessdate= 23 September 2007|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070911122313/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=161|archivedate= 11 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Barrow has many retail and leisure parks for a town of its size, including [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Cornmill Crossing|Cornmill Crossing]], [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Cornerhouse Retail Park|Cornerhouse Retail Park]], [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Hollywood Park|Hollywood Park]], [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Hollywood Park|Hindpool Retail Park]] and Walney Road Retail Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=137|title= Exploring the Area around Barrow-in-Furness|accessdate= 23 September 2007|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070911222136/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=137|archivedate= 11 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrow.furness.co.uk/barrow_lifestyle.asp?ID=L6|title= 24 Hour Shopping|accessdate=30 August 2007 |work= Barrow. Furness.co.uk|publisher= Furness Enterprise Ltd.}}</ref> Between them they host a number of supermarkets, electrical, home furnishing, clothing and discount stores, gyms, restaurants and Cumbria's largest cinema. Other modern visitor attractions in Barrow include the growing leisure destination at James Freel Close (consisting of an indoor [[kart racing]] complex, [[bowling]] alley, indoor [[skate park]], [[trampoline]] centre and gym), as well as Lazer Zone in Hindpool Road's former [[Custom House, Barrow-in-Furness|Custom House]] and a similar Lazer Quest, [[escape room]] and play centre in the former Hitchens building on Buccleuch Street.\n\n===Regeneration and redevelopment===\n[[File:Central Yard Facility Barrow July 2017.jpg|thumb|right|The Central Yard Facility, photographed in July 2017, is at the centre of BAE Systems' \u00a3300 million redevelopment]]\n[[File:Abbey Road and Holker Street, Barrow.PNG|thumb|[[Duke of Edinburgh Hotel]] and [[Emlyn Hughes House]]]]\n\nUrban regeneration has been ongoing in Barrow since the 1990s. [[Portland Walk Shopping Centre]] opened in 1998 anchored by [[Debenhams]] as part of a major reconstruction of Barrow town centre. Around the same time the [[Hindpool Retail Parks]] and [[Dock Museum]] were constructed over various former industrial sites in Barrow, including the [[dry dock]], the [[Barrow Jute Works]] and the [[Barrow Hematite Steel Company|Barrow Steel Works]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Barrow Dock Museum|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/enjoy_cumbria/places/barrow_dock_museum.shtml|publisher=BBC Cumbria|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> Recent construction projects in the town also include the \u00a343 million expansion of [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]]'s Channelside campus,<ref name=Redevelopmentcollege>{{cite web|url=http://www.furness.ac.uk/new-build|title=New build|publisher=Furness College|accessdate=26 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701184904/http://www.furness.ac.uk/new-build|archive-date=1 July 2013|url-status = dead}}</ref> \u00a322.5 million [[Furness Academy]] new build,<ref name=Redevelopmentacademy>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/furness-academy-s-22-5m-vision-finally-to-become-reality-1.913623?referrerPath=|title=Furness Academy's \u00a322.5 million vision to finally become reality|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=26 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130628032403/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/furness-academy-s-22-5m-vision-finally-to-become-reality-1.913623?referrerPath=|archivedate=28 June 2013}}</ref> \u00a314.5 million central Barrow flood relief scheme,<ref name=Floodrelief>{{cite web|url=http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2009/UU_Barrow_2009.pdf|title=Barrow DG5 Flood Relief Scheme|publisher=waterprojectsonline.coml|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> \u00a38.5 million Barrow police station,<ref name=Redevelopmentpolice>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/home/multimillion-pound-plans-for-barrow-police-station-unveiled-1.1065289?referrerPath=home|title=Multi million pound plans for Barrow police station revealed|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=26 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130628032342/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/home/multimillion-pound-plans-for-barrow-police-station-unveiled-1.1065289?referrerPath=home|archivedate=28 June 2013}}</ref> \u00a35 million town centre redevelopment scheme,<ref name=Redevelopmentcentre>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitasymonds.co.uk/news__events/news/barrow_town_centre_scheme_on_s.aspx|title=Barrow town centre scheme on schedule|publisher=Capita Symonds|accessdate=26 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506111214/http://capitasymonds.co.uk/news__events/news/barrow_town_centre_scheme_on_s.aspx|archivedate=6 May 2013}}</ref> \u00a34 million Scottish Power wind farm operations centre<ref name=\"Windoperations\"/> as well as the North Central Renewal Area, shake up of the town's residential and retirement homes and a number of large-scale hotel schemes catering for the influx of contractors working for BAE Systems (namely [[Holiday Inn Express]], [[Premier Inn]] and [[Wetherspoon]]).<ref name=Redevelopmentnorthcentral>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/PDF/NorthCentralNRAAug2008.pdf|title=North Central Renewal Area|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|accessdate=26 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714202300/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/PDF/NorthCentralNRAAug2008.pdf|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[The Waterfront Barrow-in-Furness|The Waterfront]] is an ambitious ongoing \u00a3200 million dockland regeneration project, which began in 2007. The project includes a new Barrow Marina Village which will incorporate an \u00a38 million 400-berth marina, 650 homes, restaurants, shops, hotels and a new state of the art bridge across Cavendish Dock. A large watersports centre is also proposed, with the possibility of a cruise ship terminal. Some cruise ships are already scheduled to dock in Barrow, mainly for tourists to visit the Lake District, although there is no official cruise ship terminal yet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Little-Known Barrow Plans British Fanfare for Princess Cruise Passengers|url=http://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/news.cfm?ID=3166|publisher=Cruise Critic|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> Developments have stalled since 2010 when the [[Northwest Regional Development Agency]]  was disbanded and essential government funding was lost. Despite this Barrow Borough Council has since purchased land needed to make the development a reality and currently controls 95% of the site.<ref name=Marinafuture>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/work-on-barrow-s-marina-vision-could-begin-within-three-years-1.1161141|title=Work on Barrow's Marina Vision Could Begin 'Within Three Years'|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=11 September 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911212037/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/work-on-barrow-s-marina-vision-could-begin-within-three-years-1.1161141|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref> The executive director of the council has stated construction of the Waterfront could resume by 2017 as economic prospects improve and has pledged funds to conduct a market testing exercise. The allocation of Growth Deal investment (2014\u20132021) will make improvements to the Barrow Waterfront Enterprise Zone far more secure <ref name=Marinafuture/> In 2014 a \u00a3300 million investment into the shipyard was announced by BAE Systems, in anticipation of the [[trident replacement|new generation of UK nuclear submarines]].<ref name=\"Shipyardexpansion1\"/><ref name=Shipyardexpansion2/> Construction will take up to eight years and create thousands of new jobs at the shipyard thereafter.<ref name=Shipyardexpansion1/> Amongst proposals are an extension to the DDH complex and new buildings in the central yard area off Bridge Road on Barrow Island (a site formerly mooted for a huge construction hall for the construction of [[Queen Elizabeth-class aircraft carrier|''Queen Elizabeth''-class aircraft carrier]] sections which the yard failed to win contracts for), these will house pressure hull units ready for shot blasting and painting, and be a place for joining submarine equipment modules.<ref name=Shipyardexpansion2>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/bae-systems-development-will-change-barrow-skyline-1.1122540|title=BAE Systems Development will change Barrow skyline|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=13 March 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313165418/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/bae-systems-development-will-change-barrow-skyline-1.1122540|archivedate=13 March 2014}}</ref> Redevelopment of the 5.8 hectare central yard area was completed in 2018 and is dominated by the [[Central Yard Complex Facility]] which measures {{convert|178|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|94|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide and {{convert|41|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall, only 10% smaller than the volume of the pre-expansion Devonshire Dock Hall.\n\nOther large-scale developments associated with BAE include a {{convert|30,000|sqm|sqft|abbr=on}} logistics centre which was constructed in the Waterfront Business Park in 2015 and a {{convert|8,100|sqm|sqft|abbr=on}} central training facility which is proposed at Buccleuch Dock Road.\n\n===Other===\nOther major employers include the [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]], through [[Furness General Hospital]], which employs 1,800 staff,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.nwra.gov.uk/downloads/documents/imported/321089760698.doc | title=Cumbria Prosperity Priorities Summit held on 2 April 2004 | publisher=North West Regional Assembly | accessdate=20 August 2007 | format=DOC | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927121818/http://www.nwra.gov.uk/downloads/documents/imported/321089760698.doc | archivedate=27 September 2007 |url-status = dead| df=dmy-all }}</ref> the [[Kimberly Clark]] paper mill, which has 400 employees,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.furnessenterprise.co.uk/furness_enterprise_sectors.asp?menuID=13&ID=IS6 | title=Furness Enterprise \u2013 Fast Moving Consumer Goods | publisher=Furness Enterprise | accessdate=20 August 2007 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929040235/http://www.furnessenterprise.co.uk/furness_enterprise_sectors.asp?menuID=13&ID=IS6 | archivedate=29 September 2007 |url-status = dead| df=dmy-all }}</ref> BAE Systems' [[BAE Systems Land & Armaments|Land and Armaments]] division, [[Furness Building Society]] which is one of the 20 largest of its kind, [[Cumbria County Council]] and [[Barrow-in-Furness (borough)|Barrow Borough Council]]. Amongst many retailers that have established themselves in Barrow, the furniture store [[Stollers]] is noted as being one of the largest shops of its kind in the UK.\n\n===Employment===\n[[File:Craven House, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|[[Craven House]] is headquarters of [[James Fisher & Sons]], the only Barrow company on the [[London Stock Exchange]]]] [[File:Tesco Barrow, Cumbria.jpg|thumb|right|[[Tesco]] is a significant employer, with several outlets across Barrow]]\nAccording to the 2011 census, 78.2% of males aged 16\u201364 and females aged 16\u201359 in Barrow were economically active. This figure is higher than the North West and England averages.<ref name=Employment>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=3&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=4&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1367432044166&enc=1|title=Key Figures for Economic Deprivation|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref> 73.8% of the population was employed, which again is higher than regional and national averages; the unemployment rate stood at 5.6% which is lower than both averages.<ref name=Employment/> Despite this the percentage of people claiming key benefits, which is independent of the unemployment figure, is much higher than both averages at 21.0%, or almost a quarter of all Barrovians of working age.<ref name=Employment/> The most common form of benefit received was the [[Incapacity Benefit]], claimed by 11.0% of the adult population, while 4.0% claimed [[Jobseeker's Allowance]], which is on a par with the national average.<ref name=Employment/>\n\nThe list below shows how many people were employed in certain sectors according to the 2011 census. Little change has occurred over the 10-year period since the previous census; Barrow still has a much higher percentage of workers in the manufacturing sector than the national average, ranking third in 2011 behind [[Corby]], Northamptonshire and [[Borough of Pendle|Pendle]], Lancashire.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=9&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1367430603744&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2538 |publisher=statistics.gov.uk |title=Area: Barrow-in-Furness (Local Authority) |accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=Employmenttrends>{{cite web|url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/2011-census-analysis/170-years-of-industry/170-years-of-industrial-changeponent.html|title=170 Years of Industrial Change across England and Wales|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref> South West Cumbria has one of the UK's most self-contained workforces, and Barrow itself has the sixth lowest proportion of people who travel outside of the country for work.<ref name=othercommute>{{cite web|url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/dcp171776_357812.pdf|title=2011 Census Analysis \u2013 Distance Travelled to Work|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> In 2001, 76% of the working age population in Barrow commuted within {{convert|5|km}} for work, when compared to the England average of 54%.<ref name=Traveltowork>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1006&k=distance&m=0&r=1&s=1435005696594&enc=1&domainId=16&dsFamilyId=189|title=Distance Travelled to Work \u2013 Workplace Population, 2001 (UV80)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref> A significant proportion of the town's population are employed at the [[Sellafield]] nuclear facility.\n* Manufacturing: 6,570 employed (21.0% of the town's working population)\n* Wholesale and retail trade: 4,728 (15.1%)\n* Human health and social work: 4,539 (14.5%)\n* Construction: 2,387 (7.6%)\n* Education: 2,381 (7.6%)\n* Accommodation and food service activities: 1,962 (6.3%)\n* Public administration and defence: 1,913 (6.1%)\n* Transport and storage: 1,296 (4.1%)\n* Administrative and support service: 1,055 (3.4%)\n* Professional, scientific and technical: 1,000 (3.2%)\n* Information and communication: 496 (1.6%)\n* Financial and insurance: 492 (1.6%)\n* Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply: 441 (1.4%)\n* Water supply: 264 (0.8%)\n* Real estate: 221 (0.7%)\n* Mining and quarrying: 165 (0.5%)\n* Agriculture, forestry and fishing: 122 (0.4%)\n* Other: 1,225 (3.9%)\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Road===\n[[File:Crook Scar - geograph.org.uk - 160218.jpg|thumb|right|[[Walney Bridge]] (officially Jubilee Bridge) links Barrow Island to Walney Island]]\n\nBarrow's principal road link is the [[A590 road|A590]]. This runs to Barrow from the [[M6 motorway]] via [[Ulverston]], skirting the southern [[Lake District]].<ref name=\"Map\">{{Cite web|url= http://maps.google.co.uk/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Barrow+in+Furness&ie=UTF8&ll=54.173287,-2.999268&spn=0.205782,0.6427&z=11&om=1|title= Barrow area map|accessdate=26 August 2007 |format= Flash|work= [[Google Maps]]|publisher= Google Maps}}</ref> Just north of Barrow is the southern end of the [[A595 road|A595]], linking the town to [[West Cumbria]].<ref name=\"Map\"/> The A5087 connects Barrow's southern suburbs to Ulverston via a scenic coastal route. [[Abbey Road, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey Road]] is the principal road through central Barrow, whilst [[Walney Bridge]] connects Barrow Island to [[Walney Island]].\n\nThe possibility of a bridge link over [[Morecambe Bay]] is occasionally raised, and feasibility studies have been carried out.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Hetherington | first = Peter | title = Council gives thumbs up to <span style=\"white-space:nowrap\">12&nbsp;mile&nbsp;(19&nbsp;km)</span> bridge for Morecambe Bay |work=The Guardian |location=London | date = 19 May 2004 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk_news/story/0,3604,1220030,00.html | accessdate =9 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Bus===\nBus services within the town are operated by [[Stagecoach North West]]. There is no specifically designated bus station, although many bus routes start and end near the town hall. The original bus station, since demolished, was known for its role in a 1970s television commercial for [[Chewits]] sweets.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/content/articles/2006/03/30/cumbriaonfilm_chewits_feature.shtml | title=Barrow Chewits ad | publisher=BBC Cumbria | accessdate =17 July 2007 }}</ref> As well as local suburban and village services, longer-distance buses run to [[Millom]], [[Ulverston]], [[Bowness-on-Windermere|Bowness]], [[Windermere, Cumbria (town)|Windermere]] and [[Kendal]].\n\n===Rail===\n[[File:Barrow-in-Furness Station, Cumbria.jpg|thumb|left|[[Barrow-in-Furness railway station]] viewed from [[Abbey Road, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey Road]]]]\n[[Barrow-in-Furness railway station]] provides connections to [[Whitehaven]], [[Workington]] and [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] to the north, via the [[Cumbrian Coast Line]], and to [[Ulverston]], [[Grange-over-Sands]] and [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] to the east, via the [[Furness Line]] \u2013 both of which connect to the [[West Coast Mainline]]. Numerous daily trains run to [[Manchester Piccadilly station|Manchester]]. The station handles over 600,000 passengers annually. Barrow has a second railway station, [[Roose railway station|Roose]], which serves [[Roose|the suburb of the same name]].\n\n[[Furness Abbey railway station|Furness Abbey]], Barrow's third main line station, closed in 1950. There was also a station on [[Island Road railway station|Barrow Island]], for commuters between the shipyard and nearby towns served by the Furness Railway. This railway link was severed in 1966 when the famous cradle bridge across the docks was closed permanently for safety reasons. There were also stations at [[Piel railway station|Piel]], Rabbit Hill, [[Rampside railway station|Rampside]], [[Ramsden Dock railway station|Ramsden Dock]] and [[Barrow-in-Furness Strand railway station|Strand]].\n\nBetween 1885 and 1932, the [[Barrow-in-Furness Tramways Company]] operated a [[double-decker tram]] service over several miles, primarily around central Barrow, Barrow Island and Hindpool.\n\n===Air===\n[[Barrow/Walney Island Airport]] ([[IATA airport code]]: BWF, [[ICAO]]: EGNL) is a former commercial airport and [[Royal Air Force]] base currently owned by BAE Systems which operates two [[Beechcraft King Air|Beechkraft King Air]] B200 and one B250 aircraft which fly to various destinations across the UK every weekday, including Bristol, Glasgow, London and Manchester. The airport's runways take on a triangular form, the longest runway is almost {{convert|4000|ft|m}}. The airport was expanded by BAE in 2018 including the construction of a new terminal building, hangar and control tower.\n\n[[Manchester Airport]] is the closest major airport, with direct links to Barrow railway station and about two hours away by road.\n\nIn 2018 a [[heliport]] was built on a site adjacent to Park Road, Ormsgill for energy firm [[\u00d8rsted (company)|\u00d8rsted]] and to support the offshore energy sector.\n\n===Sea===\nDespite being one of the UK's leading shipbuilding centres, the [[Associated British Ports]]' [[Port of Barrow]] is only a minor port. Historically, the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet]] and the [[Barrow Steam Navigation Company]] (a subsidiary of the Furness Railway and later [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]) operated a number of steamers and passenger ferry services between Rampside and [[Ramsden Dock]] and [[Ardrossan]] (Scotland), [[Belfast]] (Northern Ireland), [[Blackpool]], [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] (Isle of Man), [[Fleetwood]] and [[Heysham]].<ref name=Ferry>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/go-anywhere-on-a-boat-from-barrow-1.116441?referrerPath=home/2.4856 |title=Go Anywhere On a Boat From Barrow |publisher=North West Evening Mail |accessdate=11 January 2015 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112185109/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/go-anywhere-on-a-boat-from-barrow-1.116441?referrerPath=home%2F2.4856 |archivedate=12 January 2015  }}</ref> All services had ceased operation by the mid-20th century.\n\nFor a short period during the early 1880s, transatlantic travel was possible from the town. [[Anchor Line (steamship company)|The Anchor Line]] operated a fortnightly service utilising three of its steamships, ''Alexandria'', ''Caledonia'' and ''Columbia'', between Barrow and [[New York City]] via [[Dublin]]. There are proposals to construct a cruise ship terminal in Barrow as part of the Waterfront redevelopment project.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/4706191.stm | title=Town chosen for cruise ship terminal |publisher=BBC | accessdate=15 June 2007 | date=22 July 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n[[File:Holkerstreetmainstand.jpg|thumb|[[Holker Street]], the home of Barrow A.F.C.]]\n\n===Football===\n\n{{Main|Barrow A.F.C.|Holker Old Boys F.C.}}\n[[Barrow A.F.C.]] are in the [[Conference National]] division of English football.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=151|title= Sports in Barrow and Furness|accessdate= 19 August 2007|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070828161827/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=151|archivedate= 28 August 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The team, founded in 1901, are nicknamed the Bluebirds and play their home games at the [[Holker Street]] stadium.<ref name=\"Bluebirds\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/sport/clubs/barrow/12_2003.shtml|title= Barrow Football Club|accessdate=19 August 2007 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> The side were members of the [[Football League]] until they failed to be re-elected in 1972.<ref name=\"Bluebirds\"/> In 1990, they won the [[FA Trophy]] beating [[Leek Town F.C.|Leek Town]] 3\u20130 in the final at [[Wembley Stadium (1924)|Wembley Stadium]], London.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.napit.co.uk/viewus/infobank/football/fatophy.php|title= The FA Trophy|accessdate=19 August 2007 |publisher= Napit.co.uk| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070823063143/http://www.napit.co.uk/viewus/infobank/football/fatophy.php| archivedate= 23 August 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> Twenty years later, on 8 May 2010, [[Barrow A.F.C.|Barrow]] repeated the feat, beating [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage Borough]] 2\u20131 after extra time.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFATrophy/Match%20Centre/Final%202010/080510|title= Walker wins it for hometown Barrow|accessdate=8 May 2010 |publisher= TheFA.com}}</ref> Barrow were bought by Texas-based businessman Paul Casson in 2014 with a five-year plan of returning the team to the Football League and completely redeveloping Holker Street, including the addition of three new stands.\n\nFootball players born in Barrow include England internationals [[Emlyn Hughes]]<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2004/11/10/db1001.xml|title=  Emlyn Hughes Obituary|accessdate=8 July 2007 |date=  11 November 2004|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London }}</ref> and [[Gary M. Stevens|Gary Stevens]],<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.toffeeweb.com/history/legends/Stevens.asp|title= Stevens, Gary 1981\u201388|accessdate=8 July 2007 |last= Pike|first= Richard|author2=Poutianinen, Marko|year= 1999|work= Hall of Fame|publisher= ToffeeWeb| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070611233558/http://toffeeweb.com/history/legends/Stevens.asp| archivedate= 11 June 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> as well as [[Harry Hadley]],<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.englandstats.com/playerreport.php?pid=424 | title = Player Report \u2013 Harry Hadley | accessdate =21 July 2007 |publisher= EnglandStats.com}}</ref> and [[Vic Metcalfe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.englandstats.com/playerreport.php?pid=659 |title=Player Profile \u2013 Vic Metcalfe |accessdate=7 August 2007 |publisher=EnglandStats.com }}</ref>\nOf current professional footballers, [[Wayne Curtis]],<ref>{{Cite news| title=Wayne makes Wembley History | date=21 May 2007 | publisher=[[CN Group]] | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/unknown/viewarticle.aspx?id=500925 | work =[[North West Evening Mail]] | accessdate =7 August 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926211331/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/unknown/viewarticle.aspx?id=500925 |archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] striker, and Iran Under-20 and [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] winger Shana Haji<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.persianmirror.com/Article_det.cfm?id=1367&getArticleCategory=42&getArticleSubCategory=4|title= Shana Haji, the first Iranian player in Scotland|accessdate= 21 June 2007|last= Dastafshan|first= Afshin|publisher= Persian Mirror|url-status = dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010053/http://www.persianmirror.com/Article_det.cfm?id=1367&getArticleCategory=42&getArticleSubCategory=4|archivedate= 27 September 2007|df= dmy-all}}</ref> both hail from the town.\n\nHolker Old Boys F.C., based at Rakesmoor Lane, are the town's second most successful football team, and they play in the [[North West Counties Football League]] Division One.\n\n===Rugby===\n{{Main|Barrow Raiders}}\n[[File:Craven Park, Barrow.jpg|thumb|left|[[Craven Park (Barrow)|Craven Park]], the home of Barrow Raiders]]\n[[Rugby league]] is a well-established sport and the town is considered as one of the game's traditional heartlands at professional and amateur levels.<ref name=\"rugby\">{{Cite news|first=Andy |last=Wilson |title=RUGBY LEAGUE: CARLISLE MERGER SIGNALS RETHINK |work=The Guardian |location=UK |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=16 October 1997|page=27 |quote=Now Carlisle's decision to move in with Barrow, a traditional hotbed of league where the amateur game remains as strong as ever, may be followed by a new club from [[South Wales]] entering Super League next year.}}</ref> The professional team, [[Barrow Raiders]], whose home games are at [[Craven Park (Barrow)|Craven Park]], played in the [[Co-operative Championship|Championship]] until 2011 but as of 2012, they now operate in the league below, known as [[RFL League 1|League 1]]. In the 1950s the side played in three [[Challenge Cup]] finals, winning the last of these against [[Workington Town]]. In the 1997 reorganisation of the sport the original Barrow RLFC team merged with [[Carlisle RLFC|Carlisle Border Raiders]] to form Barrow Border Raiders,<ref>{{Cite news|first=Andy |last=Wilson |title=RUGBY LEAGUE: CARLISLE MERGER SIGNALS RETHINK |work=The Guardian |location=UK |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=16 October 1997|page=27 |quote=CARLISLE and Barrow have decided to merge into a new club, Barrow Border Raiders, with repercussions extending well beyond the Second Division and Cumbria.}}</ref> with the word \"border\" later dropped. Players who were born in the town and played at a professional level include brothers [[Ade Gardner|Ade]]<ref>{{cite news| title = Gardner out for indefinite period |work=BBC News | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_league/6599411.stm | date = 27 April 2007 | accessdate =21 July 2007 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070711031424/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_league/6599411.stm| archivedate= 11 July 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> and [[Mat Gardner]]<ref>{{Cite news|first=David |last=Burke |title= A Welcome MAT for My Mate ADE; HUDDERSFIELD GIANTS V ST HELENS, TOMORROW, KICK-OFF 3&nbsp;pm |work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |publisher=[[Mirror Group Newspapers]] | page=57 |date=11 March 2006|quote=Mat, brought up in Barrow with Ade, said: \"It's always been a dream of mine to play against my elder brother and this could be the time it becomes a reality. There's also a big chance we could be meeting head-on on the wing and that would be fantastic. I was pleased with my performance at [[Wakefield Trinity]], I just hope Jon Sharp was pleased too \u2013 that's obviously the key to me playing against Saints.\"}}</ref> and [[Willie Horne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/goingout/viewarticle.aspx?id=326017|title= Vickerstown Cricket Club, Walney|accessdate=21 June 2007 |date=  26 January 2006|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926211104/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/goingout/viewarticle.aspx?id=326017| archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> The latter captained Barrow to their Challenge Cup victory and represented Great Britain at an international level. He was inducted into the \"Barrow Hall of Fame\" along with former Barrow players [[Phil Jackson (rugby league born 1932)|Phil Jackson]] and [[Jimmy Lewthwaite]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rl1908.com/Legends/jackson.htm |title=Rugby League History \u2013 Interview with Phil Jackson |accessdate=4 August 2007 |last=Fagan |first=Sean |work=RL1908.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060511184546/http://www.rl1908.com/Legends/jackson.htm |archivedate=11 May 2006 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nAt a local level, eight amateur rugby league teams participate in the [[Barrow & District League]]. They include Askam, Barrow Island, Dalton, Hindpool, Milliom, Roose Pioneers, Ulverston and Walney\n\n===Golf===\n\nBarrow is home to two large golf clubs. Barrow Golf Club, founded in 1922, is situated in [[Hawcoat]] and covers some {{convert|6209|yd|m|}} with 18 holes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englishgolf-courses.co.uk/cumbria/barrow.php|title=Barrow Golf Club|website=www.englishgolf-courses.co.uk}}</ref> Furness Golf Club, founded in 1872, is the sixth oldest golf club in England and is possibly the more famous of the two. It is located on [[Walney Island]], just {{convert|50|yd|m|}} from the [[Irish Sea]]. It also offers an 18-hole course, a shop and other facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golftoday.co.uk/clubhouse/coursedir/cumbria/furness.html|title=Furness Golf Club,Barrow In Furness,Cumbria,England|website=www.golftoday.co.uk|access-date=10 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517135054/http://www.golftoday.co.uk/clubhouse/coursedir/cumbria/furness.html|archive-date=17 May 2008|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Furness Golf Centre is located on the outskirts of Barrow close to Roanhead and is home to a 14-bay driving range, golf shop, swing studio and the Fairway Hotel.<ref name=Fairway>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairway-hotel.co.uk/index.php|title=Fairway Hotel and Furness Golf Centre|publisher=Fairway Hotel|accessdate=6 April 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404005520/http://www.fairway-hotel.co.uk/index.php|archivedate=4 April 2013}}</ref> The hoaxer [[Maurice Flitcroft]], known as the \"world's worst golfer\" lived and worked in the town.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Murray|first1=Scott|last2=Farnaby|first2=Simon|title=The Phantom of the Open: Maurice Flitcroft, The World's Worst Golfer|date=2011|publisher=Yellow Jersey Press|isbn=978-0224083171}}</ref>\n\n===Motor sports===\n\nBarrow has staged [[Motorcycle speedway|speedway]] racing at three venues since the pioneer days in the late 1920s. The first track was at Holker Street. This venue had a revival for a short spell in the early to mid-1970s being utilised by the short-lived [[Barrow Bombers]]. In 1930 the sport moved to Little Park but this a somewhat hazy venue. The sport had a revival in 1978 at Park Avenue Industrial Estate but this was relatively short lived.\n\n====Bike racing====\n\nBarrow has produced a number of noteworthy motorcyclists throughout the years, such as Manx Grand Prix winner Eddie Crooks, TT Rider Dan Stewart, Speedway ace [[Adam Roynon]] and multiple British Sandtrack Champion John Pepper.\n\n====Karting====\n\nKart racer Kristian Brierley<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kartingmagazine.com/news/maxxis-tkm-festival-double-honours-bonus/attachment/kristian-brierley/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=21 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810144546/http://www.kartingmagazine.com/news/maxxis-tkm-festival-double-honours-bonus/attachment/kristian-brierley/ |archive-date=10 August 2018 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> received national attention after successfully winning the internationally televised TKM Karting Festival in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwemail.co.uk/sport/other-sport/junior-sport/16463770.askam-speedster-earns-national-karting-title/|title=Askam speedster earns national karting title|website=The Mail}}</ref>\n\nHe followed this up by winning the opening round of the British Championship in 2016.\n\nBrierley's first cousin Lydia Burney has also competed at national level in karting, as have multiple other 'Barrovians' such as Max Davis, Daniel Pepper,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwemail.co.uk/sport/other-sport/motor-sport/16460258.kirkby-karter-dan-revved-up-for-shot-at-super-stardom/|title=Kirkby karter Dan revved up for shot at Super-stardom|website=The Mail}}</ref> Kieran Pepper, Oliver Dilks and Jake Calvert.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwemail.co.uk/sport/other-sport/junior-sport/16463928.barrow-teenager-is-the-karting-king-of-britain/|title=Barrow teenager is the karting king of Britain|website=The Mail}}</ref>\n\n===Other sports===\n\nBarrow is home to the [[Walney Terriers]] [[American Football]] club, formed in 2011 the club originally trained at Memorial Fields on Walney Island before establishing training grounds elsewhere in Barrow and Ulverston. The Terriers play in the North West conference of the [[British American Football Association|BAFA]]'s National League alongside the likes of the [[Manchester Titans]] and [[Merseyside Nighthawks]].\n\nOne of the town's most notable annual sporting events is the [[Keswick to Barrow]] (K2B), a {{convert|40|mi|km|adj=on|sigfig=1}} walking and running event that has taken place every year since 1967 between [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]] and Barrow. The event has raised millions for charity and regularly sees in excess of 3,000 participants.<ref name=\"K2B\">{{cite web|title=About The Walk|publisher=Keswick to Barrow|date=|url=https://www.keswick2barrow.co.uk/about.asp|accessdate=3 May 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219014716/http://www.keswick2barrow.co.uk/about.asp|archivedate=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarrow Born Orienteer and Fell Runner Carl Hill was selected to carry the olympic torch for a stage through Morecambe in the buildup to the 2012 summer Olympics. He was nominated for this honor by his father David Hill who was proud of his sons accomplishments in running for England and Great Britain in Orienteering whilst also provided a large portion of his time to getting kids into sport.\n\n==Culture==\nBarrow, although one of the country's smallest local authorities, contains a wealth of natural and built heritage assets, which includes 274 [[Listed building|Listed Buildings]] and four [[Site of Special Scientific Interest|SSSIs]]. The 2016 Heritage Index formed by the [[Royal Society of Arts]] and the [[Heritage Lottery Fund]] placed the borough as sixth highest of 325 English districts for \u2018assets\u2019 with especially high scores relating to nationally important landscape and natural heritage assets and industrial heritage assets.<ref name=HeritageIndex>{{cite web|url=https://www.thersa.org/action-and-research/rsa-projects/public-services-and-communities-folder/heritage-and-place/England/|title=Explore the Heritage Index for England|publisher=The Royal Society for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\n{{See also|Listed buildings in Barrow-in-Furness|List of tallest buildings and structures in Barrow-in-Furness}}\n{{Panorama\n | image      = File:Barrow Panorama 1 (June 17).jpg\n | caption    = View of Barrow looking south from the [[Barrow Hematite Steel Company#Legacy|Slag Bank]] including (left to right) Fells of the [[Lake District]], [[Thorncliffe Cemetery and Crematorium|Thorncliffe Crematorium]], [[Ormsgill]], [[Holker Street]], [[Hindpool]], [[St. James' Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. James' Church]], [[Piel Castle]], the [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|Town Hall]], BAE Systems Central Yard Facility and [[Devonshire Dock Hall]], the new Barrow Police Station, [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]], [[Walney Bridge]] and Walney Channel, [[Vickerstown]], the [[Irish Sea]], [[Walney Wind Farm|Walney]] and [[Ormonde Wind Farm]]s and [[Barrow/Walney Island Airport]]\n | height     = 250\n}}\n{{Panorama\n | image      = File:Barrow panorama from Walney July 2017.jpg\n | caption    = View of Barrow looking east across Walney Channel including (left to right) Fells of the [[Lake District]], Slag Bank, Furness College, St. James' Church, the [[Dock Museum]], [[Devonshire Dock Hall]], BAE Systems Central Yard Facility and [[Walney Bridge]]\n | height     = 250\n}}\n[[File:Vickerstown and Walney Channel.jpg|thumb|right|[[Vickerstown]], a [[model village]] built on Walney Island around 1900]]\n[[File:Barrowterracota.png|thumb|right|Red brick and terracotta were popular building materials at the turn of the 20th century in Barrow \u2013 a style which is imitated to this day]]\n\nBarrow is one of Britain's few planned towns, and the spacious tree-lined avenues within the oldest parts of the town (including Central Barrow, Hindpool and Salthouse) are more akin to the layout of a much larger city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enjoyengland.com/destinations/find/englands-northwest/cumbria/barrow-in-furness.aspx |title=Destination guide for Barrow-in-Furness |accessdate=8 August 2007 |publisher=Enjoy England | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070711101803/http://www.enjoyengland.com/destinations/find/englands-northwest/cumbria/barrow-in-furness.aspx| archivedate= 11 July 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> The town centre is distinguished by its [[Victorian era|Victorian]] and [[Edwardian era]] civic buildings, such as the [[Barrow-in-Furness Town Hall|Town Hall]], [[Barrow-in-Furness Main Public Library|Main Public Library]], former [[Nan Tait Centre|Technical School]], former [[Barrow-in-Furness Central Fire Station|Central Fire Station]], [[Salvation Army]] Building, [[Custom House, Barrow-in-Furness|Custom House]], [[National Westminster Bank, Barrow-in-Furness|National Westminster Bank]], [[The Duke of Edinburgh Hotel]], [[St. George's Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. George's Church]], [[St. Mary of Furness Roman Catholic Church|St. Mary's RC Church]] and [[St. James' Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. James' Church]]. Oppositely, several distinctive buildings have been demolished in Barrow since the mid-20th century as a result of neglect or war damage, amongst the most iconic are [[Abbot's Wood, Cumbria|Abbots Wood]], [[Barrow-in-Furness railway station|Barrow Central Railway Station]], [[Infield House]], [[St. George's Square, Barrow-in-Furness#North Lonsdale Hospital|North Lonsdale Hospital]], [[Scotch Buildings]] and the Waverley Hotel. Lancaster architects [[Sharpe, Paley and Austin]] were prolific throughout the development of Barrow. A number of Barrow's landmark buildings were constructed from locally sourced sandstone, evident from the high number of brown and red coloured stone buildings in the town. Similar materials were used in a number of local buildings in the early 20th century, and often accompanied by terracotta. There are also an increasing number of modern office buildings as well as the shipyard's construction halls which dominate much of Barrow's skyline. Despite much of Barrow having been constructed from the late 19th to mid 20th centuries, architectural styles vary greatly across the town from the [[Art Deco]] [[John Whinnerah Institute]] to the [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine style]] [[St. John's Church, Barrow-in-Furness|St. John's Church]], [[Elizabethan architecture|Neo-Elizabethan]] [[Abbey House, Barrow-in-Furness|Abbey House]] and [[Tudor Revival architecture|Tudor Revival]] [[Vickerstown]] estate.\n\nBarrow has 8 [[Grade I listed buildings]], 15 [[Listed building|Grade II*]] and 249 [[Grade II]] buildings. The majority of Grade I listed buildings and structures are in and around the Furness Abbey complex while many Grade II* listed buildings in the town are 19th century tenements on Barrow Island including the [[Devonshire Buildings]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2758 |title=Listed Buildings |accessdate=16 August 2007 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030802/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=2758 |archivedate=28 September 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> There are a number of [[Conservation Area (United Kingdom)|Conservation Areas]] across Barrow named as such for their architectural or historical significance, they include [[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]], [[Biggar, Cumbria|Biggar]], [[Central Barrow]], [[Furness Abbey]], [[North Scale]], North and South [[Vickerstown]] and [[St. George's Square, Barrow-in-Furness|St. George's Square]].<ref name=Conservation>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=1696|title=Conservation Areas in the Borough|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|accessdate=9 June 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121123213335/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=1696|archivedate=23 November 2012}}</ref> Historically Barrow's skyline was dominated by shipyard cranes and industrial chimneys, although little evidence of this remains in the present day with the last [[Crane (machine)#Hammerhead crane|hammerhead crane]] \u2013 the iconic yellow crane of [[Buccleuch Dock]] \u2013 being dismantled in 2011, despite calls for listing status like the smaller [[Titan Clydebank]] in Glasgow. The tallest building in Barrow is [[Devonshire Dock Hall]] at {{convert|51|m|ft|0}}. Also worth of note are the turbines of [[Ormonde Wind Farm]] located just off the coast of Barrow which stand at {{convert|152|m|ft|0}}.\n\nIn terms of housing, the majority of dwellings in Barrow are Victorian [[Terraced house|terraces]]. At 47.0% of local housing stock in 2011, the figure is much higher than England's average of 24.5%. 29.7% of dwellings are [[semi-detached]], 12.09% [[Single-family detached home|detached]] and 10.2% flats, maisonettes or apartments.<ref name=Housing>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=6275013&c=barrow&d=13&e=7&g=6411253&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1365528720388&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2570|title=Accommodation Type \u2013 Households, 2011|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref> Great variety in housing styles is a feature across central Barrow, Barrow Island, Hindpool, and Vickerstown.  Most were built around a [[Grid plan|grid design]] in accordance with plans drawn up by James Ramsden.\n\n===Arts===\n\n'''Music'''<br />\nBarrow has produced several musical performers of note. They include [[Thomas Round]], a singer and actor in D'Oyly Carte productions of [[Savoy Opera]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://diamond.boisestate.edu/GaS/whowaswho/R/RoundThomas.htm |title=Thomas Round |accessdate=7 August 2007 |publisher=Boise State University |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060903104943/http://diamond.boisestate.edu/gas/whowaswho/R/RoundThomas.htm |archive-date=3 September 2006 |url-status = dead}}</ref> as well as [[Glenn Cornick]], the original bass guitarist in the rock band [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.j-tull.com/musicians/pastmembers/glenncornick.html |title=Glenn Cornick |accessdate=7 August 2007 |publisher=The Official Jethro Tull Website |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815135747/http://www.j-tull.com/musicians/pastmembers/glenncornick.html |archivedate=15 August 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> Paul MacKenzie, bass player with 1980s [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]]-based thrash metal band [[Xentrix]], is from Barrow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metalist.co.il/interviewprivate.asp?id=141&lang=eng |title=Metalist Magazine |accessdate=10 January 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716200952/http://www.metalist.co.il/interviewprivate.asp?id=141&lang=eng |archivedate=16 July 2011  }}</ref> More recently, hip-hop DJ and record producer [[Aim (musician)|Aim]] has had considerable commercial success.<ref>{{Cite news| first=David | last=Sue | title=Superstar DJ continues to Aim high | date=23 June 2006 | publisher=Guardian Media Group | url =http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/rock_and_pop/s/216/216434_superstar_dj_continues_to_aim_high.html | work =[[Manchester Evening News]] | accessdate =7 August 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930165611/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/rock_and_pop/s/216/216434_superstar_dj_continues_to_aim_high.html| archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref>[[File:The Forum, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|left|[[Forum 28|The Forum]], Barrow's largest theatre and arts venue]]\n\n'''Expressive arts'''<br />\nSeveral notables in Art and Literature have come from Barrow. Artist [[Keith Tyson]], the 2002 [[Turner Prize]] winner, was born in nearby [[Ulverston]], attended the Barrow-in-Furness College of Engineering and worked at the then [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering|VSEL]] shipyard.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://collection.britishcouncil.org/collection/artist/5/19092 |title=Keith Tyson Biography |accessdate=4 August 2007 |publisher=[[British Council]] |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629202045/http://collection.britishcouncil.org/collection/artist/5/19092 |archivedate=29 June 2011  }}</ref> [[Constance Spry]], the author and florist who revolutionised interior design in the 1930s, and 1940s, moved to the town with her son Anthony during World War I to work as a welfare supervisor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.designmuseum.org/design/constance-spry |title=Constance Spry / Florist, Author + Social Reformer (1886\u20131960) |accessdate=4 August 2007 |publisher=Design Museum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070806082527/http://www.designmuseum.org/design/constance-spry |archivedate=6 August 2007 |url-status = dead}}</ref> [[Peter Purves]], later a [[Blue Peter]] presenter, began his acting career with 2 years as a member of the Renaissance Theatre Company at the town's Her Majesty's Theatre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peterpurves.com/inthetheatre.html |title=Peter Purves in the Theatre |accessdate=4 August 2007 |publisher=peterpurves.com | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070911234336/http://www.peterpurves.com/inthetheatre.html| archivedate= 11 September 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-20th century, Barrow contained a wealth of theatres/cinemas including the Coliseum, Electric Theatre, Essoldo, Her Majesty's Theatre, Hippodrome, Pavilion, [[Ritz Cinema, Barrow-in-Furness|Ritz]], [[Roxy Cinema, Barrow-in-Furness|Roxy]], Royalty Theatre and Tivoli. All but the Pavilion and Roxy have since been demolished, most recently in 2004 with the demolition of the Apollo (formerly the Ritz). The Canteen Media & Arts Centre \u2013 known simply as \"The Canteen\" \u2013 and [[Forum 28|The Forum]] are now the main venues for theatre, while the [[Vue Cinemas|Vue Cinema]] in [[Hindpool Retail Parks#Hollywood Park|Hollywood Park]] is the only cinema in the town.\n\n'''Literature'''<br />\nIn fictional works, Barrow and [[Vickerstown]] on [[Walney Island]] featured in children's show ''[[The Railway Series]]'', which developed into ''[[Thomas the Tank Engine]]'', as the point where the fictional [[Sodor (fictional island)|Island of Sodor]] connected to mainland Britain and the national rail network.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.storybookengland.com/authors.php?form_id=3413682892|title= Thomas the Tank Engine books|accessdate= 25 August 2007|publisher= Storybook England|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070921151657/http://www.storybookengland.com/authors.php?form_id=3413682892|archivedate= 21 September 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA number of the [[Lake Poets]] have referred to locations in present day Barrow, with one notable example being [[William Wordsworth]]'s 1805 autobiographical poem ''[[The Prelude]]'' which describes his visits to Furness Abbey. The Portuguese poet [[Fernando Pessoa]] wrote a series of [[sonnet]]s called \"Barrow-on-Furness\" (sic). His \"heteronym\" [[\u00c1lvaro de Campos]] lived in Barrow when he was studying ship engineering, but Pessoa himself had never visited, and mistakenly assumed that \"Furness\" was the name of a river.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/obra-visor/hispania--11/html/|title= \u00c1lvaro de Campos's Geography|accessdate=1 January 2012|publisher=Hispania }}</ref> According to narrative exposition in Chapter five of [[Dorothy L. Sayers]]' 1926 novel ''[[Clouds of Witness]]'', Inspector Charles Parker, Lord Peter Wimsey's friend and eventual brother-in-law, attended Barrow-in-Furness Grammar School. Renowned novelist [[D. H. Lawrence]] was in Barrow during the outbreak of World War I and wrote about his experiences in the town. The 2015 novel ''[[Career of Evil]]'' by [[J. K. Rowling]]'s pseudonym Robert Galbraith was parially set in Barrow.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/oct/21/career-of-evil-by-robert-galbraith-review |title=Career of Evil by Robert Galbraith review \u2013 a daft but enjoyable hunt for a serial killer |accessdate=20 November 2015 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] }}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n[[File:Portland Walk.jpg|thumb|right|[[Portland Walk Shopping Centre|Portland Walk]], one of Barrow's primary retail areas]]\n\n====Newspapers====\nThere is one paid-for evening daily paper, ''[[The Mail (Cumbria)|The Mail]]''. There is also a weekly freesheet called the ''Advertiser'', which is delivered to most households in the Furness area.\n\n====Radio====\nBarrow is served by one commercial radio station, [[Heart North West]], which broadcasts from Manchester and serves the area around [[Morecambe Bay]]. Another commercial station, [[Abbey FM]], ceased broadcasting in February 2009 when it went into administration.<ref>{{Cite news| title= Abbey FM ceases broadcasting| url= http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.4343.2| accessdate= 24 February 2009| date= 30 January 2009| work= Radio Today| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090205190014/http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.4343.2| archivedate= 5 February 2009|url-status = dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> The BBC's local radio service is [[BBC Radio Cumbria]], who have studio facilities in the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/content/articles/2005/10/19/barrow_office_feature.shtml |title=BBC \u2013 Cumbria \u2013 Local Radio \u2013 The Barrow Office. |accessdate=16 August 2007 |publisher=BBC}}</ref> .  Barrow and the Furness area is served by local community radio CANDOFM 106.3FM in the local area and also available online.  With plans to expand further.  CandoFM is located in Cooke Studios, Abbey Road, Barrow-in-Furness and run by 50+ volunteers providing local information as well as an eclectic mix of shows.\n\n====Television====\nBarrow lies in the [[Granada TV]] \u2013 [[North West England]] region with the main signal coming from the [[Winter Hill transmitting station|Winter Hill]] transmitter near [[Bolton]]. There is also a relay transmitter at [[Millom]] whose signal can be received in the northern end of the town.\n\nVarious television personalities were born in the district. Dave Myers was a biker born in Barrow, and found fame as one half of television cookery duo [[the Hairy Bikers]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Rosanna |last=Greenstreet |title=My Home: Dave Myers of the Hairy Bikers |date=10 May 2006 |publisher=Independent News & Media |url=http://money.independent.co.uk/property/homes/article363011.ece |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=7 August 2007 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927211243/http://money.independent.co.uk/property/homes/article363011.ece |archivedate=27 September 2007  }}</ref> [[Karen Taylor (comedian)|Karen Taylor]] is a TV comedian best known for her BBC Three sketch show ''[[Touch Me, I'm Karen Taylor]]''.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Karen's sketch show opens | date=11 June 2007 | publisher=CN Group | url =http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508863 | work =North West Evening Mail | accessdate =25 July 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926212137/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=508863| archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref> [[Steve Dixon (newsreader)|Steve Dixon]] is a newsreader for Sky News,<ref>{{Cite news| first=Cassandra | last=Jardine | title='Diabetes is not as simple as it appears' | date=3 November 2003 | url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global/main.jhtml?xml=/global/2003/11/03/hdiab03.xml |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London | accessdate =7 August 2007 }}</ref> while [[Nigel Kneale]] was a well-known film and television scriptwriter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article622130.ece|title=Nigel Kneale|work=The Times |location=London |date=2 November 2006|accessdate=8 February 2007|page=71  | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070211131713/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article622130.ece| archivedate= 11 February 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> The UK's top Thai demo chef and celebrity 'Chef Ooy' has also lived and worked in Barrow for the last 25 years.\n\n[[File:Barrow-in-Furness statue collage.jpg|thumb|left|Barrow has a large number of public works of art, including statues of prominent political figures and sporting personalities]]\nWartime diarist and local housewife [[Nella Last]]'s memoirs were adapted for television, with parts of the town used in filming. The resulting programme, ''[[Housewife, 49]]'', written by and starring comedian [[Victoria Wood]], was broadcast by ITV in 2006. It won two [[British Academy Television Awards 2007|BAFTA]] awards \u2013 one for Best Single Drama, the other for Best Actress (Victoria Wood).<ref>{{Cite news| first=Ian | last=Wylie | title=Victoria plays it straight | date=1 December 2006 | publisher=Guardian Media Group | url =http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/film_and_tv/s/229/229723_victoria_plays_it_straight.html | work =Manchester Evening News | accessdate =5 August 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=481129|title= Top Award for Diary Drama Set in Barrow|accessdate=14 August 2007 |date= 27 March 2007|publisher= [[North West Evening Mail]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926211416/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/viewarticle.aspx?id=481129| archivedate = 26 September 2007}}</ref>\nCITV children's show [[The Treacle People]] had two villains named Barrow and Furness.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.channel4.com/learning/microsites/T/treacle/series2.html | publisher =Channel 4 | accessdate=10 May 2007 | title=Treacle People microsite }}</ref> Myles Wright also was born in Barrow and lived in the nearby village of Marton.\n\nBarrow-in-Furness is the connection between England and the fictional Island of Sodor in the [[Thomas the Tank Engine]] TV series, as well as in the Railway Series books by the [[Wilbert Awdry|Rev. W. Awdry]], on which the TV series is based.\n\n===Dialect and accent===\n{{main|Barrovian}}\nFurness is unique within Cumbria and the local dialect and accent is fairly [[Lancashire dialect and accent|Lancashire]]-orientated. Until 1974 Furness was an [[exclave]] of Lancashire. As with [[Liverpool]] for example however, the ''Barrovian'' dialect has been influenced by large numbers of settlers from various regions. During the town's rapid growth from 1860 onwards, thousands came to Barrow from [[Scotland]], [[Ireland]], [[Wales]] and elsewhere in northern England. As [[Glasgow patter|Glaswegian]] and [[Geordie]] dialects mingled in Barrow numerous more migrated from Lancashire and other parts of England which in effect created the noticeably [[Northern England English|Northern]] ''Barrovian'' dialect. In general the ''Barrovian'' accent tends to drop certain letters (including ''H'' and ''T'').\n\n===Nightlife===\n[[File:The Crow's Nest Pub - geograph.org.uk - 1559003.jpg|thumb|The Crow's Nest on Barrow Island, a typical Victorian era public house]]\nThere are many pubs and [[working men's club]]s in Barrow. Barrow has fourteen of the latter, one of the highest number per capita of any British town.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2008/10/06/barrow-in-furness-the-working-class-capital-of-britain-115875-20779478/|title=Barrow-in-Furness: The working class capital of Britain|first=Kate|last=Jackson|date=5 October 2008|publisher=}}</ref> There are also many bars and clubs found primarily in [[Central Barrow|Barrow town centre]] on [[Duke Street, Barrow-in-Furness|Duke Street]] and Cornwallis Street. Popular venues on Duke Street include the following bars: Jefferson's, the Buddha Bar, Bar Cairo and the Drawing Room. They did have a [[Yates's]] but the building was deemed unsafe and has since been demolished. Cornwallis Street \u2013 often dubbed the ''\"[[Gaza Strip]]\"'' by locals \u2013 is currently undergoing a multi-million pound renovation with the former Martini's being the flagship renovation into Club M. Other clubs on Cornwallis Street include: Kavanna's, O'Sullivan's and Skint. Between 2004 and 2010 Barrow was home to one of North West England's largest nightclubs, the {{formatnum:2500}}-capacity Blue Lagoon occupied the entire hull of the former Danish ferry [[Princess Selandia]], which has now left the town.<ref>http://www.gardinersecurity.co.uk/articles.asp?pID=1&id=314{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Barrow's largest nightclub is now [[Roxy Cinema, Barrow-in-Furness|Manhattans]], which opened on Cavendish Street in late 2011.\n\n===Food===\nA traditional favourite food in Barrow is the [[pie]], and particularly the [[meat and potato pie]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Tarbuck|first1=Martin|title=The 10 Greatest Pies In Britain|url=http://sabotagetimes.com/life/10-greatest-pies-britain|magazine=Sabotage Times|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> [[Pie shop]]s are common, and Green's of Jarrow Street is noted as a favourite of Barrow-born celebrity chef [[Dave Myers (presenter)|Dave Myers]] <ref>{{cite web|title=The Green's Green Food of Home|url=http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/the-green-s-green-s-food-of-home-1.158252|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721042202/http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/the-green-s-green-s-food-of-home-1.158252|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref> and journalist Martin Tarbuck, who declared them to be Britain's best pies in a book dedicated to the subject.<ref>{{cite news|title=Upper crust: Writer scoffs his way to a winner in search for Britain's favourite pie|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/upper-crust-writer-scoffs-way-5282206|newspaper=Daily Mirror|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nBarrow was also the home of [[soft-drink]] company Marsh's, which produced a distinctive [[sarsaparilla (soft drink)|sarsaparilla]]-flavoured fizzy drink known as ''Sass''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mystery that threatens cult soft drink|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Mystery+that+threatens+cult+soft+drink.-a060206032|publisher=Birmingham Post & Mail Ltd|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> Marsh's was purchased by Purity Soft Drinks of Birmingham in 1993, and the company stopped producing Sass in 1999. Remaining bottles have subsequently sold for high prices as a collector's item.<ref>{{cite web|title=Record Bid for Bottle of Sass|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/record-bid-for-bottle-of-sass-1.486029|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721002701/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/record-bid-for-bottle-of-sass-1.486029|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref> A new product, labelled \"Barrow Sass\", was launched in 2014 in a bid to replicate traditional Sass.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sass in the Miz at Barrow Cocktail Bar|url=http://www.in-cumbria.com/sass-in-the-mix-at-barrow-cocktail-bar-1.1219999|publisher=North-West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721070012/http://www.in-cumbria.com/sass-in-the-mix-at-barrow-cocktail-bar-1.1219999|archivedate=21 July 2015}}</ref> The coasts around Barrow have rich [[Cockle (bivalve)|cockle]] beds from which cockles have traditionally been gathered, although numbers have been low following intensive gathering during the early 2000s, in the run-up to the [[2004 Morecambe Bay cockling disaster]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Restraint needed to restore cockles|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Restraint-needed-to-restore-cockles-5387c86f-f860-4811-b37e-c5f677214e2c-ds|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721104102/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Restraint-needed-to-restore-cockles-5387c86f-f860-4811-b37e-c5f677214e2c-ds|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cocklers' gangmaster made \u00a3100 a day|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/jan/24/ukcrime1|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> One of England's few remaining [[Oyster farming|Oyster farms]] can also be found located in the [[Biggar, Cumbria|Biggar]] area of Walney. Traditional [[Cumberland sausages]] are less associated with Barrow itself than the rest of Cumbria, but are readily available from the surrounding rural area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Butchers' campaign to protect sausage in Cumbria|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Butchers-campaign-to-protect-sausage-in-Cumbria-6701513e-0a11-4974-a183-72c55fb022ee-ds|publisher=North-West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721080507/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/News/Butchers-campaign-to-protect-sausage-in-Cumbria-6701513e-0a11-4974-a183-72c55fb022ee-ds|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status = dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Cumbria has produced a number of famed dishes and is home to countless [[Michelin Guide]] restaurants, one of which is located in Dalton.\n\n==Social issues==\n\n=== Lifestyle ===\n[[File:Parade Street, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|right|The majority of housing within the town is [[Terraced house|terraced]], built for working-class families]]\nHaving emerged as mixture of working-class cultures from across Britain and Ireland in the 19th century, subsequent low levels of migration and a continued tradition of industrial employment mean that Barrow's culture still reflects many of the traditions of the British [[Working Class]].<ref name=\"Blue Cap\">{{cite news|last1=Davies|first1=Caroline|title=Barrow, capital of blue-collar Britain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2008/oct/05/1|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> In September 2008, Barrow was named as the most working-class location in the United Kingdom, based on a series of measures devised to judge the lifestyle of the people.<ref name=workingclass>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/1.244620|title=Have your say on Barrow's flat cap image|publisher=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=6 October 2010|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201022016/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/1.244620|archivedate=1 December 2008}}</ref> The research was carried out by Locallife.co.uk which determined that there is a [[Fish and chips|fish and chip shop]], [[working men's club]], [[bookmaker]]s or [[Trade union|trade union office]] for every 2,917 people ([[Crewe]], [[Doncaster]], [[Wolverhampton]] and [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] completed the top five of 'the most working class places in Britain').<ref name=workingclass2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2008/10/06/barrow-in-furness-the-working-class-capital-of-britain-115875-20779478/|title=Barrow-in-Furness: The working class capital of Britain|publisher=The Mirror|accessdate=6 October 2010}}</ref> This is in direct contrast to the 1870s, when a developing Barrow had more [[Aristocracy (class)|aristocrats]] per head of the population than anywhere else in the country.<ref name=workingclass/>\n\nIn the 2015 [[Deprivation index|Indices of Deprivation]], Barrow was ranked as the 44th most deprived district in England (out of a total of 326).<ref name=Deprivation>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/464464/File_10_ID2015_Local_Authority_District_Summaries.xlsx|title=Indices of Deprivation 2015 Local Authority Summaries|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> The equivalent figures for 2007 and 2010 stood at 29th most deprived and 32nd most deprived respectively.<ref name=Deprivation2>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=1572|title=Indices of Deprivation 2010|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=11 September 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911203616/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=1572|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref> The Indices of Deprivation is based on income, employment, education, health, crime and barriers to housing and services and living environment. Within these subcategories, most notably Barrow ranked as the 5th most deprived in terms of health deprivation and disability, and in huge contrast, 324th most deprived in terms of access to housing and services (i.e. 3rd least deprived).<ref name=Deprivation/> In the 2010 Indices of Deprivation, the majority of areas in Barrow Island, Central, Hindpool, Ormsgill were amongst the 3% most deprived areas in the country, while large parts of suburban Barrow including Newbarns and Roose were amongst the 25% of least deprived areas in England.<ref name=Deprivation2/>\n\n=== Health ===\n[[File:Furness General.jpg|thumb|left|[[Furness General Hospital]], the primary hospital for Barrow and South West Cumbria]]\nThe principal hospital in Barrow is [[Furness General Hospital]], operated by the [[University Hospitals of Morecambe Bay NHS Trust]] and located on the outskirts of the town. As of July 2010 there were 12 NHS GP practices/doctors' surgeries and 5 NHS dental surgeries in Barrow.<ref name=NHSsearch>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/servicedirectories/pages/servicesearch.aspx|title=Find and choose services|publisher=[[National Health Service (England)|NHS]]|accessdate=22 July 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100722013546/http://www.nhs.uk/servicedirectories/Pages/ServiceSearch.aspx| archivedate= 22 July 2010 |url-status = live}}</ref> The [[life expectancy]] for males in Barrow is 77.1 years (compared to the England average of 79.5) and 81.5 years for females (compared to the national average of 83.2).<ref name=NHSpublication>{{Cite web|url= http://fingertipsreports.phe.org.uk/health-profiles/2016/e07000027.pdf |title=Barrow-in-Furness Health Profile|publisher=NHS|year=2016|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref> A 2016 [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]] in depth publication on health in Barrow indicated that the population of Barrow is by most measures in a worse state than the national average.<ref name=NHSpublication/> Indicators such as hospital stays for alcohol related harm, excessive weight, diabetes, smoking related death and self-harm are significantly worse than the England average. However, a number of indicators are similar to the average or are significantly better, including rates of homelesness, STI transmission and road deaths.\"<ref name=NHSpublication/> Barrow has the tenth worst rate of [[Incapacity Benefit]] claimants for [[Mental disorder|mental illness]] in the country.\n\n=== Crime ===\n[[File:Barrow Police Station June 2015.JPG|thumb|Barrow's new main police station (under construction) in June 2015]]\nPolicing is by [[Cumbria Constabulary]], which alongside the county of Cumbria was formed in 1974. Previously the town was policed by Barrow-in-Furness Borough Police. Barrow previously had one full-time police station in Market Street in the [[Central Barrow|Central]] ward. A new multi-million pound building was built on James Freel Close on Channelside in [[Hindpool]] and is the town's only police station, with extra jail cells and improved facilities. Several consecutive annual publications by Cumbria Constabulary entitled the 'Cumbria Community Safety Strategic Assessment' have stated that overall crime in Barrow is declining, with some indicators far better than the national average.<ref name=Crimeobserv>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cumbriaobservatory.org.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/671/4674/5172/41260152144.pdf|title=Cumbria Community Safety Strategic Assessment|publisher=Cumbria Intelligence Observatory|year=2012|accessdate=9 September 2014|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910200016/http://www.cumbriaobservatory.org.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/671/4674/5172/41260152144.pdf|archivedate=10 September 2014}}</ref> Despite this, crime levels as a whole are higher than the national average: 2013 statistics show crime levels in the borough as the 16th worst in the UK; most notably, Barrow has amongst the worst rates of alcohol misuse in the country.<ref name=CrimeStats>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/crime-statistics-for-barrow-in-furness-3217045|title=Crime statistics for Barrow-in-Furness|publisher=Cumbria Constabulary|year=2013|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> Between July and December 2013 Barrow saw an average of 7.39 crimes per 100 of the population; the UK average was 6.57.<ref name=CrimeStats/> Incidents of anti-social behaviour stood at 7.83 per 100 in Barrow, cf 5.02 in the UK.<ref name=CrimeStats/> Burglary averaged 0.53 per 100 in 2013 while the national average was 1.00 per 100. Robbery averaged 0.02 in Barrow and 0.07 nationwide, shoplifting 0.72 and 0.53 and vehicle crime at 0.31 and 0.58.<ref name=CrimeStats/> Violent crimes and sexual offences occurred at a rate of 1.70 per 100, significantly higher than UK average of 1.06 and ranking the area as the 29th worst out of 348 in the country.<ref name=CrimeStats/> Crime rates remain the highest in deprived areas of inner wards such as Central and Hindpool.<ref name=Crimeobserv/>\n\nSince November 2019 [[Ministry of Defence Police]] have been based at the [[BAE Systems]] Shipyard.\n\n==Education==\n{{See also|List of schools in Barrow-in-Furness}}\n[[File:Furness College campus, Barrow-in-Furness.jpg|thumb|The Copper Box building at [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]]'s Channelside campus]]\n[[File:Furness Academy newbuild2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Furness Academy]] was established in 2009 and opened a new site in 2013]]\nEducation in the state-funded sector includes fifteen [[primary school]]s, five [[infant school]]s, five [[junior school]]s and many nurseries. The three [[secondary school]]s in the town are: [[Furness Academy]], [[St. Bernard's Catholic High School]] and [[Walney School]]. [[Chetwynde School]] is an all-through school for children aged 4 to 18. Formerly an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent school]], Chetwynde became a state-funded [[Free school (England)|free school]] in 2014.\n\nIn the further education sector there is one college, [[Furness College, Barrow-in-Furness|Furness College]]. Furness College merged with [[Barrow Sixth Form College]] in 2016 forming the largest college in Cumbria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barrow colleges merger hailed \"exciting new era for education\"|url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/barrow/Barrow-colleges-merger-hailed-exciting-new-era-for-education-c401988c-92d0-4bde-9806-3b13892705b3-ds|website=North West Evening Mail|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> Technical and professional qualifications are delivered at the Channelside campus, with A' levels delivered at the Rating Lane campus, the home of the former sixth form college. Although there is no [[higher education]] institution based in Barrow, Furness College offers several higher apprenticeships, [[foundation degree]]s, [[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor's]] and [[Master's degree|Master's]] programmes accredited by the [[University of Cumbria]], [[University of Lancaster]] and the [[University of Central Lancashire]].<ref>{{cite web|title=University Education|url=http://www.furness.ac.uk/course-index/university-education|publisher=Furness College|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe town's main library is the [[Barrow-in-Furness Main Public Library|Central Library]] in [[Ramsden Square]], situated near the town centre.<ref name=\"Library\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=163|title= Libraries and Archives|accessdate= 18 August 2007|publisher= Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070827135601/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=163|archivedate= 27 August 2007|url-status = dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> The library was established in 1882 in a room near the town hall, and moved to its current premises in 1922. A branch of the County Archive Service, opened in 1979 and containing many of the town's archives, is located within adjoining premises,<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.familia.org.uk/services/england/cumbria_barrow.html|title= Cumbria County Council (Barrow)|accessdate=18 August 2007 |publisher= Familia| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070906141740/http://www.familia.org.uk/services/england/cumbria_barrow.html| archivedate= 6 September 2007 |url-status = live}}</ref> whilst until 1991 the library also housed the Furness Museum, a forerunner of the Dock Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/museum_history.htm|title= Museum History|accessdate=18 August 2007 |format= Flash|publisher= [[Dock Museum]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070805222430/http://www.dockmuseum.org.uk/museum_history.htm| archivedate = 5 August 2007}}</ref> Smaller branch libraries are currently provided at [[Walney]], [[Roose]] and [[Barrow Island, Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Island]]. Known librarian Michael Wilson originates in Barrow-in-Furness. Michael Wilson is currently leader of the Collection Logistics Alpha Team at Cambridge University Library.<ref name=\"Library\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cumbria}}\n* [[Barrovian]]\n* [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness]]\n* [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)]]\n* [[List of people from Barrow-in-Furness]]\n* [[List of ships and submarines built in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n* [[Listed buildings in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n* [[List of places of worship in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Barrow-in-Furness}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Barrow-in-Furness}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n{{Cumbria}}\n{{Barrow-in-Furness topics}}\n{{Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barrow-In-Furness}}\n[[Category:Barrow-in-Furness| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Districts of Barrow-in-Furness| ]]\n[[Category:Furness]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns of the Irish Sea]]\n[[Category:Planned communities in England]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1867]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in North West England]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Morecambe Bay]]\n[[Category:1867 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Category:Unparished areas in Cumbria", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrow-in-Furness"}
{"title_page": "Fifth column", "text_new": "{{other uses2|Fifth Column}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n[[File:\"Appreciate America Stop the Fifth Column\" - NARA - 513873.jpg|thumb|upright|World War II poster from the United States]]\nA '''fifth column''' is any group of people who undermine a larger group from within, usually in favor of an enemy group or nation.  The activities of a fifth column can be overt or clandestine. Forces gathered in secret can mobilize openly to assist an external attack. This term is also extended to organised actions by military personnel. Clandestine fifth column activities can involve acts of sabotage, disinformation, or espionage executed within defense lines by secret sympathizers with an external force.\n\n==Origin==\n[[File:\u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043b\u044c \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432.JPG|thumb|160px|left|[[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republican]] patrol on the streets of Madrid, 1936]]\nThe term \"fifth column\" originated in Spain (originally ''quinta columna'') during the early phase of the [[Spanish Civil War|Civil War]]. It gained extreme popularity in the [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republican]] media since early October 1936, and immediately started to make rounds also abroad.<ref>in French newspapers the term first appeared on October 4, 1936, one day after its first usage in the Madrid press, ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k7634839j/f5.item.r=Cinqui%C3%A8me%20colonne.zoom La Passionaria preche la terreur]'', [in:] ''Le Journal'' 04.10.1936. In more distant countries like Poland the term started to appear since mid-October, see e.g. ''[https://polona.pl/item/dziennik-wilenski-r-20-nr-285-18-pazdziernika-1936,MTU3NDQwNDU/0/#info:metadata Oviedo ostatecznie uwolnione]'', [in:] ''Dziennik Wile\u0144ski'' 18.10.1936</ref> \n\nExact origins of the term are not clear. Its first identified appearance was in a secret telegram sent to [[Berlin]] by the [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Charg\u00e9 d'affaires|charge d\u2019affaires]] in [[Alicante]], [[:de:Hans Hermann V\u00f6lckers|Hans-Hermann V\u00f6lckers]] dated September 30, 1936. He referred to an unidentified \"supposed statement by [[Francisco Franco|Franco]]\" which \"is being circulated\" (apparently in the [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republican]] zone or in the Republican-held [[Levante, Spain|Levantine]] zone). In the statement, Franco allegedly claimed that there were four [[Nationalist faction (Spanish Civil War)|Nationalist]] columns approaching Madrid and the fifth column waited to rise from the inside.<ref>Ruiz, Julius (2014), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=HqBcAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA185&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIbjAH#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The 'Red Terror' and the Spanish Civil War]'', Cambridge, {{ISBN|9781107054547}}, p. 187</ref> However, the telegram was part of the secret German diplomatic correspondence and was discovered long after the Civil War.\n\nThe first public use of the term identified is in the October 3, 1936 issue of the Madrid [[Communist]] daily ''[[Mundo Obrero]]''. In a front-page article the party propagandist [[Dolores Ib\u00e1rruri]] referred the same statement as reported by V\u00f6lckers, but attributed it to general [[Emilio Mola]].<ref>the actual copy of ''Mundo Obrero'' is not available for consultation online. Many authors claim that in the article Ibarruri referred to an unidentified Mola's radio broadcast, see e.g. Preston Paul (2011), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=IsNUHLStdDUC&pg=PT198&lpg=PT198&dq=mola+quinta+columna&source=bl&ots=jKdsKJnw5W&sig=ACfU3U0ZBMg0Q2B9a3vKHX5Uge1Pik9lZg&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi68vHu3P7nAhVwkosKHQ7uCaIQ6AEwCXoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=mola%20quinta%20columna&f=false La Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola: reacci\u00f3n, revoluci\u00f3n y venganza]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788499891507}}. However, other scholars when quoting Ibarruri do not refer the broadcast detail, see e.g. Ruiz 2014, pp. 185-186</ref> On the same day the [[Communist Party of Spain|PCE]] activist Domingo Gir\u00f3n made a similar claim during a public rally.<ref>Domingo Gir\u00f3n was a Madrid mid-level Communist activist. In his speech he referred to \"cierta declaraci\u00f3n hecha por el general Mola a un periodista extranjero\", ''[https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000207223&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina Un gran mitin del Socorro Rojo internacional]'', [in:] ''Hoja Oficial del lunes'' 04.10.1936. In March 1939, he was detained by the Casadistas and handed over to the Francoists later on. Following trial, he was sentenced to death and executed on July 3, 1941</ref> During the following days Republican papers repeated the story, but with differing detail; some attributed the phrase to [[Gonzalo Queipo de Llano|general Queipo de Llano]].<ref>Ruiz 2014, pp. 186-187</ref> In mid-October media already warned against \"famous fifth column\".<ref>''[https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000145318&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina Informacion radiotelegrafica]'', [in:] ''El bien publico'' 13.10.1936</ref>\n\nHistorians have never identified the original statement referred by V\u00f6lckers, Ib\u00e1rruri and others.<ref> De Jong Louis (2019), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=RM6gDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT14&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The German Fifth Column in the Second World War]'', London, {{ISBN|9781000008098}}</ref> Though transcripts of Franco\u2019s, Queipo and Mola\u2019s radio addresses have been published, they did not contain the term referred;<ref>Preston Paul (2012), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=7PKHUTjX0UAC&pg=PT563&lpg=PT563&dq=Carlos+Contreras,+%27En+defensa+de+Madrid:+la+quinta+columna%27,+Mi&source=bl&ots=SoEfQPpYaK&sig=ACfU3U09M9IDV3rBmcuduPV8H5De5v4bZA&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiwiMbS4P7nAhXloosKHRPxBtYQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Carlos%20Contreras%2C%20'En%20defensa%20de%20Madrid%3A%20la%20quinta%20columna'%2C%20Mi&f=false The Spanish Holocaust: Inquisition and Extermination in Twentieth-Century Spain]'', London, {{ISBN|9780393239669}} </ref> no other original statement with the phrase in question has ever surfaced. A British journalist who took part in Mola\u2019s press conference on October 28, 1936 claimed that Mola referred to ''quinta columna'' on this very day,<ref> Preston Paul (2011), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=IsNUHLStdDUC&pg=PT198&lpg=PT198&dq=mola+quinta+columna&source=bl&ots=jKdsKJnw5W&sig=ACfU3U0ZBMg0Q2B9a3vKHX5Uge1Pik9lZg&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi68vHu3P7nAhVwkosKHQ7uCaIQ6AEwCXoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=mola%20quinta%20columna&f=false La Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola: reacci\u00f3n, revoluci\u00f3n y venganza]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788499891507}}</ref> though at that time the term had already been used in the Republican press for more than 3 weeks.<ref>''[https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/consulta/resultados_ocr.do Prensa Historica]'' service, ''[http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/ Hemeroteca Digital]'' service  </ref>\n\n[[Historiographic]] works offer differing perspectives on authorship of the term. Many scholars have no doubt about Mola\u2019s role and refer to \"fifth column\" as to \"a term coined in 1936 by General Emilio Mola\",<ref>Kennedy, David M. (ed.) (2007), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=0bRaa7UuD6EC&pg=PA79&dq=fifth+column+the+term+invented&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjx4vn84v7nAhUJxYsKHWQPA8cQ6AEIMzAB#v=onepage&q=fifth%20column%20the%20term%20invented&f=false The Library of Congress World War II Companion]'', New York, {{ISBN|9781416553069}}, p. 79, also Lejeune Anthony (ed.) (2018), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=yHh0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT268&dq=quinta+columna+mola+nunca&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQlIvr7v7nAhUqposKHS7gBZIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=quinta%20columna%20mola%20nunca&f=false Concise Dictionary of Foreign Quotations]'', London, {{ISBN|9781135974893}}, , also Romero Salvad\u00f3, Francisco J., (2013), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=i5e7wRi-HGcC&pg=PA199&dq=ibarruri+quinta+columna&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjW6pmn9P7nAhWBl4sKHbf4C-4Q6AEINTAB#v=onepage&q=ibarruri%20quinta%20columna&f=false Historical Dictionary of the Spanish Civil War]'', London, {{ISBN|9780810880092}}, p. 199, </ref> though they admit that the exact statement can not be identified.<ref>Preston Paul (2011), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=aPV1johx8NMC&pg=PR211&dq=quinta+columna+mola+nunca&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQlIvr7v7nAhUqposKHS7gBZIQ6AEISDAD#v=onepage&q=quinta%20columna%20mola%20nunca&f=false El holocausto espa\u00f1ol: Odio y exterminio en la Guerra Civil y despu\u00e9s]'', 2011, {{ISBN|9788499920498}}, </ref> In some sources Mola is noted as a person who used the term during an impromptu press interview, and different though detailed versions of the exchange are offered.<ref>one version is \u201cs\u00f3mo es, general Mola, que piensa usted tomar Madrid con cuatro columnas?; no, no tengo cuatro; son cinco las columnas que tengo, porque en Madrid hay una quinta columna\", Carrillo Alejandro (1943), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=suJYAAAAMAAJ&q=no+tiene+usted+sino+cuatro+columnas,general.+Tengo+la+quinta+columna+en+Madrid&dq=no+tiene+usted+sino+cuatro+columnas,general.+Tengo+la+quinta+columna+en+Madrid&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ3_7a8P7nAhVeAxAIHd5pCvgQ6AEIPzAC Defensa de la revoluci\u00f3n en el Parlamento]'', s.n. 1943,. Other version is \u201cno tiene usted sino cuatro columnas, general; tengo la \u201cQuinta Columna\u201d en Madrid\u201d, P\u00e9rez de Oliva, Fern\u00e1n (1991), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=vk1PJ632CMEC&pg=PA22&dq=no+tiene+usted+sino+cuatro+columnas,general.+Tengo+la+quinta+columna+en+Madrid&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ3_7a8P7nAhVeAxAIHd5pCvgQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=no%20tiene%20usted%20sino%20cuatro%20columnas%2Cgeneral.%20Tengo%20la%20quinta%20columna%20en%20Madrid&f=false Historia de la invenci\u00f3n de las Indias]'', Madrid 1991, {{ISBN|9789682317699}}, p. 22</ref> Probably the most popular version refers the theory of Mola\u2019s authorship with a grade of doubt, either noting that it is presumed but never proven<ref>Barros Andrew, Thomas Martin (2018), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=BWJjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIPTAC#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The Civilianization of War: The Changing Civil\u2013Military Divide]'', 1914\u20132014, Cambridge, {{ISBN|9781108429658}}, p. 49</ref> or that the phrase \"is attributed\" to Mola,<ref> Loeffel Robert (2015), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=MvWKCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR22&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIRzAD#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The Fifth Column in World War II: Suspected Subversives in the Pacific War and Australia]'', London, {{ISBN|9781137506672}}</ref> who \"apparently claimed\" so,<ref>Beevor, Antony (2006), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=Q-mayoYS6eIC&pg=PT369&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIhQEwCQ#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The Battle for Spain: The Spanish Civil War 1936-1939]'', London, {{ISBN|9781101201206}}</ref> or they note \"la famosa quinta columna a la que parece que se hab\u00eda referido el general Mola.\"<ref>Cierva, Ricardo de la (1996), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=Jm8fAAAAMAAJ&q=quinta+columna+de+mola+invencion+comunista&dq=quinta+columna+de+mola+invencion+comunista&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiUqcWj8_7nAhWhlosKHQPsAqw4FBDoAQgnMAA Historia esencial de la Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola: todos los problemas resueltos, sesenta a\u00f1os despu\u00e9s]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788488787125}}</ref> Some authors consider it possible if not likely that the term has been invented by the Communist propaganda with the purpose of either raising morale or providing justification for [[Republican repression in Madrid (1936\u20131939)|terror and repression]]; initially it might have been part of the [[whispering campaign]], but was later openly floated by Communist propagandists.<ref>Ruiz Julius (2014), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=HqBcAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA185&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIbjAH#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The 'Red Terror' and the Spanish Civil War]'', Cambridge, {{ISBN|9781107054547}}, p. 185. The opposing view is that the Republican repression was inadvertently triggered by Mola, who did not realize what effect his alleged statement would have, Laguna Reyes Albert, Vargas M\u00e1rquez Antonio (2019), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=u7mPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT10&dq=quinta+columna+mola+nunca&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQlIvr7v7nAhUqposKHS7gBZIQ6AEIPTAC#v=onepage&q=quinta%20columna%20mola%20nunca&f=false La Quinta Columna: La guerra clandestina tras las l\u00edneas republicanas 1936-1939]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788491645894}}</ref> There are also other theories afloat.<ref>a British correspondent in the Republican zone claimed after the Civil War that \"many weeks\" before October 1936 he had used the term in ''The Daily Telegraph'' when discusing the Nationalist advance towards Madrid. Allegedly the term was picked up by Republican journalists and in turn somehow filtered out to the Nationalist zone; Mola liked it and started to use it. The alleged ''Daily Telegraph'' reference has never been identified. Thomas, Hugh (2018), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=J4VMDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=pl&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=oswald&f=false La guerra civil espa\u00f1ola]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788466344821}}</ref>\n[[File:\u0414\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0441 \u0418\u0431\u0430\u0440\u0440\u0443\u0440\u0438.JPG|thumb|[[Dolores Ib\u00e1rruri]]]]\nThough the 1936 usage is widely regarded as the origins of the phrase, historian [[Christopher Clark]] quotes a February 1906 letter by Austrian [[military attach\u00e9]] Joseph Pomiankowski using the phrase, \"the fifth-column work of the [[People's Radical Party|[Serbian] Radicals]] in peacetime, which systematically poisons the attitude of our [[South Slavs|South Slav population]] and could, if the worst came to the worst, create very serious difficulties for our army.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Sleepwalkers : How Europe Went to War in 1914|last=M.|first=Clark, Christopher|isbn=9780061146657|edition=First U.S.|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780061146657/page/58 58]|oclc=795757585|date=March 19, 2013|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780061146657/page/58}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Krieg im Frieden\" : die F\u00fchrung der k.u.k. Armee und die Grossmachtpolitik \u00d6sterreich-Ungarns 1906-1914|last=G\u00fcnther.|first=Kronenbitter|date=2003|publisher=Oldenbourg|isbn=3486567004|location=M\u00fcnchen|pages=327|oclc=53805594}}</ref><ref>Letter from Austrian military attache in Belgrade, Serbia, Joseph Pomiankowski to Beck, cited and quoted from reference #2, G\u00fcnther Kronenbitter: ''Krieg im Frieden. Die F\u00fchrung der k.u.k. Armee und die Gro\u00dfmachtpolitik \u00d6sterreich-Ungarns 1906\u20131914'' (\"War in Peace. The Leadership of the Imperial and Royal Army and the Great Power Politics of Austria-Hungary 1906-1914\"), Verlag Oldenbourg, Munich, 2003, {{ISBN|3-486-56700-4}}, p. 327</ref>\n\nSome writers, mindful of the origin of the phrase, use it only in reference to military operations rather than the broader and less well defined range of activities that sympathizers might engage in to support an anticipated attack.{{efn|[[Madeleine Albright]], for example, in a lengthy account of [[Germans|German]] sympathizers in [[Czechoslovakia]] in the first years of [[World War II]], does not use the phrase to describe their actions until she considers their possible response to a German invasion: \"Many, perhaps most, of the Sudetens would have provided the enemy with a fifth column\".<ref name=albright>{{cite book|last=Albright|first=Madeleine|title=Prague Winter: A Personal Story of Remembrance and War, 1937-1948|url=https://archive.org/details/praguewinterpers0000albr|url-access=registration|year=2012|publisher=HarperCollins|location=NY|pages=[https://archive.org/details/praguewinterpers0000albr/page/102 102]}}</ref>}}\n\n==Second World War==\n{{Globalize|section|the USA|date=February 2019}}\nBy the late 1930s, as American involvement in the war in Europe became more likely, the term \"fifth column\" was commonly used to warn of potential sedition and disloyalty within the borders of the United States. The fear of betrayal was heightened by the rapid [[Battle of France|fall of France]] in 1940, which some blamed on internal weakness and a pro-German \"fifth column\". A series of photos run in the June 1940 issue of ''[[Life magazine|Life]]'' magazine warned of \"signs of Nazi Fifth Column Everywhere\". In a speech to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] that same month, [[Winston Churchill]] reassured [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]] that \"Parliament has given us the powers to put down Fifth Column activities with a strong hand.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1940-the-finest-hour/we-shall-fight-on-the-beaches|title=We Shall Fight on the Beaches|last=Churchill|first=Winston|date=June 4, 1940|website=winstonchurchill.org|access-date=25 July 2017}}</ref> In July 1940, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine referred to talk of a fifth column as a \"national phenomenon\".<ref>Richard W. Steele, ''Free Speech in the Good War'' (St. Martin's Press, 1999, 75-6)</ref>\n\nIn August 1940, ''[[The New York Times]]'' mentioned \"the first spasm of fear engendered by the success of fifth columns in less fortunate countries\".<ref>''The New York Times'': [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/08/25/96932000.pdf Delbert Clark, \"Aliens to Begin Registering Tuesday,\" August 25, 1940]. Retrieved June 27, 2012.</ref> One report identified participants in Nazi \"fifth columns\" as \"partisans of authoritarian government everywhere,\" citing [[Poland]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The German Fifth Column in Poland|last=Polish Ministry of Information|publisher=Dale Street Books|year=2014|isbn=9781941656099|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=3\u20136}}</ref> [[Czechoslovakia]], [[Norway]], and the [[Netherlands]]. During the [[Norwegian Campaign|Nazi invasion of Norway]], the head of the Norwegian fascist party, [[Vidkun Quisling]], proclaimed the formation of a new fascist government in control of Norway, with himself as Prime Minister, by the end of the first day of fighting. The word \"quisling\" soon became a byword for \"collaborator\" or \"traitor\".<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/06/16/121427281.pdf |first=Otto D. |last= Tolischus |title=How Hitler Made Ready: I - The Fifth Column |date=June 16, 1940 |accessdate= July 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' on August 11, 1940 featured three editorial cartoons using the term.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/08/11/94836997.pdf |first=Frederick R. |last=Barkley |title=Nation Shapes Defense against Foes at Home |date= August 11, 1940| accessdate= July 7, 2012}}</ref> [[John Langdon-Davies]], a British journalist who covered the Spanish Civil War, wrote an account called ''The Fifth Column'' which was published the same year. In November 1940, Ralph Thomson, reviewing Harold Lavine's ''Fifth Column in America,'' a study of Communist and fascist groups in the U.S., in ''The New York Times,'' questioned his choice of that title: \"the phrase has been worked so hard that it no longer means much of anything.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thomson|first1=Ralph |title=Books of the Times|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/11/27/94016453.pdf |accessdate=April 25, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=November 27, 1940}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Seuss cartoon.png|thumb|[[Dr. Seuss]] cartoon in [[PM (newspaper)|PM]] dated February 13, 1942, with the caption 'Waiting for the Signal from Home']]\nImmediately following the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]], U.S. Secretary of the Navy [[Frank Knox]] issued a statement that \"the most effective Fifth Column work of the entire war was done in Hawaii with the exception of Norway.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Niiya |first=Brian |url=http://encyclopedia.densho.org/Frank_Knox/ |title=Frank Knox |publisher=Densho Encyclopedia |accessdate=August 27, 2014}}</ref> In a column published in ''[[The Washington Post]]'', dated 12 February 1942, the columnist [[Walter Lippmann]] wrote of imminent danger from actions that might be taken by [[Japanese American]]s. Titled \"The Fifth Column on the Coast,\" he wrote of possible attacks that could be made along the West Coast of the United States that would amplify damage inflicted by a potential attack by Japanese naval and air forces.<ref>{{cite web|last=Niiya |first=Brian |url=http://encyclopedia.densho.org/The_Fifth_Column_on_the_Coast/ |title=The Fifth Column on the Coast |publisher=Densho Encyclopedia |accessdate=August 27, 2014}}</ref> Suspicion about an active fifth column on the coast led eventually to the [[internment of Japanese Americans]].\n\nDuring the [[Philippines Campaign (1941\u201342)|Japanese invasion of the Philippines]], an article in the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' in December 1941 said the indigenous [[Moro people|Moro Muslims]] were \"capable of dealing with Japanese fifth columnists and invaders alike\".<ref>{{cite news |date= December 22, 1941 |title=80 Japanese Troop Ships Are Sighted Off Luzon (Continued From Page1) |url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oJRRAAAAIBAJ&pg=2732,2587117&hl=en |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |page = 7 |accessdate= October 30, 2014}}</ref> Another in the ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'' the following month described how the large population of Japanese immigrants in [[Davao Region|Davao]] in the Philippines welcomed the invasion: \"the first assault on Davao was aided by numbers of Fifth Columnists\u2013residents of the town\".<ref>{{cite news |last= Curtis |first= Herbert |date= January 13, 1942 |title= Japanese Infiltration Into Mindanao |url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sDRlAAAAIBAJ&pg=2656,1332631&hl=en |newspaper= Vancouver Sun |page = 4 |accessdate= October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Later usage==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1986-042-14, Anschluss sudetendeutscher Gebiete.jpg|thumb|[[Sudeten German]] [[Freikorps]]]]\n\n* German minority organizations in [[Czechoslovakia]] formed the [[Sudetendeutsches Freikorps|Sudeten German Free Corps]], which aided the [[Third Reich]]. Some claimed they were \"self-defense formations\" created in the aftermath of [[World War I]] and unrelated to the German invasion two decades later.<ref>Robert G.L. Waite, ''Vanguard of Nazism: The Free Corps Movement in Post-War Germany, 1918-1923'' (1952), 88</ref> More often their origins were discounted and they were defined by the role they played in 1938\u201339: \"The same pattern was repeated in Czechoslovakia. [[Konrad Henlein|Henlein]]'s Free Corps played in that country the part of fifth column\".<ref>Yale Law School: [http://avalon.law.yale.edu/imt/12-20-45.asp Nuremberg Trial Proceedings Volume 4, 215, December 20, 1945]. Retrieved July 19, 2012</ref>\n* In 1945, a document produced by the [[U.S. Department of State]] compared the earlier efforts of Nazi Germany to mobilize the support of sympathizers in foreign nations to the superior efforts of the international communist movement at the end of World War II: \"a communist party was in fact a fifth column as much as any [German] Bund group, except that the latter were crude and ineffective in comparison with the Communists\".<ref>Thomas G. Paterson, ''Meeting the Communist Threat: Truman to Reagan'' (Oxford University Press, 1988), 10</ref> [[Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr.]], wrote in 1949: \"the special Soviet advantage\u2014the warhead\u2014lies in the fifth column; and the fifth column is based on the local Communist parties\".<ref>Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr., ''The Politics of Freedom'' (Heinemann, 1950), 92-3</ref>\n* [[Zainichi Koreans|North Koreans]] living in [[Japan]], particularly those affiliated with the organization [[Chongryun]] (which is itself affiliated with the government of [[North Korea]]) are sometimes seen as a \"fifth column\" by some Japanese, and have been the victims of verbal and physical attacks. These have occurred more frequently since the government of [[Kim Jong Il]] acknowledged it had [[North Korean abductions of Japanese|abducted people from Japan]] and [[North Korean missile test, 2006|tested ballistic missiles]].<ref>\"North Koreans in Japan have long been vilified as a communist fifth column\" (Hans Greimel, \"Test sparks N. Korea Backlash in Japan\", [[Associated Press]] dispatch, October 24, 2006 {{cite web |url=http://www.plesserholland.com/pdf/10.24.06-Kang-AP-NK.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-01-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205074933/http://www.plesserholland.com/pdf/10.24.06-Kang-AP-NK.pdf |archivedate=February 5, 2007 |df=mdy-all }})</ref>\n* Some [[Israeli Jews]], including politicians, [[rabbi]]s, journalists, and historians, who believe that [[Arab citizens of Israel|Israeli Arabs]] identify more with the [[Palestinian nationalism|Palestinian cause]] than with the state of Israel or [[Zionism]], have referred to them, who compose approximately 20% of Israel's population, as a fifth column.<ref>\"... they hurl accusations against us, like that we are a 'fifth column'.\" (Roee Nahmias, \"[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3285075,00.html Arab MK: Israel committing 'genocide' of Shiites]\", [[Ynetnews]] August 2, 2006)</ref><ref>\"... a fifth column, a league of traitors\" (Evelyn Gordon, \"[http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull&cid=1157913624780 No longer the political fringe]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\", [[Jerusalem Post]] September 14, 2006)</ref>\n* [[Counter-jihad]] literature has sought to portray Western Muslims as a \"fifth column\", collectively seeking to destabilize Western nations' identity and values for the benefit of an international Islamic movement intent on the [[Eurabia|establishment of a caliphate in Western countries]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Akbarzadeh|first1=Shahram|last2=Roose|first2=Joshua M.|title=Muslims, Multiculturalism and the Question of the Silent Majority|journal=Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs|date=September 2011|volume=31|issue=3|pages=309\u2013325|doi=10.1080/13602004.2011.599540}}</ref> Following the 2015 attack by French-born Muslims on the offices of ''[[Charlie Hebdo shooting|Charlie Hebdo]]'' in Paris, the leader of the [[UK Independence Party]] [[Nigel Farage]] said that Europe had \"a fifth column living within our own countries\".<ref>{{cite news|work=National Review |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/395914/ukips-farage-multiculturalism-creating-fifth-column-west-brendan-bordelon |first=Brendan |last=Bordelon |title=UKIP's Farage: Multiculturalism Creating 'Fifth Column' in West |date= January 7, 2015 | accessdate= January 8, 2015}}</ref> In 2001 Dutch politician [[Pim Fortuyn]] talked about Muslim immigrants being a \"fifth column\" the night he was dismissed as leader of [[Liveable Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.historischnieuwsblad.nl/nl/artikel/32279/fortuyn-ramp-voor-politiek-en-vaderland.html|title=Fortuyn: ramp voor politiek en vaderland|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n* The term was frequently used by some [[Media portrayal of the Ukrainian crisis|Russian media]] during [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine]] to describe any form of criticism of Russian policy in Ukraine. [[Aleksandr Dugin]] came up with a concept of \"sixth column\" describing those members of Russian elite who do not demonstrate sufficient enthusiasm in supporting the official policy and thus indirectly support the enemy.<ref name=\"\u0417\u0430 \u0410\u0445\u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\">{{cite web|author=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0414\u0443\u0433\u0438\u043d|script-title=ru:\u0417\u0430 \u0410\u0445\u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0434\u044c\u044e \u0432\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0448\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0430|url=http://www.nakanune.ru/news/2014/5/21/22353563/|website=Nakanune.ru|language=Russian|date=May 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the US an Australian radio play, ''The Enemy Within'', proved to be very popular, though this popularity was due to the belief that the stories of fifth column activities were based on real events. In December 1940 the Australian censors had the series banned.<ref>{{cite book |first=Robert |last=Loeffel |title=The Fifth Column in World War II: Suspected Subversives in the Pacific War and Australia |publisher=Palgrave |year=2015 |pages=85}}</ref>\n\nBritish reviewers of [[Agatha Christie]]'s novel ''[[N or M?]]'' in 1941 used the term to describe the struggle of two British partisans of the Nazi regime working on its behalf in Britain during World War II.<ref>''The Times Literary Supplement,'' November 29, 1941 (p. 589); ''The Observer,'' December 7, 1941 (p. 3)</ref>\n\nJames Ellroy heavily references the presence of fifth column activities in Los Angeles following the attacks on Pearl Harbor in his novels, ''Perfidia'' and ''This Storm''.\n\nIn [[Frank Capra]]'s film ''[[Meet John Doe]]'' (1941), newspaper editor Henry Connell warns the politically-na\u00efve protagonist, John Doe, about a businessman's plans to promote his own political ambitions using the apolitical John Doe Clubs. Connell says to John: \"Listen, pal, this fifth-column stuff is pretty rotten, isn't it?\", identifying the businessman with anti-democratic interests in the United States. When Doe agrees, he adds: \"And you'd feel like an awful sucker if you found yourself marching right in the middle of it, wouldn't you?\"<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=McGilligan | editor-first=Patrick |last1=Riskin |first1=Robert |title=Six Screenplays |url=https://archive.org/details/sixscreenplaysby00robe |url-access=registration |date=1997|publisher=University of California Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/sixscreenplaysby00robe/page/664 664], 696}}</ref>\n\n[[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[Saboteur (film)|Saboteur]]'' (1942) features [[Robert Cummings]] asking for help against \"fifth columnists\" conspiring to sabotage the American war effort.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} Soon the term was being used in popular .S entertainment. \n\nSeveral World War II era animated shorts include the term. Cartoons of [[Porky Pig]] asked any \"fifth columnists\" in the audience to leave the theater immediately.<ref>{{IMDb title | id = 0033892 | title = Meet John Doughboy}}</ref> In [[Looney Tunes]]' ''Foney Fables'', the narrator of a comic fairy tale described a wolf in sheep's clothing as a \"fifth columnist\".<ref>{{IMDb title | id = 0034744 | title = Foney Fables}}</ref> There was a [[Merrie Melodies]] cartoon released in 1943 titled ''[[The Fifth-Column Mouse]].''<ref>{{IMDb title | id = 0035872 | title = The Fifth-Column Mouse}}</ref> Comic books also contained references to the Fifth column.<ref>{{cite book |last= Goodnow |first= Trischa |title= The 10 Cent War: Comic Books, Propaganda, and World War II |url= https://books.google.com/?id=dbnPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT127&lpg=PT127&dq=comic+book+references+to+fifth+column#v=onepage&q=comic%20book%20references%20to%20fifth%20column&f=false|isbn= 9781496810311 |date= January 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nGraham Greene, in ''[[The Quiet American]]'' (1955) famously uses the phrase \"Fifth Column, Third Force, Seventh Day\" in the second chapter.\n\nThe [[V (franchise)|V franchise]] is a set of TV shows, novels and comics about an alien invasion of Earth. A group of aliens opposed to the invasion and assist the human Resistance Movement is called The Fifth Column.\n\nIn the episode \"Flight Into the Future\" from the 1960s TV show ''[[Lost In Space]]'', Dr. Smith was referred to as the fifth columnist of the Jupiter 2 expedition. In the first episode, he was a secret agent sent to sabotage the mission who got caught on board at liftoff.\n\nThere is an American weekly news podcast called \"The Fifth Column\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wethefifth.com/|title=The Fifth Column / Podcast|website=The Fifth Column / Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> hosted by [[Kmele Foster]], [[Matt Welch]], [[Michael C. Moynihan]], and Anthony Fisher.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alien invasion#Alien infiltration|Alien infiltration]]\n* [[Copperhead (politics)]]\n* [[Black propaganda]]\n* [[Demographic threat]]\n* [[Entryism]]\n* [[False flag]]\n* [[Front organization]]\n* [[Quisling]]\n* [[Sleeper cell]]\n* [[Stay-behind]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\nFoyles War, Series 2 Episode 3, \"War Games\" - \"It's the Second salvage collection I've missed, they've got me down as a fifth columnist\"\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* {{cite book|title=The German Fifth Column in Poland|location=London|publisher=Polish Ministry of Info|date=1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Fifth Column at Work|first=Bohumil|last=Bilek|location=London|publisher=Trinity|date=1945}}\n* {{cite book|first=Robert|last=Loeffel|title=The Fifth Column in World War II: Suspected Subversives in the Pacific War and Australia|publisher=Palgrave|date=2015}}\n\n{{Media manipulation}}\n\n[[Category:Deep politics]]\n[[Category:Intelligence operations by type]]\n[[Category:Irregular military]]\n[[Category:Psychological warfare techniques]]\n[[Category:Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:Urban guerrilla warfare tactics]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses2|Fifth Column}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n[[File:\"Appreciate America Stop the Fifth Column\" - NARA - 513873.jpg|thumb|upright|World War II poster from the United States]]\nA '''fifth column''' is any group of people who undermine a larger group from within, usually in favor of an enemy group or nation.  The activities of a fifth column can be overt or clandestine. Forces gathered in secret can mobilize openly to assist an external attack. This term is also extended to organised actions by military personnel. Clandestine fifth column activities can involve acts of sabotage, disinformation, or espionage executed within defense lines by secret sympathizers with an external force.\n\n==Origin==\n[[File:\u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043b\u044c \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432.JPG|thumb|160px|left|[[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republican]] patrol on the streets of Madrid, 1936]]\nThe term \"fifth column\" originated in Spain (originally ''quinta columna'') during the early phase of the [[Spanish Civil War|Civil War]]. It gained extreme popularity in the [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republican]] media since early October 1936, and immediately started to make rounds also abroad.<ref>in French newspapers the term first appeared on October 4, 1936, one day after its first usage in the Madrid press, ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k7634839j/f5.item.r=Cinqui%C3%A8me%20colonne.zoom La Passionaria preche la terreur]'', [in:] ''Le Journal'' 04.10.1936. In more distant countries like Poland the term started to appear since mid-October, see e.g. ''[https://polona.pl/item/dziennik-wilenski-r-20-nr-285-18-pazdziernika-1936,MTU3NDQwNDU/0/#info:metadata Oviedo ostatecznie uwolnione]'', [in:] ''Dziennik Wile\u0144ski'' 18.10.1936</ref> \n\nExact origins of the term are not clear. Its first identified appearance was in a secret telegram sent to [[Berlin]] by the [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Charg\u00e9 d'affaires|charge d\u2019affaires]] in [[Alicante]], [[:de:Hans Hermann V\u00f6lckers|Hans-Hermann V\u00f6lckers]] dated September 30, 1936. He referred to an unidentified \"supposed statement by [[Francisco Franco|Franco]]\" which \"is being circulated\" (apparently in the [[Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)|Republican]] zone or in the Republican-held [[Levante, Spain|Levantine]] zone). In the statement, Franco allegedly claimed that there were four [[Nationalist faction (Spanish Civil War)|Nationalist]] columns approaching Madrid and the fifth column waited to rise from the inside.<ref>Ruiz, Julius (2014), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=HqBcAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA185&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIbjAH#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The 'Red Terror' and the Spanish Civil War]'', Cambridge, {{ISBN|9781107054547}}, p. 187</ref> However, the telegram was part of the secret German diplomatic correspondence and was discovered long after the Civil War.\n\nThe first public use of the term identified is in the October 3, 1936 issue of the Madrid [[Communist]] daily ''[[Mundo Obrero]]''. In a front-page article the party propagandist [[Dolores Ib\u00e1rruri]] referred the same statement as reported by V\u00f6lckers, but attributed it to general [[Emilio Mola]].<ref>the actual copy of ''Mundo Obrero'' is not available for consultation online. Many authors claim that in the article Ibarruri referred to an unidentified Mola's radio broadcast, see e.g. Preston Paul (2011), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=IsNUHLStdDUC&pg=PT198&lpg=PT198&dq=mola+quinta+columna&source=bl&ots=jKdsKJnw5W&sig=ACfU3U0ZBMg0Q2B9a3vKHX5Uge1Pik9lZg&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi68vHu3P7nAhVwkosKHQ7uCaIQ6AEwCXoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=mola%20quinta%20columna&f=false La Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola: reacci\u00f3n, revoluci\u00f3n y venganza]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788499891507}}. However, other scholars when quoting Ibarruri do not refer the broadcast detail, see e.g. Ruiz 2014, pp. 185-186</ref> On the same day the [[Communist Party of Spain|PCE]] activist Domingo Gir\u00f3n made a similar claim during a public rally.<ref>Domingo Gir\u00f3n was a Madrid mid-range Communist activist. In his speech he referred to \"cierta declaraci\u00f3n hecha por el general Mola a un periodista extranjero\", ''[https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000207223&posicion=4&presentacion=pagina Un gran mitin del Socorro Rojo internacional]'', [in:] ''Hoja Oficial del lunes'' 04.10.1936. In March 1939 he was detained by the Casadistas and handed over to the Francoists later on. Following trial, he was sentenced to death and executed on July 3, 1941</ref> During the following days Republican papers repeated the story, but with differing detail; some attributed the phrase to [[Gonzalo Queipo de Llano|general Queipo de Llano]].<ref>Ruiz 2014, pp. 186-187</ref> In mid-October media already warned against \"famous fifth column\".<ref>''[https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/catalogo_imagenes/grupo.do?path=1000145318&posicion=2&presentacion=pagina Informacion radiotelegrafica]'', [in:] ''El bien publico'' 13.10.1936</ref>\n\nHistorians have never identified the original statement referred by V\u00f6lckers, Ib\u00e1rruri and others.<ref> De Jong Louis (2019), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=RM6gDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT14&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The German Fifth Column in the Second World War]'', London, {{ISBN|9781000008098}}</ref> Though transcripts of Franco\u2019s, Queipo and Mola\u2019s radio addresses have been published, they did not contain the term referred;<ref>Preston Paul (2012), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=7PKHUTjX0UAC&pg=PT563&lpg=PT563&dq=Carlos+Contreras,+%27En+defensa+de+Madrid:+la+quinta+columna%27,+Mi&source=bl&ots=SoEfQPpYaK&sig=ACfU3U09M9IDV3rBmcuduPV8H5De5v4bZA&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiwiMbS4P7nAhXloosKHRPxBtYQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Carlos%20Contreras%2C%20'En%20defensa%20de%20Madrid%3A%20la%20quinta%20columna'%2C%20Mi&f=false The Spanish Holocaust: Inquisition and Extermination in Twentieth-Century Spain]'', London, {{ISBN|9780393239669}} </ref> no other original statement with the phrase in question has ever surfaced. A British journalist who took part in Mola\u2019s press conference on October 28, 1936 claimed that Mola referred to ''quinta columna'' on this very day,<ref> Preston Paul (2011), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=IsNUHLStdDUC&pg=PT198&lpg=PT198&dq=mola+quinta+columna&source=bl&ots=jKdsKJnw5W&sig=ACfU3U0ZBMg0Q2B9a3vKHX5Uge1Pik9lZg&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi68vHu3P7nAhVwkosKHQ7uCaIQ6AEwCXoECA0QAQ#v=onepage&q=mola%20quinta%20columna&f=false La Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola: reacci\u00f3n, revoluci\u00f3n y venganza]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788499891507}}</ref> though at that time the term had already been used in the Republican press for more than 3 weeks.<ref>''[https://prensahistorica.mcu.es/es/consulta/resultados_ocr.do Prensa Historica]'' service, ''[http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/ Hemeroteca Digital]'' service  </ref>\n\n[[Historiographic]] works offer differing perspectives on authorship of the term. Many scholars have no doubt about Mola\u2019s role and refer to \"fifth column\" as to \"a term coined in 1936 by General Emilio Mola\",<ref>Kennedy, David M. (ed.) (2007), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=0bRaa7UuD6EC&pg=PA79&dq=fifth+column+the+term+invented&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjx4vn84v7nAhUJxYsKHWQPA8cQ6AEIMzAB#v=onepage&q=fifth%20column%20the%20term%20invented&f=false The Library of Congress World War II Companion]'', New York, {{ISBN|9781416553069}}, p. 79, also Lejeune Anthony (ed.) (2018), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=yHh0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT268&dq=quinta+columna+mola+nunca&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQlIvr7v7nAhUqposKHS7gBZIQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=quinta%20columna%20mola%20nunca&f=false Concise Dictionary of Foreign Quotations]'', London, {{ISBN|9781135974893}}, , also Romero Salvad\u00f3, Francisco J., (2013), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=i5e7wRi-HGcC&pg=PA199&dq=ibarruri+quinta+columna&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjW6pmn9P7nAhWBl4sKHbf4C-4Q6AEINTAB#v=onepage&q=ibarruri%20quinta%20columna&f=false Historical Dictionary of the Spanish Civil War]'', London, {{ISBN|9780810880092}}, p. 199, </ref> though they admit that the exact statement can not be identified.<ref>Preston Paul (2011), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=aPV1johx8NMC&pg=PR211&dq=quinta+columna+mola+nunca&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQlIvr7v7nAhUqposKHS7gBZIQ6AEISDAD#v=onepage&q=quinta%20columna%20mola%20nunca&f=false El holocausto espa\u00f1ol: Odio y exterminio en la Guerra Civil y despu\u00e9s]'', 2011, {{ISBN|9788499920498}}, </ref> In some sources Mola is noted as a person who used the term during an impromptu press interview, and different though detailed versions of the exchange are offered.<ref>one version is \u201cs\u00f3mo es, general Mola, que piensa usted tomar Madrid con cuatro columnas?; no, no tengo cuatro; son cinco las columnas que tengo, porque en Madrid hay una quinta columna\", Carrillo Alejandro (1943), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=suJYAAAAMAAJ&q=no+tiene+usted+sino+cuatro+columnas,general.+Tengo+la+quinta+columna+en+Madrid&dq=no+tiene+usted+sino+cuatro+columnas,general.+Tengo+la+quinta+columna+en+Madrid&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ3_7a8P7nAhVeAxAIHd5pCvgQ6AEIPzAC Defensa de la revoluci\u00f3n en el Parlamento]'', s.n. 1943,. Other version is \u201cno tiene usted sino cuatro columnas, general; tengo la \u201cQuinta Columna\u201d en Madrid\u201d, P\u00e9rez de Oliva, Fern\u00e1n (1991), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=vk1PJ632CMEC&pg=PA22&dq=no+tiene+usted+sino+cuatro+columnas,general.+Tengo+la+quinta+columna+en+Madrid&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ3_7a8P7nAhVeAxAIHd5pCvgQ6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=no%20tiene%20usted%20sino%20cuatro%20columnas%2Cgeneral.%20Tengo%20la%20quinta%20columna%20en%20Madrid&f=false Historia de la invenci\u00f3n de las Indias]'', Madrid 1991, {{ISBN|9789682317699}}, p. 22</ref> Probably the most popular version refers the theory of Mola\u2019s authorship with a grade of doubt, either noting that it is presumed but never proven<ref>Barros Andrew, Thomas Martin (2018), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=BWJjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIPTAC#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The Civilianization of War: The Changing Civil\u2013Military Divide]'', 1914\u20132014, Cambridge, {{ISBN|9781108429658}}, p. 49</ref> or that the phrase \"is attributed\" to Mola,<ref> Loeffel Robert (2015), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=MvWKCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR22&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIRzAD#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The Fifth Column in World War II: Suspected Subversives in the Pacific War and Australia]'', London, {{ISBN|9781137506672}}</ref> who \"apparently claimed\" so,<ref>Beevor, Antony (2006), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=Q-mayoYS6eIC&pg=PT369&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIhQEwCQ#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The Battle for Spain: The Spanish Civil War 1936-1939]'', London, {{ISBN|9781101201206}}</ref> or they note \"la famosa quinta columna a la que parece que se hab\u00eda referido el general Mola.\"<ref>Cierva, Ricardo de la (1996), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=Jm8fAAAAMAAJ&q=quinta+columna+de+mola+invencion+comunista&dq=quinta+columna+de+mola+invencion+comunista&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiUqcWj8_7nAhWhlosKHQPsAqw4FBDoAQgnMAA Historia esencial de la Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola: todos los problemas resueltos, sesenta a\u00f1os despu\u00e9s]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788488787125}}</ref> Some authors consider it possible if not likely that the term has been invented by the Communist propaganda with the purpose of either raising morale or providing justification for [[Republican repression in Madrid (1936\u20131939)|terror and repression]]; initially it might have been part of the [[whispering campaign]], but was later openly floated by Communist propagandists.<ref>Ruiz Julius (2014), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=HqBcAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA185&dq=mola+fifth+column&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-l43q3_7nAhVks4sKHU_ZB8YQ6AEIbjAH#v=onepage&q=mola%20fifth%20column&f=false The 'Red Terror' and the Spanish Civil War]'', Cambridge, {{ISBN|9781107054547}}, p. 185. The opposing view is that the Republican repression was inadvertently triggered by Mola, who did not realize what effect his alleged statement would have, Laguna Reyes Albert, Vargas M\u00e1rquez Antonio (2019), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=u7mPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT10&dq=quinta+columna+mola+nunca&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQlIvr7v7nAhUqposKHS7gBZIQ6AEIPTAC#v=onepage&q=quinta%20columna%20mola%20nunca&f=false La Quinta Columna: La guerra clandestina tras las l\u00edneas republicanas 1936-1939]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788491645894}}</ref> There are also other theories afloat.<ref>a British correspondent in the Republican zone claimed after the Civil War that \"many weeks\" before October 1936 he had used the term in ''The Daily Telegraph'' when discusing the Nationalist advance towards Madrid. Allegedly the term was picked up by Republican journalists and in turn somehow filtered out to the Nationalist zone; Mola liked it and started to use it. The alleged ''Daily Telegraph'' reference has never been identified. Thomas, Hugh (2018), ''[https://books.google.es/books?id=J4VMDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=pl&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=oswald&f=false La guerra civil espa\u00f1ola]'', Madrid, {{ISBN|9788466344821}}</ref>\n[[File:\u0414\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0441 \u0418\u0431\u0430\u0440\u0440\u0443\u0440\u0438.JPG|thumb|[[Dolores Ib\u00e1rruri]]]]\nThough the 1936 usage is widely regarded as the origins of the phrase, historian [[Christopher Clark]] quotes a February 1906 letter by Austrian [[military attach\u00e9]] Joseph Pomiankowski using the phrase, \"the fifth-column work of the [[People's Radical Party|[Serbian] Radicals]] in peacetime, which systematically poisons the attitude of our [[South Slavs|South Slav population]] and could, if the worst came to the worst, create very serious difficulties for our army.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Sleepwalkers : How Europe Went to War in 1914|last=M.|first=Clark, Christopher|isbn=9780061146657|edition=First U.S.|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780061146657/page/58 58]|oclc=795757585|date=March 19, 2013|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780061146657/page/58}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Krieg im Frieden\" : die F\u00fchrung der k.u.k. Armee und die Grossmachtpolitik \u00d6sterreich-Ungarns 1906-1914|last=G\u00fcnther.|first=Kronenbitter|date=2003|publisher=Oldenbourg|isbn=3486567004|location=M\u00fcnchen|pages=327|oclc=53805594}}</ref><ref>Letter from Austrian military attache in Belgrade, Serbia, Joseph Pomiankowski to Beck, cited and quoted from reference #2, G\u00fcnther Kronenbitter: ''Krieg im Frieden. Die F\u00fchrung der k.u.k. Armee und die Gro\u00dfmachtpolitik \u00d6sterreich-Ungarns 1906\u20131914'' (\"War in Peace. The Leadership of the Imperial and Royal Army and the Great Power Politics of Austria-Hungary 1906-1914\"), Verlag Oldenbourg, Munich, 2003, {{ISBN|3-486-56700-4}}, p. 327</ref>\n\nSome writers, mindful of the origin of the phrase, use it only in reference to military operations rather than the broader and less well defined range of activities that sympathizers might engage in to support an anticipated attack.{{efn|[[Madeleine Albright]], for example, in a lengthy account of [[Germans|German]] sympathizers in [[Czechoslovakia]] in the first years of [[World War II]], does not use the phrase to describe their actions until she considers their possible response to a German invasion: \"Many, perhaps most, of the Sudetens would have provided the enemy with a fifth column\".<ref name=albright>{{cite book|last=Albright|first=Madeleine|title=Prague Winter: A Personal Story of Remembrance and War, 1937-1948|url=https://archive.org/details/praguewinterpers0000albr|url-access=registration|year=2012|publisher=HarperCollins|location=NY|pages=[https://archive.org/details/praguewinterpers0000albr/page/102 102]}}</ref>}}\n\n==Second World War==\n{{Globalize|section|the USA|date=February 2019}}\nBy the late 1930s, as American involvement in the war in Europe became more likely, the term \"fifth column\" was commonly used to warn of potential sedition and disloyalty within the borders of the United States. The fear of betrayal was heightened by the rapid [[Battle of France|fall of France]] in 1940, which some blamed on internal weakness and a pro-German \"fifth column\". A series of photos run in the June 1940 issue of ''[[Life magazine|Life]]'' magazine warned of \"signs of Nazi Fifth Column Everywhere\". In a speech to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] that same month, [[Winston Churchill]] reassured [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MPs]] that \"Parliament has given us the powers to put down Fifth Column activities with a strong hand.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1940-the-finest-hour/we-shall-fight-on-the-beaches|title=We Shall Fight on the Beaches|last=Churchill|first=Winston|date=June 4, 1940|website=winstonchurchill.org|access-date=25 July 2017}}</ref> In July 1940, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine referred to talk of a fifth column as a \"national phenomenon\".<ref>Richard W. Steele, ''Free Speech in the Good War'' (St. Martin's Press, 1999, 75-6)</ref>\n\nIn August 1940, ''[[The New York Times]]'' mentioned \"the first spasm of fear engendered by the success of fifth columns in less fortunate countries\".<ref>''The New York Times'': [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/08/25/96932000.pdf Delbert Clark, \"Aliens to Begin Registering Tuesday,\" August 25, 1940]. Retrieved June 27, 2012.</ref> One report identified participants in Nazi \"fifth columns\" as \"partisans of authoritarian government everywhere,\" citing [[Poland]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The German Fifth Column in Poland|last=Polish Ministry of Information|publisher=Dale Street Books|year=2014|isbn=9781941656099|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=3\u20136}}</ref> [[Czechoslovakia]], [[Norway]], and the [[Netherlands]]. During the [[Norwegian Campaign|Nazi invasion of Norway]], the head of the Norwegian fascist party, [[Vidkun Quisling]], proclaimed the formation of a new fascist government in control of Norway, with himself as Prime Minister, by the end of the first day of fighting. The word \"quisling\" soon became a byword for \"collaborator\" or \"traitor\".<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/06/16/121427281.pdf |first=Otto D. |last= Tolischus |title=How Hitler Made Ready: I - The Fifth Column |date=June 16, 1940 |accessdate= July 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' on August 11, 1940 featured three editorial cartoons using the term.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/08/11/94836997.pdf |first=Frederick R. |last=Barkley |title=Nation Shapes Defense against Foes at Home |date= August 11, 1940| accessdate= July 7, 2012}}</ref> [[John Langdon-Davies]], a British journalist who covered the Spanish Civil War, wrote an account called ''The Fifth Column'' which was published the same year. In November 1940, Ralph Thomson, reviewing Harold Lavine's ''Fifth Column in America,'' a study of Communist and fascist groups in the U.S., in ''The New York Times,'' questioned his choice of that title: \"the phrase has been worked so hard that it no longer means much of anything.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thomson|first1=Ralph |title=Books of the Times|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1940/11/27/94016453.pdf |accessdate=April 25, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=November 27, 1940}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Seuss cartoon.png|thumb|[[Dr. Seuss]] cartoon in [[PM (newspaper)|PM]] dated February 13, 1942, with the caption 'Waiting for the Signal from Home']]\nImmediately following the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]], U.S. Secretary of the Navy [[Frank Knox]] issued a statement that \"the most effective Fifth Column work of the entire war was done in Hawaii with the exception of Norway.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Niiya |first=Brian |url=http://encyclopedia.densho.org/Frank_Knox/ |title=Frank Knox |publisher=Densho Encyclopedia |accessdate=August 27, 2014}}</ref> In a column published in ''[[The Washington Post]]'', dated 12 February 1942, the columnist [[Walter Lippmann]] wrote of imminent danger from actions that might be taken by [[Japanese American]]s. Titled \"The Fifth Column on the Coast,\" he wrote of possible attacks that could be made along the West Coast of the United States that would amplify damage inflicted by a potential attack by Japanese naval and air forces.<ref>{{cite web|last=Niiya |first=Brian |url=http://encyclopedia.densho.org/The_Fifth_Column_on_the_Coast/ |title=The Fifth Column on the Coast |publisher=Densho Encyclopedia |accessdate=August 27, 2014}}</ref> Suspicion about an active fifth column on the coast led eventually to the [[internment of Japanese Americans]].\n\nDuring the [[Philippines Campaign (1941\u201342)|Japanese invasion of the Philippines]], an article in the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' in December 1941 said the indigenous [[Moro people|Moro Muslims]] were \"capable of dealing with Japanese fifth columnists and invaders alike\".<ref>{{cite news |date= December 22, 1941 |title=80 Japanese Troop Ships Are Sighted Off Luzon (Continued From Page1) |url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oJRRAAAAIBAJ&pg=2732,2587117&hl=en |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |page = 7 |accessdate= October 30, 2014}}</ref> Another in the ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'' the following month described how the large population of Japanese immigrants in [[Davao Region|Davao]] in the Philippines welcomed the invasion: \"the first assault on Davao was aided by numbers of Fifth Columnists\u2013residents of the town\".<ref>{{cite news |last= Curtis |first= Herbert |date= January 13, 1942 |title= Japanese Infiltration Into Mindanao |url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sDRlAAAAIBAJ&pg=2656,1332631&hl=en |newspaper= Vancouver Sun |page = 4 |accessdate= October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Later usage==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1986-042-14, Anschluss sudetendeutscher Gebiete.jpg|thumb|[[Sudeten German]] [[Freikorps]]]]\n\n* German minority organizations in [[Czechoslovakia]] formed the [[Sudetendeutsches Freikorps|Sudeten German Free Corps]], which aided the [[Third Reich]]. Some claimed they were \"self-defense formations\" created in the aftermath of [[World War I]] and unrelated to the German invasion two decades later.<ref>Robert G.L. Waite, ''Vanguard of Nazism: The Free Corps Movement in Post-War Germany, 1918-1923'' (1952), 88</ref> More often their origins were discounted and they were defined by the role they played in 1938\u201339: \"The same pattern was repeated in Czechoslovakia. [[Konrad Henlein|Henlein]]'s Free Corps played in that country the part of fifth column\".<ref>Yale Law School: [http://avalon.law.yale.edu/imt/12-20-45.asp Nuremberg Trial Proceedings Volume 4, 215, December 20, 1945]. Retrieved July 19, 2012</ref>\n* In 1945, a document produced by the [[U.S. Department of State]] compared the earlier efforts of Nazi Germany to mobilize the support of sympathizers in foreign nations to the superior efforts of the international communist movement at the end of World War II: \"a communist party was in fact a fifth column as much as any [German] Bund group, except that the latter were crude and ineffective in comparison with the Communists\".<ref>Thomas G. Paterson, ''Meeting the Communist Threat: Truman to Reagan'' (Oxford University Press, 1988), 10</ref> [[Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr.]], wrote in 1949: \"the special Soviet advantage\u2014the warhead\u2014lies in the fifth column; and the fifth column is based on the local Communist parties\".<ref>Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr., ''The Politics of Freedom'' (Heinemann, 1950), 92-3</ref>\n* [[Zainichi Koreans|North Koreans]] living in [[Japan]], particularly those affiliated with the organization [[Chongryun]] (which is itself affiliated with the government of [[North Korea]]) are sometimes seen as a \"fifth column\" by some Japanese, and have been the victims of verbal and physical attacks. These have occurred more frequently since the government of [[Kim Jong Il]] acknowledged it had [[North Korean abductions of Japanese|abducted people from Japan]] and [[North Korean missile test, 2006|tested ballistic missiles]].<ref>\"North Koreans in Japan have long been vilified as a communist fifth column\" (Hans Greimel, \"Test sparks N. Korea Backlash in Japan\", [[Associated Press]] dispatch, October 24, 2006 {{cite web |url=http://www.plesserholland.com/pdf/10.24.06-Kang-AP-NK.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-01-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205074933/http://www.plesserholland.com/pdf/10.24.06-Kang-AP-NK.pdf |archivedate=February 5, 2007 |df=mdy-all }})</ref>\n* Some [[Israeli Jews]], including politicians, [[rabbi]]s, journalists, and historians, who believe that [[Arab citizens of Israel|Israeli Arabs]] identify more with the [[Palestinian nationalism|Palestinian cause]] than with the state of Israel or [[Zionism]], have referred to them, who compose approximately 20% of Israel's population, as a fifth column.<ref>\"... they hurl accusations against us, like that we are a 'fifth column'.\" (Roee Nahmias, \"[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3285075,00.html Arab MK: Israel committing 'genocide' of Shiites]\", [[Ynetnews]] August 2, 2006)</ref><ref>\"... a fifth column, a league of traitors\" (Evelyn Gordon, \"[http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull&cid=1157913624780 No longer the political fringe]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\", [[Jerusalem Post]] September 14, 2006)</ref>\n* [[Counter-jihad]] literature has sought to portray Western Muslims as a \"fifth column\", collectively seeking to destabilize Western nations' identity and values for the benefit of an international Islamic movement intent on the [[Eurabia|establishment of a caliphate in Western countries]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Akbarzadeh|first1=Shahram|last2=Roose|first2=Joshua M.|title=Muslims, Multiculturalism and the Question of the Silent Majority|journal=Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs|date=September 2011|volume=31|issue=3|pages=309\u2013325|doi=10.1080/13602004.2011.599540}}</ref> Following the 2015 attack by French-born Muslims on the offices of ''[[Charlie Hebdo shooting|Charlie Hebdo]]'' in Paris, the leader of the [[UK Independence Party]] [[Nigel Farage]] said that Europe had \"a fifth column living within our own countries\".<ref>{{cite news|work=National Review |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/395914/ukips-farage-multiculturalism-creating-fifth-column-west-brendan-bordelon |first=Brendan |last=Bordelon |title=UKIP's Farage: Multiculturalism Creating 'Fifth Column' in West |date= January 7, 2015 | accessdate= January 8, 2015}}</ref> In 2001 Dutch politician [[Pim Fortuyn]] talked about Muslim immigrants being a \"fifth column\" the night he was dismissed as leader of [[Liveable Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.historischnieuwsblad.nl/nl/artikel/32279/fortuyn-ramp-voor-politiek-en-vaderland.html|title=Fortuyn: ramp voor politiek en vaderland|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n* The term was frequently used by some [[Media portrayal of the Ukrainian crisis|Russian media]] during [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine]] to describe any form of criticism of Russian policy in Ukraine. [[Aleksandr Dugin]] came up with a concept of \"sixth column\" describing those members of Russian elite who do not demonstrate sufficient enthusiasm in supporting the official policy and thus indirectly support the enemy.<ref name=\"\u0417\u0430 \u0410\u0445\u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\">{{cite web|author=\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u0414\u0443\u0433\u0438\u043d|script-title=ru:\u0417\u0430 \u0410\u0445\u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0434\u044c\u044e \u0432\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0448\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0430|url=http://www.nakanune.ru/news/2014/5/21/22353563/|website=Nakanune.ru|language=Russian|date=May 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the US an Australian radio play, ''The Enemy Within'', proved to be very popular, though this popularity was due to the belief that the stories of fifth column activities were based on real events. In December 1940 the Australian censors had the series banned.<ref>{{cite book |first=Robert |last=Loeffel |title=The Fifth Column in World War II: Suspected Subversives in the Pacific War and Australia |publisher=Palgrave |year=2015 |pages=85}}</ref>\n\nBritish reviewers of [[Agatha Christie]]'s novel ''[[N or M?]]'' in 1941 used the term to describe the struggle of two British partisans of the Nazi regime working on its behalf in Britain during World War II.<ref>''The Times Literary Supplement,'' November 29, 1941 (p. 589); ''The Observer,'' December 7, 1941 (p. 3)</ref>\n\nJames Ellroy heavily references the presence of fifth column activities in Los Angeles following the attacks on Pearl Harbor in his novels, ''Perfidia'' and ''This Storm''.\n\nIn [[Frank Capra]]'s film ''[[Meet John Doe]]'' (1941), newspaper editor Henry Connell warns the politically-na\u00efve protagonist, John Doe, about a businessman's plans to promote his own political ambitions using the apolitical John Doe Clubs. Connell says to John: \"Listen, pal, this fifth-column stuff is pretty rotten, isn't it?\", identifying the businessman with anti-democratic interests in the United States. When Doe agrees, he adds: \"And you'd feel like an awful sucker if you found yourself marching right in the middle of it, wouldn't you?\"<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=McGilligan | editor-first=Patrick |last1=Riskin |first1=Robert |title=Six Screenplays |url=https://archive.org/details/sixscreenplaysby00robe |url-access=registration |date=1997|publisher=University of California Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/sixscreenplaysby00robe/page/664 664], 696}}</ref>\n\n[[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[Saboteur (film)|Saboteur]]'' (1942) features [[Robert Cummings]] asking for help against \"fifth columnists\" conspiring to sabotage the American war effort.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} Soon the term was being used in popular .S entertainment. \n\nSeveral World War II era animated shorts include the term. Cartoons of [[Porky Pig]] asked any \"fifth columnists\" in the audience to leave the theater immediately.<ref>{{IMDb title | id = 0033892 | title = Meet John Doughboy}}</ref> In [[Looney Tunes]]' ''Foney Fables'', the narrator of a comic fairy tale described a wolf in sheep's clothing as a \"fifth columnist\".<ref>{{IMDb title | id = 0034744 | title = Foney Fables}}</ref> There was a [[Merrie Melodies]] cartoon released in 1943 titled ''[[The Fifth-Column Mouse]].''<ref>{{IMDb title | id = 0035872 | title = The Fifth-Column Mouse}}</ref> Comic books also contained references to the Fifth column.<ref>{{cite book |last= Goodnow |first= Trischa |title= The 10 Cent War: Comic Books, Propaganda, and World War II |url= https://books.google.com/?id=dbnPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT127&lpg=PT127&dq=comic+book+references+to+fifth+column#v=onepage&q=comic%20book%20references%20to%20fifth%20column&f=false|isbn= 9781496810311 |date= January 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nGraham Greene, in ''[[The Quiet American]]'' (1955) famously uses the phrase \"Fifth Column, Third Force, Seventh Day\" in the second chapter.\n\nThe [[V (franchise)|V franchise]] is a set of TV shows, novels and comics about an alien invasion of Earth. A group of aliens opposed to the invasion and assist the human Resistance Movement is called The Fifth Column.\n\nIn the episode \"Flight Into the Future\" from the 1960s TV show ''[[Lost In Space]]'', Dr. Smith was referred to as the fifth columnist of the Jupiter 2 expedition. In the first episode, he was a secret agent sent to sabotage the mission who got caught on board at liftoff.\n\nThere is an American weekly news podcast called \"The Fifth Column\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wethefifth.com/|title=The Fifth Column / Podcast|website=The Fifth Column / Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> hosted by [[Kmele Foster]], [[Matt Welch]], [[Michael C. Moynihan]], and Anthony Fisher.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alien invasion#Alien infiltration|Alien infiltration]]\n* [[Copperhead (politics)]]\n* [[Black propaganda]]\n* [[Demographic threat]]\n* [[Entryism]]\n* [[False flag]]\n* [[Front organization]]\n* [[Quisling]]\n* [[Sleeper cell]]\n* [[Stay-behind]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\nFoyles War, Series 2 Episode 3, \"War Games\" - \"It's the Second salvage collection I've missed, they've got me down as a fifth columnist\"\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* {{cite book|title=The German Fifth Column in Poland|location=London|publisher=Polish Ministry of Info|date=1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Fifth Column at Work|first=Bohumil|last=Bilek|location=London|publisher=Trinity|date=1945}}\n* {{cite book|first=Robert|last=Loeffel|title=The Fifth Column in World War II: Suspected Subversives in the Pacific War and Australia|publisher=Palgrave|date=2015}}\n\n{{Media manipulation}}\n\n[[Category:Deep politics]]\n[[Category:Intelligence operations by type]]\n[[Category:Irregular military]]\n[[Category:Psychological warfare techniques]]\n[[Category:Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:Urban guerrilla warfare tactics]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrigin", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifth_column"}
{"title_page": "Ross Errilly Friary", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n[[Image:RossErrillyFriary.jpg|300px|thumb|Right|The ruins of the Ross Errilly Friary.]]\n\nThe '''Ross Errilly Friary''' ({{lang-ga|Mainistir Ros Oirialaigh}}, often [[Anglicisation|anglicised]] in 18th & 19th century sources as ''Rosserelly'') is a [[medieval]] [[Franciscan]] [[friary]] located about a mile to the northwest of [[Headford]], [[County Galway]], Ireland. It is a [[National Monument (Ireland)|National Monument]] of Ireland and among the best-preserved medieval monastic sites in the country.  Though usually referred to by locals as \"Ross Abbey,\" this is not technically correct as the community never had an [[abbot]].<ref>Mooney 13\u201314.</ref>\n\nThe church and bell tower are to the south of a small but well preserved central [[cloister]] and domestic buildings are to the north.   Amongst these are a kitchen (equipped with an oven and a water tank for live fish), a bake house, and a refectory or dining area.  The dormitories are on the upper levels.  One unusual feature is a second courtyard or cloister, built to accommodate the friary's growing population.\n\nLike many other abandoned Christian sites in Ireland, Ross Errilly has continued to be used as a burial ground by area residents.  In addition to tombs that date from the friary's active period, many graves dating from the 18th through 20th centuries can be found inside the church walls.  In some cases, tombstones comprise the floors of walkways and crawlspaces.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Foundation ===\n[[File:Ross Friary East Range 2010 09 14.jpg|right|360px]]\nBoth [[Luke Wadding]] and the [[Annals of the Four Masters|Four Masters]] (who refer to Ross Errilly in their Annals as ''Ros-Oirbhealagh'') record that the abbey was founded in 1351, but this date has been called into question by numerous historians.  Architectural cues and documentary evidence have given rise to a modern consensus that the friary was founded sometime in the middle of the 15th century, perhaps around 1460.<ref>Mooney 12.</ref> The earliest existing documentary evidence however comes from a reference to the friary in the will of Galway man John Blake, son of Henry, who bequeathed the sum of 40 pence to the friary in 1469. But on the other hand some facts in support of the legend on the founding of the friary in 1351 cannot be overlooked. Firstly, history tells us that there was a plague \u2013 the \"Black Death\" rampant in the country in 1348 and succeeding years. Secondly, Archbishop MacHugh, who is credited with the foundation of the friary, was the metropolitan in Tuam. He was a Franciscan and a native of the Headford area and he died of the plague in 1349, and it could have taken three years to build the first part of the friary owing to the prevalence of the plague and the marshy condition of the soil.<ref group=note>\"The Friary of Ross\" a History and a Guide.</ref> In any case, it is clear from the architectural evidence that any religious building that may have been on the site prior to that time was greatly expanded during the 15th century. Around 1473, a delegation of Franciscans from Ross Errilly went to Donegal at the request of the [[Tyrconnell]] clan and founded the Donegal Friary, where the Four Masters would later write their famous Annals.\n\n=== After the English Reformation ===\n\nLife at Ross Errilly was disrupted by the [[English Reformation]].  The Franciscans had loudly opposed [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII's]] break with Rome, which would prove costly after the schism.  In 1538, English authorities imprisoned two hundred of the monks and banished or killed an indeterminate number of others.  The rest of the Franciscans' history at Ross Errilly would be marked by repeated evictions and other persecutions.\n\n[[Image:Refriary fish.jpg|300px|thumb|Right|This tank was used to hold live fish caught from the nearby [[Black River (Ireland)|Black River]].]]\n\nAt the beginning of the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]], the abbey was confiscated and given to Richard Burgh, the 2nd [[Earl of Clanrickarde]].  Burgh, a descendant of the de Burghs who had helped found the abbey, quietly gave it back to the Franciscans.  In 1572, an enclosing ditch and wall were constructed around the friary.<ref>Stalley 9.</ref>\n\nIn 1584, the English crown again confiscated the monastery from the Franciscans and gave it to an English noble who evicted the monks and plundered the building's contents.  In 1586, the Earl of Clanrickarde purchased the monastery and again returned it to the Franciscans.\n\nBy the end of the century, however, the crown had once again expelled the monks and converted the monastery into an English garrison for use during the [[Nine Years' War (Ireland)|Nine Years' War]].\n\nIn 1604, Ulick Burke, 3rd Earl of Clanrickarde, continuing to honour the de Burgh tradition of supporting Ross Errilly, financed the rehabilitation and reoccupation of the monastery by the Franciscans.  Their stay was short-lived; in 1612 Lord Arthur Chichester, [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland|Lord Deputy of Ireland]], ordered the [[Protestant archbishop of Tuam]], William Daniel, to expel the monks and to demolish the abbey's altars.  Daniel apparently complied with the order, but sent advance word to the residents of Ross Errilly and advised them to evacuate the abbey's most precious items.\n\nIn 1626, the monks returned to Ross Errilly and enjoyed a quarter-century of relative peace.  Records of the [[Franciscan|OFM]] in Ireland indicate that the community at this time consisted of just six priests and two brothers.  One piece of evidence for the friary's occupancy during this period is a handwritten [[testimony|testimonium]], dated 27 November 1636, and signed by a Boetius Mac Egan, then a [[prelate]] in residence at the friary.<ref>{{cite book | last = O'Donovan | first = John (trans.) | authorlink = John O'Donovan (scholar)|editor=[[James Henthorn Todd|Todd, James H.]] |editor2=[[William Reeves (bishop)|Reeves, William]] |title=The Martyrology of Donegal: A Calendar of the Saints of Ireland | url = https://archive.org/details/TheMartyrologyOfDonegal |year=1864 |publisher=Irish Archaeological and Celtic Society |location=Dublin |language=English, Latin | nopp = true |page=liii }}</ref>\n\n=== Rebellion and the Cromwellian era ===\n\nOn 18 February 1642, Ulick Burke and the monks were involved in the rescue of about 40 Protestant refugees of the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641|1641 uprising]], including the family of Dr. John Maxwell, the Protestant bishop of [[Killala]]. The refugees were being led from the town of [[Shrule]] when the Catholic soldiers comprising their escort massacred them.  It's not reliably known how many were killed, but one estimate placed the number of victims at 65.  Burke and the monks brought the survivors back to the Headford area and obtained shelter for them among the townspeople until safe passage to England could be arranged.\n\nThe [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland|Irish campaigns]] of [[Oliver Cromwell]] brought an end to this era of English tolerance of the Catholic Church in Ireland.  For a few nervous years, Ross Errilly served as an informal refugee shelter for Catholic clergy who had been flushed out of other parts of Ireland by Cromwell's forces.\n\nOn 10 August 1656, Cromwellian forces finally made their way to Ross Errilly.  The 140 Franciscans living there had fled a few hours earlier, but the soldiers ransacked the grounds, destroying crosses and other religious iconography and even defiling tombs in search of loot.  Legend maintains that the fleeing monks somehow found the time to remove the bell from the bell tower and sink it in the nearby Black River, where it remains today.  The [[English Restoration]] in 1660 brought [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] to the throne. His nominally tolerant policies towards Catholics allowed the reoccupation and repair of the abbey in 1664.\n\n=== Final years ===\n[[File:Ross Friary Cloister Garden NW Corner 2010 09 14.jpg|right|360px]]\nThe [[Glorious Revolution of 1688]], which deposed Charles' younger brother, the Catholic [[James II of England|James II]], eventually led to the [[Popery Act 1698|Popery Act of 1698]], which placed a [[Bounty (reward)|bounty]] on Catholic clergy.  Once again, the Franciscans of Ross Errilly became fugitives and abandoned the premises.\n\nLocal records indicate that by 1712, Franciscans had returned to the abbey.  Some sources indicate that the abbey was abandoned again in 1731, for reasons which are unclear.  What's certain is that by 1753, they had returned to the site.  The property was now owned by Lord St. George, a local noble, who picked up where the Clanrickardes had left off and secretly patronised the abbey.  By this time, the [[Penal Laws (Ireland)|Penal Laws]] were in effect and St. George risked life imprisonment by supporting the monks. A vengeful family who had lost a [[lawsuit]] to St. George reported to the authorities that he was sheltering Catholic religious at the monastery.  St. George learned of the accusations and the monks evacuated the monastery for the last time.  Before authorities arrived at the abbey, St. George had the abbey's interior whitewashed and had employed a group of [[weaving|weavers]] and their [[loom]]s inside the building.  The inquiry was ended without further incident, but the sham factory was soon closed and the monks never returned again.\n\nThe monks built cabins of wood and stone on a small island in the Black River, about one mile (1.6&nbsp;km) downstream from the abbey.  The island (which no longer exists) was known informally as \"Friars Island,\" and the community supported the monks with food, fuel and clothing via a wooden drawbridge.  For 36 years, the monks continued to celebrate Sunday [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] in the deteriorating abbey building.  In 1789, a Henry Lynch of [[Ballycurrin]] cheaply leased {{convert|16|acre|m2}} to the dispossessed monks at the foot of a hill in the [[townland]] of Kilroe, near Headford.  By 1801, only three monks remained, though Mass continued to be said at Kilroe until 1804.  There were still three monks in the community when it was closed in 1832.\n\n=== Abandonment and neglect ===\n\n[[Image:Rossabbey.jpg|300px|thumb|right|The abbey ruins as depicted in [[William Wilde]]'s 1867 book, ''[[Lough Corrib]], Its Shores and Islands''.]]\n\nIn the meantime, the long-abandoned friary continued its descent into ruin.  In 1835, English tourist John Barrow described the abbey as \"a remarkably fine old ruin ... in a disgracefully neglected state.\"  In particular, Barrow was astonished by the large amount of unburied human remains at the site, which included \"moss-grown skulls and human thigh and leg-bones strewed about so plentifully that not a step can be taken without encountering them.\"<ref>Barrow, John. ''A Tour Round Ireland, Through the Sea-coast Counties, in the Autumn of 1835.'' London. John Murray, Albemarle Street. 1836. p.260.</ref> Geographer [[Samuel Lewis (publisher)|Samuel Lewis]] noted the continued decay in 1837, writing that the abbey was \"partially covered in ivy\" and that the roof had collapsed in 1812.  Despite the neglect, Lewis was able to report that \"one of the windows is still perfect.\"<ref>{{cite web  | last = Lewis  | first = Samuel  | authorlink = Samuel Lewis (publisher)  | title = A Topographical Dictionary of Ireland  | publisher = Samuel Lewis  | year = 1837  | url = http://www.libraryireland.com/topog/h.php | accessdate = 24 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[William Wilde]] visited the abbey ruins in July 1866.  Like Barrow, he described \"heaps of skulls and bones\" in the church and claimed that the site had become notorious for its unburied remains.  Wilde noted with dismay that further \"desecration\" was being effected by sheep and cattle, which roamed freely through the ruins.  He also credited a nearby resident, Oliver Burke, with some early efforts to preserve the site by \"removing obstructions from between the [[mullion]]s of the beautiful windows\" and making \"repairs to the tower, thereby rendering it accessible to the top.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Lough Corrib, its shores and islands: with notices of Lough Mask |last=Wilde |first=William |authorlink=William Wilde |year=1867 |publisher=M.H. Gill |location=Dublin |pages=118\u20139 }}</ref> In 1868, Burke, a [[barrister]] by profession, wrote his own account of the friary's history.\n\n=== Today ===\n\nToday, the ruin of Ross Errilly is maintained by the [[Office of Public Works]] and is open to the public free of charge. It has been used as a filming location for ''[[Bad Karma (2002 film)|Bad Karma]]'', The Suicide Club, Moving Target & series Reign.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [[List of abbeys and priories in Ireland#County Galway|List of abbeys and priories in Ireland (County Galway)]]\n* [[Headford]]\n* [[Soraca Jonin]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Citation | last = Mooney  | first = Canice | title = The Friary of Ross: Foundation and Early Years  | journal = Journal of the Galway Archaeological and Historical Society | volume = 29  | pages = 7\u201314 | year = 1960 }}\n* {{Citation | last = Stalley  | first = Roger | title = The End of the Middle Ages: Gothic Survival in Sixteenth-Century Connacht  | journal = The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland | volume = 133  | pages = 5\u201323 | year = 2003 }}\n\n== External links==\n{{more footnotes|article|date=February 2008}}\n\n* [http://franciscans.ie/content/view/74/35/ Ross Abbey] at Irish Franciscans OFM\n* [http://www.irelandoldnews.com/Galway/1909/AUG.html Tuam Herald, Saturday, August 7 1909] at Ireland Old News\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/articles/abbeyrosserrily/ The Irish Ecclesiastical Record, Vol. V, No. I, October 1868] at Library Ireland\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/articles/ShruelDPJ1-33/index.php The Dublin Penny Journal, Volume 1, Number 33, February 9, 1833] at Library Ireland\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/topog/h.php A Topographical Dictionary of Ireland by Samuel Lewis] at Library Ireland\n* [http://www.headford.org/ross.htm History of Ross Abbey] at Headford.ie\n* [http://www.ucc.ie/celt/published/T100005C/index.html The Annals of the Four Masters] at University College Cork\n* [http://www.lawrencetown.com/longago.htm Long Ago in Ireland] at Lawrencetown Village, Co. Galway\n* [https://sketchfab.com/models/70c645a1dcf54e29982c1c5be905bc03 Ross Errilly Friary ] a 3D model of friary on Sketchfab\n\n{{coord|53|28|47.25|N|9|7|53.25|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Franciscan monasteries in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:1351 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Religion in County Galway]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in County Galway]]\n[[Category:Ruins in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Christian monasteries established in the 14th century]]\n[[Category:National Monuments in County Galway]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n[[Image:RossErrillyFriary.jpg|300px|thumb|Right|The ruins of the Ross Errilly Friary.]]\n\nThe '''Ross Errilly Friary''' ({{lang-ga|Mainistir Ros Oirialaigh}}, often [[Anglicisation|anglicised]] in 18th & 19th century sources as ''Rosserelly'') is a [[medieval]] [[Franciscan]] [[friary]] located about a mile to the northwest of [[Headford]], [[County Galway]], Ireland. It is a [[National Monument (Ireland)|National Monument]] of Ireland and among the best-preserved medieval monastic sites in the country.  Though usually referred to by locals as \"Ross Abbey,\" this is not technically correct as the community never had an [[abbot]].<ref>Mooney 13\u201314.</ref>\n\nThe church and bell tower are to the south of a small but well preserved central [[cloister]] and domestic buildings are to the north.   Amongst these are a kitchen (equipped with an oven and a water tank for live fish), a bake house, and a refectory or dining area.  The dormitories are on the upper levels.  One unusual feature is a second courtyard or cloister, built to accommodate the friary's growing population.\n\nLike many other abandoned Christian sites in Ireland, Ross Errilly has continued to be used as a burial ground by area residents.  In addition to tombs that date from the friary's active period, many graves dating from the 18th through 20th centuries can be found inside the church walls.  In some cases, tombstones comprise the floors of walkways and crawlspaces.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Foundation ===\n[[File:Ross Friary East Range 2010 09 14.jpg|right|360px]]\nBoth [[Luke Wadding]] and the [[Annals of the Four Masters|Four Masters]] (who refer to Ross Errilly in their Annals as ''Ros-Oirbhealagh'') record that the abbey was founded in 1351, but this date has been called into question by numerous historians.  Architectural cues and documentary evidence have given rise to a modern consensus that the friary was founded sometime in the middle of the 15th century, perhaps around 1460.<ref>Mooney 12.</ref> The earliest existing documentary evidence however comes from a reference to the friary in the will of Galway man John Blake, son of Henry, who bequeathed the sum of 40 pence to the friary in 1469. But on the other hand some facts in support of the legend on the founding of the friary in 1351 cannot be overlooked. Firstly, history tells us that there was a plague \u2013 the \"Black Death\" rampant in the country in 1348 and succeeding years. Secondly, Archbishop MacHugh, who is credited with the foundation of the friary, was the metropolitan in Tuam. He was a Franciscan and a native of the Headford area and he died of the plague in 1349, and it could have taken three years to build the first part of the friary owing to the prevalence of the plague and the marshy condition of the soil.<ref group=note>\"The Friary of Ross\" a History and a Guide.</ref> In any case, it is clear from the architectural evidence that any religious building that may have been on the site prior to that time was greatly expanded during the 15th century. Around 1473, a delegation of Franciscans from Ross Errilly went to Donegal at the request of the [[Tyrconnell]] clan and founded the Donegal Friary, where the Four Masters would later write their famous Annals.\n\n=== After the English Reformation ===\n\nLife at Ross Errilly was disrupted by the [[English Reformation]].  The Franciscans had loudly opposed [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII's]] break with Rome, which would prove costly after the schism.  In 1538, English authorities imprisoned two hundred of the monks and banished or killed an indeterminate number of others.  The rest of the Franciscans' history at Ross Errilly would be marked by repeated evictions and other persecutions.\n\n[[Image:Refriary fish.jpg|300px|thumb|Right|This tank was used to hold live fish caught from the nearby [[Black River (Ireland)|Black River]].]]\n\nAt the beginning of the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]], the abbey was confiscated and given to Richard Burgh, the 2nd [[Earl of Clanrickarde]].  Burgh, a descendant of the de Burghs who had helped found the abbey, quietly gave it back to the Franciscans.  In 1572, an enclosing ditch and wall were constructed around the friary.<ref>Stalley 9.</ref>\n\nIn 1584, the English crown again confiscated the monastery from the Franciscans and gave it to an English noble who evicted the monks and plundered the building's contents.  In 1586, the Earl of Clanrickarde purchased the monastery and again returned it to the Franciscans.\n\nBy the end of the century, however, the crown had once again expelled the monks and converted the monastery into an English garrison for use during the [[Nine Years' War (Ireland)|Nine Years' War]].\n\nIn 1604, Ulick Burke, 3rd Earl of Clanrickarde, continuing to honour the de Burgh tradition of supporting Ross Errilly, financed the rehabilitation and reoccupation of the monastery by the Franciscans.  Their stay was short-lived; in 1612 Lord Arthur Chichester, [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland|Lord Deputy of Ireland]], ordered the [[Protestant archbishop of Tuam]], William Daniel, to expel the monks and to demolish the abbey's altars.  Daniel apparently complied with the order, but sent advance word to the residents of Ross Errilly and advised them to evacuate the abbey's most precious items.\n\nIn 1626, the monks returned to Ross Errilly and enjoyed a quarter-century of relative peace.  Records of the [[Franciscan|OFM]] in Ireland indicate that the community at this time consisted of just six priests and two brothers.  One piece of evidence for the friary's occupancy during this period is a handwritten [[testimony|testimonium]], dated 27 November 1636, and signed by a Boetius Mac Egan, then a [[prelate]] in residence at the friary.<ref>{{cite book | last = O'Donovan | first = John (trans.) | authorlink = John O'Donovan (scholar)|editor=[[James Henthorn Todd|Todd, James H.]] |editor2=[[William Reeves (bishop)|Reeves, William]] |title=The Martyrology of Donegal: A Calendar of the Saints of Ireland | url = https://archive.org/details/TheMartyrologyOfDonegal |year=1864 |publisher=Irish Archaeological and Celtic Society |location=Dublin |language=English, Latin | nopp = true |page=liii }}</ref>\n\n=== Rebellion and the Cromwellian era ===\n\nOn 18 February 1642, Ulick Burke and the monks were involved in the rescue of about 40 Protestant refugees of the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641|1641 uprising]], including the family of Dr. John Maxwell, the Protestant bishop of [[Killala]]. The refugees were being led from the town of [[Shrule]] when the Catholic soldiers comprising their escort massacred them.  It's not reliably known how many were killed, but one estimate placed the number of victims at 65.  Burke and the monks brought the survivors back to the Headford area and obtained shelter for them among the townspeople until safe passage to England could be arranged.\n\nThe [[Cromwellian conquest of Ireland|Irish campaigns]] of [[Oliver Cromwell]] brought an end to this era of English tolerance of the Catholic Church in Ireland.  For a few nervous years, Ross Errilly served as an informal refugee shelter for Catholic clergy who had been flushed out of other parts of Ireland by Cromwell's forces.\n\nOn 10 August 1656, Cromwellian forces finally made their way to Ross Errilly.  The 140 Franciscans living there had fled a few hours earlier, but the soldiers ransacked the grounds, destroying crosses and other religious iconography and even defiling tombs in search of loot.  Legend maintains that the fleeing monks somehow found the time to remove the bell from the bell tower and sink it in the nearby Black River, where it remains today.  The [[English Restoration]] in 1660 brought [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] to the throne. His nominally tolerant policies towards Catholics allowed the reoccupation and repair of the abbey in 1664.\n\n=== Final years ===\n\nThe [[Glorious Revolution of 1688]], which deposed Charles' younger brother, the Catholic [[James II of England|James II]], eventually led to the [[Popery Act 1698|Popery Act of 1698]], which placed a [[Bounty (reward)|bounty]] on Catholic clergy.  Once again, the Franciscans of Ross Errilly became fugitives and abandoned the premises.\n\nLocal records indicate that by 1712, Franciscans had returned to the abbey.  Some sources indicate that the abbey was abandoned again in 1731, for reasons which are unclear.  What's certain is that by 1753, they had returned to the site.  The property was now owned by Lord St. George, a local noble, who picked up where the Clanrickardes had left off and secretly patronised the abbey.  By this time, the [[Penal Laws (Ireland)|Penal Laws]] were in effect and St. George risked life imprisonment by supporting the monks. A vengeful family who had lost a [[lawsuit]] to St. George reported to the authorities that he was sheltering Catholic religious at the monastery.  St. George learned of the accusations and the monks evacuated the monastery for the last time.  Before authorities arrived at the abbey, St. George had the abbey's interior whitewashed and had employed a group of [[weaving|weavers]] and their [[loom]]s inside the building.  The inquiry was ended without further incident, but the sham factory was soon closed and the monks never returned again.\n\nThe monks built cabins of wood and stone on a small island in the Black River, about one mile (1.6&nbsp;km) downstream from the abbey.  The island (which no longer exists) was known informally as \"Friars Island,\" and the community supported the monks with food, fuel and clothing via a wooden drawbridge.  For 36 years, the monks continued to celebrate Sunday [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] in the deteriorating abbey building.  In 1789, a Henry Lynch of [[Ballycurrin]] cheaply leased {{convert|16|acre|m2}} to the dispossessed monks at the foot of a hill in the [[townland]] of Kilroe, near Headford.  By 1801, only three monks remained, though Mass continued to be said at Kilroe until 1804.  There were still three monks in the community when it was closed in 1832.\n\n=== Abandonment and neglect ===\n\n[[Image:Rossabbey.jpg|300px|thumb|right|The abbey ruins as depicted in [[William Wilde]]'s 1867 book, ''[[Lough Corrib]], Its Shores and Islands''.]]\n\nIn the meantime, the long-abandoned friary continued its descent into ruin.  In 1835, English tourist John Barrow described the abbey as \"a remarkably fine old ruin ... in a disgracefully neglected state.\"  In particular, Barrow was astonished by the large amount of unburied human remains at the site, which included \"moss-grown skulls and human thigh and leg-bones strewed about so plentifully that not a step can be taken without encountering them.\"<ref>Barrow, John. ''A Tour Round Ireland, Through the Sea-coast Counties, in the Autumn of 1835.'' London. John Murray, Albemarle Street. 1836. p.260.</ref> Geographer [[Samuel Lewis (publisher)|Samuel Lewis]] noted the continued decay in 1837, writing that the abbey was \"partially covered in ivy\" and that the roof had collapsed in 1812.  Despite the neglect, Lewis was able to report that \"one of the windows is still perfect.\"<ref>{{cite web  | last = Lewis  | first = Samuel  | authorlink = Samuel Lewis (publisher)  | title = A Topographical Dictionary of Ireland  | publisher = Samuel Lewis  | year = 1837  | url = http://www.libraryireland.com/topog/h.php | accessdate = 24 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[William Wilde]] visited the abbey ruins in July 1866.  Like Barrow, he described \"heaps of skulls and bones\" in the church and claimed that the site had become notorious for its unburied remains.  Wilde noted with dismay that further \"desecration\" was being effected by sheep and cattle, which roamed freely through the ruins.  He also credited a nearby resident, Oliver Burke, with some early efforts to preserve the site by \"removing obstructions from between the [[mullion]]s of the beautiful windows\" and making \"repairs to the tower, thereby rendering it accessible to the top.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Lough Corrib, its shores and islands: with notices of Lough Mask |last=Wilde |first=William |authorlink=William Wilde |year=1867 |publisher=M.H. Gill |location=Dublin |pages=118\u20139 }}</ref> In 1868, Burke, a [[barrister]] by profession, wrote his own account of the friary's history.\n\n=== Today ===\n\nToday, the ruin of Ross Errilly is maintained by the [[Office of Public Works]] and is open to the public free of charge. It has been used as a filming location for ''[[Bad Karma (2002 film)|Bad Karma]]'', The Suicide Club, Moving Target & series Reign.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [[List of abbeys and priories in Ireland#County Galway|List of abbeys and priories in Ireland (County Galway)]]\n* [[Headford]]\n* [[Soraca Jonin]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Citation | last = Mooney  | first = Canice | title = The Friary of Ross: Foundation and Early Years  | journal = Journal of the Galway Archaeological and Historical Society | volume = 29  | pages = 7\u201314 | year = 1960 }}\n* {{Citation | last = Stalley  | first = Roger | title = The End of the Middle Ages: Gothic Survival in Sixteenth-Century Connacht  | journal = The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland | volume = 133  | pages = 5\u201323 | year = 2003 }}\n\n== External links==\n{{more footnotes|article|date=February 2008}}\n\n* [http://franciscans.ie/content/view/74/35/ Ross Abbey] at Irish Franciscans OFM\n* [http://www.irelandoldnews.com/Galway/1909/AUG.html Tuam Herald, Saturday, August 7 1909] at Ireland Old News\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/articles/abbeyrosserrily/ The Irish Ecclesiastical Record, Vol. V, No. I, October 1868] at Library Ireland\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/articles/ShruelDPJ1-33/index.php The Dublin Penny Journal, Volume 1, Number 33, February 9, 1833] at Library Ireland\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/topog/h.php A Topographical Dictionary of Ireland by Samuel Lewis] at Library Ireland\n* [http://www.headford.org/ross.htm History of Ross Abbey] at Headford.ie\n* [http://www.ucc.ie/celt/published/T100005C/index.html The Annals of the Four Masters] at University College Cork\n* [http://www.lawrencetown.com/longago.htm Long Ago in Ireland] at Lawrencetown Village, Co. Galway\n* [https://sketchfab.com/models/70c645a1dcf54e29982c1c5be905bc03 Ross Errilly Friary ] a 3D model of friary on Sketchfab\n\n{{coord|53|28|47.25|N|9|7|53.25|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Franciscan monasteries in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:1351 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Religion in County Galway]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in County Galway]]\n[[Category:Ruins in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Christian monasteries established in the 14th century]]\n[[Category:National Monuments in County Galway]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinal years:pic", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ross_Errilly_Friary"}
{"title_page": "Hasan R\u0131za Pasha", "text_new": "{{Ottoman Turkish name|H\u00fcseyin R\u0131za|Pasha}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Hasan R\u0131za \n| honorific_suffix  = Pasha\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = Hasan Riza Pasha.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = Hasan R\u0131za Pasha\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 1871\n| death_date    = 30 January 1913\n| birth_place   = [[Baghdad]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_place   = [[Shkod\u00ebr]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| placeofburial = [[Parruc\u00eb Mosque]], [[Shkod\u00ebr]] \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| rank          = [[Birindji ferik|General]]\n| servicenumber = \n| battles       = [[Siege of Scutari (1912\u20131913)|Siege of Shkod\u00ebr]]\n| battles_label = \n| relations     = [[Mehmed Nam\u0131k Pasha]] (father)\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = \n<!--Military service-->\n| allegiance          = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}}\n| branch              = {{army|Ottoman Empire}}\n| serviceyears        = \n| unit                = \n| commands            = \n| awards              = \n}}\n'''Hasan R\u0131za Pasha''' (1871 &ndash; 30 January 1913), was a general in the [[Military of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Army]].\n\n==Life==\nThe son of the distinguished Ottoman statesman [[Mehmed Nam\u0131k Pasha]], who was the Governor of [[Baghdad]] where Hasan Riza was born. He was of Turkish origin, as Mehmed Nam\u0131k's grandfather migrated from [[Konya]] to [[Constantinople]]. He entered the [[Ottoman Military Academy]] in 1892 and graduated on March 13, 1895. He continued his studies in [[German Empire|Germany]] (1899\u20131900). After serving in Iraq (1901\u2013-1911) he was promoted to the rank of ''General'' and assigned as [[W\u0101li|wali]] of [[Shkod\u00ebr]].<ref name=\"Elsie\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgf6GWJxuZgC&pg=PA192 |page=192|author=[[Robert Elsie]]|title=A Biographical Dictionary of Albanian History| publisher=I. B. Tauris|isbn=978-1780764313|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was the main commander during the [[Siege of Scutari (1912\u20131913)|Siege of Shkod\u00ebr]] and became the symbol of resistance against the [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbian]] and [[Kingdom of Montenegro|Montenegrin]] invasion. He did his utmost to defend the town and its fortress that were under siege by Montenegrin and Serbian forces for seven months, stating ''\"Shkodra is our fate or our grave, but not our shame\"''.<ref name=\"Elsie\"/> However, in the midst of the siege, Hasan Riza Pasha was assassinated by agents of [[Essad Pasha Toptani|Essad Pasha]]. \n\nEdith Durham wrote that after Hasan Riza had supper with Essad, he was shot dead a few yards away from the house by two men disguised as women. Osman Bali and Mehmed Kavaja<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IzI0uOZ2j6gC&pg=PA72 |title=The Albanians: A Modern History |last=Vickers |first=Door Miranda |year=1999}}</ref>, both servants of [[Essad Pasha Toptani|Essad Pasha]]<ref name=\"HRP\">{{cite book|title=Hasan Riza Pasha: Mbrojt\u00ebs i Shkodr\u00ebs n\u00eb Luft\u00ebn Ballkanike, 1912-1913|last=Ulli|first=Prenk|coauthors=|year=1995|publisher=Albin|location=[[Shkod\u00ebr]], [[Albania]]|pages=34\u201340|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ccUzHAAACAAJ&dq=Hasan+Riza+Pasha&hl=en&ei=lx32TfXBGomZOuzuiLYH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA|accessdate=2011-06-13}}</ref>, boasted afterwards that they had done the deed. The town crier proclaimed that nothing was to be said about the murder, and Essad now took command.\n\nRiza Pasha wanted to keep up the defense of the besieged city but Essad Pasha wanted to continue his secret negotiations with Montenegro, which were done through the counsel of Russia in Shkodra. Essad Pasha's plan was to hand over Shkodra to the Serbs and Montenegrins as the price for their support in his attempt to proclaim himself King of Albania. Essad Pasha handed Shkodra over to [[Janko Vukoti\u0107|General Vukoti\u0107]]. \n\n==Legacy==\nHasan Riza Pasha is well remembered in Shkod\u00ebr. He was buried at [[Parruc\u00eb Mosque]].\n\nA Turkish-Albanian college in Shkod\u00ebr bears his name. He got decorated for \"First Class Bravery\" ({{lang-sq| \"Trim\u00ebri e Klasit t\u00eb Par\u00eb}}) in August 1996, by [[President of Albania|Albanian President]] [[Sali Berisha]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.lajmeshqip.com/kultura/shkodra-perkujtoi-hasan-riza-pashen| language=Albanian|title=Shkodra p\u00ebrkujtoi Hasan Riza Pash\u00ebn |trans-title=Shkodra commemorates Hasan Riza Pasha| accessdate=2014-12-06|date=2011-03-18| publisher=lajmeshqip.com}}</ref> and a monument was erected in his honor in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Panorama|title=Hakmarrja: Dhunohet monumenti i Hasan Riza Pashes|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/hakmarrja-dhunohet-monumenti-i-hasan-riza-pashes/|accessdate=16 October 2017|date=July 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hasan Riza Pasha monument in Shkod\u00ebr.JPG|thumb|right|Monument dedicated to Hasan Riza Pasha in [[Shkod\u00ebr]]]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hasan Riza}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Baghdad]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Army generals]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Military College alumni]]\n[[Category:Ottoman military personnel of the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Assassinated people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Albania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Ottoman Turkish name|H\u00fcseyin R\u0131za|Pasha}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Hasan R\u0131za \n| honorific_suffix  = Pasha\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = Hasan Riza Pasha.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = Hasan R\u0131za Pasha\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 1871\n| death_date    = 30 January 1913\n| birth_place   = [[Baghdad]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_place   = [[Shkod\u00ebr]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| placeofburial = [[Parruc\u00eb Mosque]], [[Shkod\u00ebr]] \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| rank          = [[Birindji ferik|General]]\n| servicenumber = \n| battles       = [[Siege of Scutari (1912\u20131913)|Siege of Shkod\u00ebr]]\n| battles_label = \n| relations     = [[Mehmed Nam\u0131k Pasha]] (father)\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = \n<!--Military service-->\n| allegiance          = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}}\n| branch              = {{army|Ottoman Empire}}\n| serviceyears        = \n| unit                = \n| commands            = \n| awards              = \n}}\n'''Hasan R\u0131za Pasha''' (1871 &ndash; 30 January 1913), was a general in the [[Military of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Army]].\n\n==Life==\nThe son of the distinguished Ottoman statesman [[Mehmed Nam\u0131k Pasha]], who was the Governor of [[Baghdad]] where Hasan Riza was born. He was of Turkish origin, as Mehmed Nam\u0131k's grandfather migrated from [[Konya]] to [[Constantinople]]. He entered the [[Ottoman Military Academy]] in 1892 and graduated on March 13, 1895. He continued his studies in [[German Empire|Germany]] (1899\u20131900). After serving in Iraq (1901\u2013-1911) he was promoted to the rank of ''General'' and assigned as [[W\u0101li|wali]] of [[Shkod\u00ebr]].<ref name=\"Elsie\">{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgf6GWJxuZgC&pg=PA192 |page=192|author=[[Robert Elsie]]|title=A Biographical Dictionary of Albanian History| publisher=I. B. Tauris|isbn=978-1780764313|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was the main commander during the [[Siege of Scutari (1912\u20131913)|Siege of Shkod\u00ebr]] and became the symbol of resistance against the [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbian]] and [[Kingdom of Montenegro|Montenegrin]] invasion. He did his utmost to defend the town and its fortress that were under siege by Montenegrin and Serbian forces for seven months, stating ''\"Shkodra is our fate or our grave, but not our shame\"''.<ref name=\"Elsie\"/> However, in the midst of the siege, Hasan Riza Pasha was assassinated by agents of [[Essad Pasha Toptani|Essad Pasha]]. \n\nEdith Durham wrote that after Hasan Riza had supper with Essad, he was shot dead a few yards away from the house by two men disguised as women. Osman Bali and Mehmed Kavaja<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IzI0uOZ2j6gC&pg=PA72 |title=The Albanians: A Modern History |last=Vickers |first=Door Miranda |year=1999}}</ref>, both servants of [[Essad Pasha Toptani|Essad Pasha]]<ref name=\"HRP\">{{cite book|title=Hasan Riza Pasha: Mbrojt\u00ebs i Shkodr\u00ebs n\u00eb Luft\u00ebn Ballkanike, 1912-1913|last=Ulli|first=Prenk|coauthors=|year=1995|publisher=Albin|location=[[Shkod\u00ebr]], [[Albania]]|pages=34\u201340|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ccUzHAAACAAJ&dq=Hasan+Riza+Pasha&hl=en&ei=lx32TfXBGomZOuzuiLYH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA|accessdate=2011-06-13}}</ref>, boasted afterwards that they had done the deed. The town crier proclaimed that nothing was to be said about the murder, and Essad now took command.\n\nRiza Pasha wanted to keep up the defense of the besieged city but Essad Pasha wanted to continue his secret negotiations with Montenegro, which were done through the counsel of Russia in Shkodra. Essad Pasha's plan was to hand over Shkodra to the Serbs and Montenegrins as the price for their support in his attempt to proclaim himself King of Albania. Essad Pasha handed Shkodra over to [[Janko Vukoti\u0107|General Vukoti\u0107]]. \n\n==Legacy==\nHasan Riza Pasha is well remembered in Shkod\u00ebr. He was burried at [[Parruc\u00eb Mosque]].\n\nA Turkish-Albanian college in Shkod\u00ebr bears his name. He got decorated for \"First Class Bravery\" ({{lang-sq| \"Trim\u00ebri e Klasit t\u00eb Par\u00eb}}) in August 1996, by [[President of Albania|Albanian President]] [[Sali Berisha]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.lajmeshqip.com/kultura/shkodra-perkujtoi-hasan-riza-pashen| language=Albanian|title=Shkodra p\u00ebrkujtoi Hasan Riza Pash\u00ebn |trans-title=Shkodra commemorates Hasan Riza Pasha| accessdate=2014-12-06|date=2011-03-18| publisher=lajmeshqip.com}}</ref> and a monument was erected in his honor in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Panorama|title=Hakmarrja: Dhunohet monumenti i Hasan Riza Pashes|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/hakmarrja-dhunohet-monumenti-i-hasan-riza-pashes/|accessdate=16 October 2017|date=July 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hasan Riza Pasha monument in Shkod\u00ebr.JPG|thumb|right|Monument dedicated to Hasan Riza Pasha in [[Shkod\u00ebr]]]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hasan Riza}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Baghdad]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Army generals]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Ottoman Military College alumni]]\n[[Category:Ottoman military personnel of the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:Assassinated people of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Albania]]\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hasan_R%C4%B1za_Pasha"}
